<HEADLINE>A very public break-up: a marriage dissolves before record TV audiences</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ron McKenna, Calum Macdonald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Though divorce will not be an issue for the churches, remarriage certainly
would be, report Ron McKenna and Calum Macdonald
THE Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr George Carey, was consulted before the letters
from the Queen were sent and agreed with their contents, church sources said.
Earlier, a Church of England spokesman, the Rev Eric Shegog, said that from the
church's point of view, a divorce would be no bar to Charles becoming king.
The Archdeacon of York said a royal divorce would not be an issue for the
church, but a remarriage would.
The Venerable George Austin told BBC2's Newsnight: ``There comes a time, sad
and painful as it is, that a marriage has to be recognised as dead, and after
the shenanigans and tantrums of the past few weeks, it has been very publicly
obvious that it does seem to have died.''
He added: ``Certainly for many people who hold to a traditional view of
marriage and its sanctity, remarriage would cause problems.''
The reaction from politicians and church leaders in Scotland was sympathetic.
The Very Rev Dr James Weatherhead, principal clerk to the General Assembly of
the Church of Scotland and former Moderator, said it was ``not surprising''.
``I don't know that there is any strong comment that I can make. I don't think
there are any distinct consequences for the church.''
Dr Weatherhead said that the monarch although a member of the Church of
Scotland was not, unlike the English position, the surpeme ruler.
``The convention is that when the monarch comes to Scotland she is a member of
the Church of Scotland. It is normal for the Queen when she comes to attend the
Church of Scotland that she takes communion there.''
He also said that divorce had long been recognised by the church under certain
circumstances.
``I think the church as a whole will sympathise with all involved. Any divorce
is a breakdown of human relationships. That is something that makes people sad.
It is the kind of a predicament where things have gone wrong. It is not a
judgment thing,'' he added.
Father Tom Connelly, a spokesman for the Roman Catholic Church in Scotland,
said: ``Naturally, it is always very sad if a marriage breaks down.
``We do recognise that if the breakdown is irretrievable, then it is very often
better for the children if the parents separate, but of course we don't accept
you can get remarried if you divorce.''
Scotland's political leaders emphasised that there were no constitutional
implications. Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said: ``On a human
level, it seems sadly inevitable, but I don't think it has any constitutional
ramifications at all.''
Scottish Conservative Party chairman Sir Michael Hirst said: ``It is always
extremely sad when a marriage ends. I think the best thing we could all do is
leave them to sort it out for themselves away from the glare of publicity and
in the interest of themselves and their children.''
Sir Michael was reluctant to comment on the impact of the Panorama interview
but added: ``I think the current situation is clearly unsatisfactory and a
strain on everybody. I am very sad for them.......for them all.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond commented: ``If the marriage is finished, and that is
pretty obvious, then the best thing is divorce. I'm sort of doubtful if you
should divorce by royal consent. The decision is for them and not anyone else.''
</TEXT>
