<HEADLINE>In search of a place not too far from centre of attention</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE recent high-level talks about the Princess of Wales's future role are
thought likely to run parallel with negotiations about a divorce settlement.
The Panorama interview is being viewed by many as a deliberate move by the
princess to enable her to demand more favourable terms by indicating her
determination to stand her own ground.
Her first priority will be to be given unlimited access to her sons.
With Prince William in direct line of succession to the throne, that should
ensure her a place never too far from the centre of public attention for the
rest of her life.
But financial security, leaving her free to maintain a lifestyle free from the
demeaning need to beg favours from the rich and famous around the world, is
also very important to the princess.
She is thought likely to insist on a home of her own, although she might prefer
to maintain a base within the recognised royal family environment, such as her
present Kensington Palace home.
Staff, transport, and protection would also be needed to allow her to continue
the public duties she clearly wishes to carry out.
The now infamous TV interview, when the Princess of Wales admitted adultery,
was clearly the deciding factor in influencing the Queen to urge Prince Charles
and his estranged wife to divorce.
After the November 20 Panorama bombshell, in which the princess called royal
officials ``the enemy'' and questioned the prince's suitability to be King,
nothing would again be the same.
This seemed clear when Diana apparently could not face spending Christmas with
the Royal Family at Sandringham and turned down the Queen's invitation.
Charles had already set the pattern by appearing last year on a prime-time TV
documentary when he too confessed to infidelity.
The Jonathan Dimbleby television scoop was followed up with an authoratative
book in which more private thoughts were aired in public.
The couple's unhappy marriage may have been doomed to fail.
The princess told BBC1's Panorama of the strains placed on her marriage by the
prince's relationship with Camilla Parker Bowles. There were three people in
her marriage, Diana complained.
The royal couple had struggled in vain to keep some sort of unity but, perhaps
inevitably, they decided to separate three years ago.
Since then, there has been been an uneasy truce.
The couple have appeared together in public, albeit rarely, and usually with
Prince William and Prince Harry, at state occasions such as the summer's VE and
VJ-Day commemorations.
But those close to the royals knew that Charles and Diana just did not get on.
At times they managed to disguise their dislike for each other, perhaps for the
sake of the children.
In truth, however, there was never any chance of a reconciliation.
The princess told the nation, and the world, on Panorama that, despite her
affair with ex-cavalry officer James Hewitt, she did not want a divorce.
The prince, since receiving his mother's dramatic letter, has now made it known
to the princess that he shares the Queen's view that an early divorce is
desirable.
Divorce is a matter for the husband and wife. But clearly the Queen could not
stand by and watch the couple's very public marriage break-up inflict damage to
the very institution of monarchy.
Neither Charles nor Diana wanted to be seen to make the first move to divorce.
Now the Queen has done it for them.
And, although no-one was speaking for the princess last night, it seems divorce
proceedings will start early in the new year, if not sooner.
</TEXT>
