<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Abandoning pretence of family gathering</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782467</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A STRONG sign of major changes within the royal household came on Monday with
the announcement that the Princess of Wales would not be spending Christmas Day
with her sons and the rest of the royal family at Sandringham.
The about-turn, taken as a clear indicator of worsening relations between
estranged Diana and her royal in-laws, was announced as the Prince of Wales and
Camilla Parker Bowles were riding on the same hunt.
As both households were by then aware of the content of the Queen's letter, it
may have been decided to abandon any pretence of a close family gathering in
that the knowledge the divorce stance would become public.
Prince Charles and Mrs Parker Bowles were careful not to be seen together as
they joined around 100 other riders on the Duke of Beaufort's Hunt near
Highgrove House. Mrs Parker Bowles stayed with the hunt for about two hours,
leaving half an hour before the prince's arrival.
Of the princess's decision to have Christmas alone, Buckingham Palace said she
had made ``private, alternative plans.'' Prince William and Prince Harry would
be joining other members of the royal family, the palace added.
</TEXT>
