<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BCCI ruling paves way for council settlement of #4.8m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Western Isles Council last night welcomed the news that compensation may
finally be paid to the creditors of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce
International. It could mean the council receiving almost #5m in the spring.
A Luxembourg Court yesterday accepted the withdrawal of a motion by former BCCI
employees appealing against their settlement. This left the way clear for the
compensation package already agreed by BCCI's biggest shareholder, the Abu
Dhabi Government, being paid.
The move has already been approved by courts in England and the Cayman Islands.
The settlement means, in effect, that between 25,000 and 28,000 verified
claimants will get a first dividend of 20% of their claim. In the case of the
islands council, which lost #24m, this would be #4.8m.
Vice-convener Angus Graham said: ``We have had so many final hurdles, but this
looks more definite and I think we can expect the payment in April or May.
``If we get our 20% it will make quite a difference to the council and would
mean us saving #400,000 a year in loan charges, so we certainly welcome the
news.''
</TEXT>
