<DOCNO>GH951221-000004</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000004</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pact on steel clears way for summit in Dublin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR Major and his Irish counterpart, John Bruton, plan to give the Northern
Ireland peace process a joint boost by staging a summit meeting in Dublin today.
Their talks got an eleventh-hour go-ahead last night after the settlement of an
unrelated London-Dublin row in Brussels.
Britain's determination to veto a European Union plan to back with cash the
#30m takeover of the troubled, state-backed Irish Steel company by an Indian
buyer had threatened to sour inter-government relations to an extent that a
peace summit would not have been worthwhile.
Failure of the takeover would mean the loss of almost 400 jobs at an Irish
Steel plant in Cobh, near Cork.
But British Steel said it was ``very disappointed with the outcome of the
negotiations''.
``British Steel holds to its belief that the use of Article 95 of the Treaty of
Paris to approve individual subsidy cases is illegal,'' it said.
``The company will, therefore, be challenging the decision in the European
Court of Justice and will also request the court to ensure that the purchaser
repays any illegal aid.''
The British Iron and Steel Producers' Association said: ``The British
Government has wasted the opportunity to assert the rule of law and set down an
important precedent for the future.
``The deal reached today fails in any real sense to curtail Irish Steel's
future output and the UK steel producers deplore this compromise. The UK steel
industry will be pursuing this through the European Courts.''
Weeks of negotiations between senior officials from the two governments failed
to break the deadlock in        the peace talks, and yes-       terday
afternoon the two prime ministers were in telephone contact about the affair.
However, soon after the start of a crucial EU ministerial session in Brussels,
sources on both sides confirmed they had settled their differences.
That permitted the activation of plans for Mr Major to head south to meet Mr
Bruton, late this afternoon, after a series of engagements in Northern Ireland.
Mr Major, accompanied by his wife, Norma, will be a dinner guest of Mr Bruton's
tonight before flying home tomorrow morning.
Dublin sources said the aim of the summit would be to maintain the dynamic of
the momentum created by the joint communique on the agreement they struck at
their last meeting in Downing Street.
</TEXT>
