<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Life sentence for husband who suffocated his wife then faked robbery and grief The tears of a conman</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GORDON Wardell, the ``grieving'' husband who shed tears for his murdered wife
on television as part of an elaborate plot to hoodwink police, began a life
sentence for her murder yesterday.
Wardell was described by Mr Justice Cresswell as an ``extremely dangerous,
evil, and devious man'' after a jury at Oxford Crown Court unanimously
convicted him of murdering his wife Carol, 39, a Woolwich Building Society
manageress, in September last year.
Wardell, 42, of Meriden, Warwickshire, had tried to outsmart detectives by
claiming that he and his wife were the victims of a ``terrible robbery that
went wrong''.
Shortly after the killing he faced the TV cameras at a police news conference
appealing for help in tracing the murderer. He kept up the charade of
distraught widower at Mrs Wardell's funeral.
After the jury delivered its verdict, the court heard that Wardell had already
spent time behind bars for an attack on a woman.
As a 17-year-old schoolboy he was jailed for four years after luring a
teacher's wife into woods, indecently assaulting her and stabbing her in the
neck.
Passing sentence, Mr Cresswell said: ``You killed your wife in a brutal manner
and then cynically attempted to escape detection by going to elaborate lengths
to make it appear that your crime was the work of a gang of robbers.
``This was an outrage to your wife, her family, and to everybody who knew her.''
As the verdict was announced there were gasps of ``yes!'' from the public
gallery and Mrs Wardell's 67-year-old mother, Joan Heslop, broke down in tears
of relief.
Wardell showed little emotion, shaking his head slowly as the foreman read the
verdict.
Wardell, an executive for a car parts company, earning #27,000 a year, told
police an elaborate story of how the supposed killers of his wife knocked him
out with drugs when he arrived home from a quiet Sunday evening pint on
September 11 last year.
After beating himself to make the raid look believable, Wardell gagged himself
with a ripped sheet from his garage and tied his hands and legs to a rubbish
bin stand before telling how the raiders took his wife.
After leaving hospital in a wheelchair and wearing tinted glasses, a frail
Wardell, who lost two-stone in weight in the weeks after his wife's death,
faced the media to broadcast his tale of the scene of terror which greeted him
upon his return home.
After the sentence, Mrs Heslop said she would like to see Wardell hanged for
what he did to her daughter. ``He should be dead,'' she said.
Mrs Heslop said that Wardell had stayed with her for three weeks after the
killing and it was not until the day after the funeral that she first suspected
her son-in-law.
``It was just a mother's feeling, I suppose,'' she said.
Wardell's painstaking efforts to cover his tracks after suffocating his wife
began when he drove to the building society branch she managed in Nuneaton,
tapped into her security codes and looted the safe of #14,000.
He planted one of Mrs Wardell's sandals in the office then dumped her body in a
lay-by.
Wardell returned home and bound and gagged himself in the living room as if
trussed up by the fictitious gang.
After he was found by police he claimed that the last time he saw his wife was
the previous evening as she was being held at knifepoint on their sofa by a man
in a clown's mask.
In his subsequent television appearance Wardell choked back tears as he told
how he had ``lost everything'' and appealed for help in the hunt for his wife's
``totally evil'' killer.
Describing the conviction as ``wonderful, absolutely wonderful'' Mrs Heslop
added: ``A light has gone out of our lives never to return. But justice has
been done. Carol will be able to rest in peace now.
``She loved life and was full of life. To have it taken away tragically in such
a way was terrible.''
Mrs Heslop said that she knew nothing of Wardell's previous conviction until
his arrest, but could not say if Mrs Wardell knew about her husband's criminal
history.
She added that she was ``absolutely disgusted'' by Wardell's phoney display of
grief as he carried out his plot to deceive detectives.
Mrs Wardell's brother, Tony Heslop, 46, described the verdict as ``brilliant,
great, perfect''.
His sister, Susan Field, 42, said: ``Carol kept us together because the family
meant everything to her.''
Detective Superintendent Tony Bayliss, who led the Warwickshire police
investigation described Wardell as ``cool, cold, calculating'' and a
``dangerous, evil man''.
His motive for murder had not been fully established but was believed to be
``domestically orientated''.
Mr Bayliss said that his suspicions were aroused when there was no response
from the public or from ``our sources of help'' to police appeals, despite a
large reward being offered.
Police were also suspicious about aspects the the crime.
If the motive had been cash why had the gang chosen such a rural building
society branch? Why had they only taken about #14,000 from the safe and left
the automated cash machine untouched along with credit cards in the safe?
Why did pathologists find that the five-man gang had not tried to rip off Mrs
Wardell's gold rings and chain or make off with cash and thousands of pounds
worth of cameras, televisions, and spirits from their home?
Closer examination of what had happened at the Woolwich also raised questions.
Mrs Wardell used a personalised security code to gain access to the staff areas
of the branch and she had been trained that in the case of any raid she should
use what was know as the ``duress code''.
By tapping in that number she would have sent a silent alarm to security and
alerted them to the raid without tipping off the gang.
Wardell expected police to believe that his wife, praised by colleagues for her
commitment to her work, would not have tried to get help when the branch was
robbed.
Asked about Wardell's elaborate plot, Mr Bayliss said: ``I don't think he was
an actor. He was a person you could not get beneath the skin. Very cold.''
Asked why his criminal history did not arouse immediate suspicion, the
detective said: ``Just because someone has a previous conviction it does not
automatically make them a suspect in a murder case.''
Mr Bayliss said that Wardell's possible involvement in other outstanding crimes
in the Midlands was ``a matter we will deal with in due course'', adding that
other forces ``may want to speak to us in the light of today's events''.
He believed that the key evidence was from an anaesthetist who rejected
Wardell's claims that he was unconscious for many hours as a result of being
``drugged'' by his invented assailants.
Mr Bill Clegg, QC, defending Wardell, said afterwards that the possibility of
an appeal would be ``under consideration''.
</TEXT>
