<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man who almost killed before</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GORDON Wardell was not a newcomer to apparently motiveless attacks on innocent
women.
Wardell, 42, a 6ft 3ins keep-fit fanatic, had almost killed before, but
neighbours and friends in the Warwickshire village of Meriden where he and his
wife Carol lived a seemingly idyllic life, were unaware of his violent past.
The young Wardell, a bespectacled promising A-level student at the Woodlands
comprehensive school in Coventry, lured his science master's wife to a wood
before launching a terrifying attack on the woman in front of her two young
sons in 1970.
The 17-year-old youth, who had never had a girlfriend, told 32-year-old science
master's wife Brenda Hayes that he had found a rare plant her absent husband
had been looking for.
He then rode his bike to the spot and waited for the woman to arrive before
ambushing her at knifepoint, tying her hands behind her back and sticking
plaster over her mouth.
The teenager, who, a court heard, had a fantasy that he was Hollywood film star
Paul Newman, then squirted de-icer in her face and indecently assaulted her
before stabbing her in the neck twice.
Mrs Hayes needed nine pints of blood to recover from the attack and Wardell was
jailed for four years after being found guilty of grievous bodily harm when the
prosecution dropped a charge of attempted murder.
Wardell told police at the time: ``I was fed up and it was just a reaction - I
don't know what to or what for.''
</TEXT>
