<DOCNO>GH951221-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland set for deep freeze</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND shivered yesterday as weathermen predicted that temperatures are set
to drop even further before Christmas.
Shetland had a foretaste of what might be in store for the rest of the country
when blizzards blocked almost 600 miles of roads and closed airports after the
islands' worst snow in 11 years.
At the Rothiemurchus Estate, near Aviemore, Scott Hosie, 25, went fishing
Eskimo-style through a hole in the ice.
The coldest night of the winter so far sent the mercury down to -8 degrees and
brought snowploughs and gritters out across the North of Scotland. The A96
Lecht road from Tomintoul to Cockbridge was closed overnight.
Mr Ian Symon, of Castle Douglas-based Weather Watchers, yesterday predicted
heavy snow falls before Christmas over most of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Endless stream of allegations buried in the mists of time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE allegations that led to the ruling Labour group being described as the
Monklands Mafia have been around so long that they seem buried in the mists of
time.
In fact it was in August, 1992, that The Herald revealed deep divisions within
the Lanarkshire towns of Airdrie and Coatbridge over the way the Monklands
council was being run by its Labour leaders.
Conservative politicians began to take an interest, and ever since the stream
of allegations has been endless.
The concerted campaign led by an English MP can be put down partly to attempts
to embarrass the late Labour Party leader John Smith and then Shadow Scottish
Secretary Tom Clarke in their very own heartland.
In addition, Monklands offered a golden opportunity to transfer the Tory sleaze
label to Labour.
But what helped the allegations linger so long were protests by Labour
councillors. Four resigned as vice-conveners for numerous reasons - including
that nearly all convenerships went to Coatbridge councillors.
They also believed that for many years Catholic councillors from Coatbridge had
been biased against the mainly Protestant town of Airdrie.
The quartet were suspended at various times for breaches of local party
discipline.
An internal inquiry by the Scottish Labour Party executive in October, 1992,
issued six months later, said all claims regarding irregularities should be
passed to the Government, the Accounts Commission, and the police.
Overall, the complaints of religious bigotry and a spending bias in favour of
Coatbridge were ``dynamite'' which exploded when combined with allegations of
``jobs for the boys''.
These included the seemingly bizarre claim of personal patronage in hiring
staff. A two-tier application system was confirmed in which people applying
from the local Jobcentre were given pink forms and people who knew councillors
were given ``higher priority'' green forms.
However, an inquiry ordered by the Scottish Office into Monklands District
Council's employment practices yesterday concluded that the local authority did
not fail to comply with requirements.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth said later of the conclusions by Mr William
Nimmo Smith, QC: ``No further action is therefore required by me.''
The inquiry came after the allegations of nepotism among senior councillors
refused to go away even after the council had commissioned its own inquiry,
chaired by Professor Robert Black.
Arguably, Professor Black's report, published in June, merely muddied the
waters by doing little more than record on paper all the allegations.
The report indirectly led to then Scottish Secretary Ian Lang ordering a public
inquiry into staff appointments, something he had long resisted because most of
the allegations were unsubstantiated.
Despite Dover MP David Shaw's repeated baiting in the House of Commons, Labour
MPs John Smith and Tom Clarke refused to become embroiled in the controversy.
However, Mr Clarke issued a statement yesterday welcoming the findings, while
Mr Shaw pledged to fight on despite being castigated by the Government inquiry
for an ``irresponsible'' attitude in evidence.
Mr Smith's successor, Mrs Helen Liddell, confronted the allegations head-on
during last year's Monklands East by-election. She faced an SNP candidate, Kay
Ullrich, who had claimed only a Nationalist victory would make Labour clean up
its act and ``restore and revitalise the reputation of Monklands''.
Only time will tell if Mr Nimmo Smith's findings will do just that. Ironically,
the Monklands name will be wiped off the political map with local government
reorganisation in April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots director may face extradition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SECOND director of an Edinburgh-based company at the centre of claims over
alleged violations of the US embargo against Libya may face extradition
proceedings.
The US customs service was last night reported to be considering seeking the
extradition of a director at McNeil International.
No-one was available for comment at the firm's West End offices.
Company director David McKeeve, 36, from Glasgow, appeared in court in Boston
on Tuesday charged with breaching the US embargo by attempting to export more
than #250,000 of computing equipment.
He and McNeil International are accused of submitting false information to
shipping agents and the US customs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nursery alert after suspected meningitis case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YOUNG boy is recovering     in a Glasgow hospital from         a suspected
case of menin-gitis.
The three-year-old child, who has not been named, is a pupil at Fortrose
Nursery School, Peel Street, Glasgow. Parents of 36 other children who attend
the same morning sessions at the nursery, and four members of staff, were
yesterday given courses of antibiotics.
The parents of 30 other children who take part in afternoon sessions at the
nursery have been advised of the situation. They have been told to seek
immediate medical help if their children show symptoms of the disease or become
ill in any way.
The boy was taken to Yorkhill Hospital for Sick Children on Monday with
suspected meningococcal meningitis, a bacterial form of the brain infection.
The disease causes inflammation of the brain and can be life-threatening.
A hospital spokesman said the child had initially been taken to intensive care,
but was now being cared for in a general ward. ``His condition is more settled
and he seems brighter,'' he said.
Dr Rob Brogan, a consultant in public health medicine with Greater Glasgow
Health Board, said: ``There is minimal risk to other children because of the
steps we have taken.
``The boy is doing well, he is responding to treatment. If we get the disease
early with antibiotics, the chances are excellent. We would expect the child to
make a full recovery.''
Dr Brogan said it was thought that the boy had picked up the bug in the past
seven days, by coming into close contact with a carrier, someone among the 10%
of the population who carry the bug naturally in the back of their throats.
The antibiotics were aimed at wiping out the infection in the carrier, and
therefore helping to prevent other people picking up the disease.
Dr Brogan added: ``At this time of year especially, there is quite a number of
people who carry it in the back of their throats and it doesn't do them any
harm, they have a natural immunity to it.
``This is just one isolated case. We get a lot of sporadic cases at this time
of year and we take these steps to stop it developing into an outbreak.''
Symptoms of meningitis include fever, drowsiness, sensitivity to light,
headache, neck stiffness, and a body rash.
q.A twelve-month-old boy is detained in the Borders General Hospital also
suffering from meningococal meningitis. Earlier this month two women were
treated at the same hospital for the virus.
</TEXT>
