<HEADLINE>Buy-out teams secure deals to run two more rail lines</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAIL privatisation passed another milestone yesterday with the announcement of
two more passenger franchises, for Great Western Trains and LTS, going to
management-employee buy-out teams.
Together with Tuesday's announcement that Perth-based bus operator Stagecoach
is to run South West Trains out of London Waterloo, this completes the first
tranche of franchises. Contracts for the second tranche, which includes Inter
City East Coast, are due to be let in the spring.
GWT, which operates out of London Paddington, and LTS, which serves Tilbury and
Southend in Essex from London Fenchurch Street, have won contracts of 10 and 15
years respectively, subject to investment plans being cleared with the rail
franchising director.
``New services, new rolling stock, less cost,'' was the jubiliant declaration
from Transport Secretary Sir George Young as he welcomed the deals as
``excellent news for passengers''.
Less ecstatic was Labour transport spokesman, Brian Wilson MP, who warned that
all three franchises ``will cost the taxpayer far more than they did before BR
was broken up two years ago.
``In 1993/94 neither South West Trains nor Great Western received any subsidy
at all,'' he said.
Mr Wilson predicted that there would be ``very few more franchises let before a
General Election''.
The Great Western franchise goes to Great Western Holdings, with the line's
management and employees owning 51% of the voting shares. It is backed by West
Country-based bus operator FirstBus, venture capitalists 3i and funding from
Intermediate Capital Group and the Royal Bank of Scotland.
LTS Rail is a comparatively small commuter line operating out of London's
Fenchurch Street station, taking in such stations as Barking, Upminster,
Tilbury, Basildon, Southend and Shoeburyness. The LTS franchise has been won by
the buy-out team Enterprise Rail, backed by 3i and Gresham Trust, and the new
company is committed to investment in the franchise and intends to completely
re-equip the business with new trains not later than the year 2002.
Meanwhile, the managing director of ScotRail, Mr John Ellis, has reaffirmed his
commitment to leading a management bid for any future private franchise of the
passenger service.
He added that a privatised ScotRail would introduce new rolling stock on the
Glasgow to Edinburgh line, with existing trains on the line being moved into
service on other routes.
</TEXT>
