<HEADLINE>Rape case PC sentenced to one year for unlawful sex</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLICEMAN who had sex with a 15-year-old solvent abuser on the back seat of
his patrol car after being told to drive her to hospital was sentenced to 12
months yesterday.
The judge told PC Adam Grice-Roberts, 32, he had been guilty of a ``grave
breach of trust'' towards a girl he was supposed to be looking after.
The jury at Preston Crown Court rejected her claims that the officer had raped
her. He pled guilty to unlawful sexual intercourse.
The court had heard the sex took place in his Rover patrol car in the
underground car park of Blackpool Central police station after he had been
called to find the girl collapsed in an alleyway, sniffing butane gas.
The judge told Grice-Roberts: ``You had intercourse with her not only when you
were on duty but when you were supposed to be looking after her.
``It is of the greatest public interest that members of the public should be
able to trust police officers. That trust has been lamentably abused.''
Grice-Roberts claimed the girl had offered him sex and he believed she was 17.
The girl's family criticised the year-long sentence for an offence that carries
a maximum two years.
Her mother said: ``I am totally disgusted. He knew he was going to get the
lightest possible sentence because he is a policeman, a policeman who took
advantage of a girl who should have been in his care.''
The girl was visiting her family from the children's home where she was living
in North Wales when the incident happened.
She gave evidence by a video-link.
The shamed officer resigned from the force during the case, he has lost his
police house and his fiancee, who became engaged to him when his marriage broke
up, has left him.
Grice-Roberts, of Lindle Crescent, Hutton, near Preston, will serve his
sentence segregated from other prisoners, as a convicted police officer and a
sex offender, for his own safety.
His mother said he accepted his actions were very foolish and that he deeply
regretted them.
</TEXT>
