<HEADLINE>Widow of taxi driver wins legal victory on killing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent and CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE widow and family of a taxi driver have won a crucial legal victory in their
damages action against the man charged with murdering him but acquitted by a
jury's not proven verdict.
A judge ruled yesterday that David Anderson had no relevant defence to a claim
by Mrs Margaret Mullan that he was responsible for her husband's death.
Temporary judge Mr Gordon Coutts, QC, decided that any further hearing in the
case at the Court of Session should be restricted to the amount of damages to
be awarded to Mrs Mullan and her three children. They are claiming a total of
#100,000.
Mr Coutts also ruled that there was no justification for an inquiry into the
family's motive in bringing the action.
Mr Anderson, 24, of Nelson Road, Gourock, who claims that the true purpose of
the case is to have him branded as a killer, is expected to appeal yesterday's
decision to three judges.
Mr Mullan, 38, was working as a taxi driver at the time of his death in
February, 1990.
He took an early morning booking to drive Mr Anderson from Gourock to Greenock.
At some point in the journey Mr Anderson produced a hunting knife which
penetrated Mr Mullan's heart and killed him.
In May, 1990, a jury at the High Court in Paisley returned a not proven verdict
against Mr Anderson and the Mullans raised a civil action against him a week
later.
They claimed that by his actions Mr Anderson was responsible for the death of
Mr Mullan by stabbing him or causing a knife to penetrate his chest to a depth
of five inches.
In a written decision issued yesterday, Mr Coutts said that it had been argued
on Mr Anderson's behalf that it was contrary to public policy to allow the
action to go ahead.
Mr Anderson claimed that he had taken out the knife, which he used at work and
normally carried, to show to the taxi driver. He alleged that Mr Anderson left
his seat and the knife went into his chest as the driver kept moving towards
him.
He maintained that contact was entirely accidental.
Mr Coutts said counsel for Mr Anderson had attacked the motivation of the
Mullan family in bringing the case, claiming that they were using the court for
an improper purpose.
It was alleged that the Mullans' true aim was not to recover damages but
effectively to have Mr Anderson declared to have murdered or otherwise
unlawfully killed Mr Mullan.
Mr Coutts said: ``If there is any justification whatsoever for a preliminary
inquiry into the motivation of a pursuer in a case, which I doubt, this is not
such a case.
``The absence of any precedent is in itself a powerful argument against any
such inquiry being proper, but, further, in the present case, which bears to be
simply an action seeking damages, it would seem wholly inappropriate.
``The only reason why some damages might not be recoverable would be if Mr
Anderson was bankrupt and I do not think that the Mullans should be deprived of
establishing their right to damages even if they have difficulty in recovery.''
Mr Anderson was said to be out of work and to have no assets, but the judge
added: ``I see no reason why he should not be required to pay a sum each week.
A wrong has been done to these pursuers and they are entitled to a remedy.''
On the question of Mr Anderson's defence to the action, counsel for the Mullans
argued that the production of a knife capable of causing death in a taxi in a
deserted location on a dark night amounted to negligence.
This is the first case of its kind to reach this stage in a Scottish court. Joe
and Kate Duffy sued Francis Auld in a civil action after the charge of
murdering their daughter Amanda was found not proven, but Mr Auld did not
defend the action and there was no court hearing.
Mrs Mullan was said to feel personally vindicated by the court's decision. Mr
John O'Donnell, a solicitor speaking on her behalf, said she was pleased but
not surprised by the outcome.
He added that Mrs Mullan had never been interested in making Scottish legal
history despite the ground-breaking nature of her legal battle.
</TEXT>
