<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council inquiry clears primary teacher</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TEACHER acquitted last week of assaulting three unruly pupils was yesterday
also cleared by his employers of any professional misconduct.
Thomas McGhee, 40, was told the news at the end of a three-hour disciplinary
hearing at Central Regional Council's headquarters in Stirling. He is a senior
teacher at a primary school in the area.
Although he was not suspended and continued to teach while awaiting the court
case, Mr McGhee said that at times he had found it difficult to cope.
``I'm just relieved the whole thing is over and perhaps I can get back to
teaching the class in a normal situation again.
``I've had enough of court and the legal system for the rest of my life. I did
not have any doubts of the outcome.''
Mr Ken Wimbor, EIS assistant secretary, who accompanied Mr McGhee to the
hearing, said the union's lawyers would be meeting with local authorities in
the new year in the hope of resolving the issue of discipline guidelines.
He insisted that teachers faced a dilemma in disciplining rowdy pupils.
If they did intervene they faced the possibility of appearing in court accused
of assault, then a professional disciplinary hearing. If they turned a blind
eye they could be accused of negligence.
He said: ``I'm obviously concerned that any member has to endure this kind of
pressure for so long.
``The fact that Tom was found not guilty last week and the charges have not
been upheld following a disciplinary hearing are obviously a concern.
``It's not fair to have two procedures and that's one of the matters we'll be
examining with some urgency.''
Councillors on Central's education committee welcomed the news that Mr McGhee
had been cleared.
Conservative Councillor Helen Scott said: ``It seems a little bit unnecessary
to have a disciplinary hearing after the court has made its decision.
``I think it's extremely difficult for teachers when they are faced with
violence in the classroom and I think there's a lack of guidance. I'm sure they
need help in that way.''
Evelyn Boyce, Central's head of school development, who conducted yesterday's
hearing, said: ``Mr McGhee was not sacrificed on the altar of political
correctness or any other altar.
``For many years teachers have not been able to use corporal punishment not
because of political correctness but to create an appropriate environment for
young people, and because there are other means available of disciplining
pupils.''
Mrs Boyce defended holding the disciplinary hearing. ``There are two separate
processes each with their own integrity.
``Our responsibility as employers means we have a duty to ensure our employees
are not involved in any misconduct.
``We're not above the law but we do have separate duties as employers and the
criteria that apply in a court of law are not necessarily the criteria we have
to look at.''
Mrs Boyce said it would be difficult to give clearer guidelines to teachers on
discipline.
She explained: ``It's not always possible to give very specific guidance
because each situation can be unique and different.
``Given that all situations are unique and different it wouldn't be possible to
lay down recommendations as to the minimum level of contact there should be
between teachers and pupils.
``But recommendations have to be that contact should always be at the minimum
level and cannot be excessive in any circumstances.''
Mr McGhee was cleared in court of assaulting three boy pupils. Two boys claimed
he had banged their heads together and the other alleged he had grabbed him by
the face and lifted him off the ground.
Mr McGhee said he had simply given the two a ticking off, and used the crook of
his finger to lift the other boy's chin up so that he could get eye contact.
</TEXT>
