<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vandals attack graveyard</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>News Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VANDALS have desecrated the grave of a woman's daughter, son-in-law and six
grandchildren. A stone angel and photographs were torn from the grave which Mrs
Sarah Stewart, 59, tends at Alness Parish Church, Easter Ross.
Mrs Stewart, of Westford, Alness, lost her daughter and five of her
grandchildren in a car crash in 1991. Also buried at the family memorial are
her daughter's husband and a sixth grandchild. Mrs Stewart is offering a #100
reward to anyone who can help catch the individuals.
Climbers rescued
TWO climbers rescued by an RAF helicopter crew from the Aonach Eagach ridge in
Glencoe were named by police yesterday as Mr Nicholas Carmody, 39, of
Clochaenog, Clwyd, North Wales, and Mr Duncan Gomes, 30, of Uchaff, Mold,
Clwyd. The men were for five hours in freezing conditions.
Oil detector
A TECHNIQUE that will allow pollution officials to detect an oil slick's
``fingerprint'' and track its source will be in use by the end of next year,
said the Government's Marine Pollution Control Unit.
Fake champagne
TRADING standards officers who have seized hundreds of bottles of counterfeit
Celtic FC champagne in raids around Glasgow believe that Rangers fans may also
be drinking similar bottles of fake Rangers champagne.
Farmer fined
FARMER Colin Ferguson, 43, of Leckuary Farm, Kilmichael Glen, near
Lochgilphead, was fined #500 at Lochgilphead yesterday for failing to provide
sufficient food and water for four cows last March.
Flying visit
THE pilot of the British Airways Express flight from Stornoway, Captain Steve
Maric, 36, was given emergency dental treatment on Benbecula in time for his
return flight to Lewis.
Hero honoured
CONSTABLE Paul Menzies, 25, of Grampian police, who plunged into the sea off
Aberdeen in May to rescue a woman psychiatric patient from drowning, was
presented with a Royal Humane Society Award yesterday for his outstanding
bravery.
Artistic loan
THREE paintings by 17th century Dutch artists have been allocated to the Royal
Scottish Academy on permanent loan, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
announced yesterday. They are: A Village Wedding, by Jan Steen; The Castle of
Bentheim from below, by Jacob van Ruisdael; and The Bird Trap, by Nicholas
Berchem.
Housing warning
THE new unitary Dundee City Council faces a housing crisis after the Government
announced nearly #5m of cuts in the its housing allocation, housing convener
Iain Luke warned.
Red-footed
AN ARMED robber, caught because he was wearing bright red shoes, was jailed for
four years yesterday. Paul Murphy, 29, admitted assaulting and robbing two
shopkeepers in Saltcoats. The High Court in Glasgow heard that police
investigating another crime the next day arrested Murphy when they noticed his
shoes.
Dental facts
MANY people do not know that dental treatment is free for those receiving
family credit or income support or those aged under 18, according to a survey
carried out among residents of the Wester Hailes area of Edinburgh by the
Centre for Dental Education at Edinburgh University.
Murder charge
MR Barry Elder, 27, of Carlops Road, Penicuik, appeared in private at Edinburgh
Sheriff Court yesterday, charged with murdering unemployed chef Mr George
Bissett, 40, of White Horse Close, Edinburgh, in the city's Royal Mile last
Saturday. He was remanded in custody.
</TEXT>
