<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The career woman who had time for charity work</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAROL Wardell was a conscientious woman who threw herself into her career after
finding out she could not have the children she longed for.
The Coventry-born bank worker had been promoted rapidly after joining the
Woolwich as a cashier at its Coventry branch 13 years ago. She met her future
husband at a party in Hinckley, Leicestershire.
When they began chatting she found out she had been taught by Wardell's mother
and soon after a romance began to blossom.
His parents were impressed by her devotion to him and hoped she would help
Wardell, who had been in and out of work since leaving prison, settle down.
The couple married on April 17, 1982, at the Holy Trinity church in Coventry.
They moved into the three-bedroomed detached home built on the former Triumph
Bonneville motorcycle factory site in rural Warwickshire.
Her work never interfered with her home life and she was a regular dinner
hostess who kept a meticulously clean household.
Mrs Wardell was described as fun-loving by colleagues who admired her calm
influence in the work place.
Her older brother Tony Heslop, who lives in Rugby, Warwickshire, said at the
time of her death: ``She and Gordon had been trying for a family for years but
she never managed to fall pregnant. It appears she could not have children.''
Oxford Crown Court had heard that Wardell had not had sex with his wife for six
months before her death and the relationship had been suffering because he had
been made redundant and was out of work for a time.
Betty Wardell, 68, paid tribute to her daughter-in-law. ``Carol was Gordon's
whole life. Initially Carol was not very ambitious but it grew over the years.
She worked so hard and took at least two examinations a year.''
Mrs Wardell did charity work in her spare time. She was a founder member of
Share, a Coventry based self-help and relaxation group.
She also gave her free time to a charity for the mentally handicapped.
Mrs Wardell had experience of dealing with an armed raid at her workplace. She
was praised by her employers after facing a gunman who grabbed #180 at her
Nuneaton branch in February 1992.
</TEXT>
