<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Water authority forced to abandon meeting</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MEETING of the new East of Scotland Water Authority was cancelled yesterday
after being disrupted by demonstrators.
A Santa Claus figure burst into the council chambers of Newtown St Boswell's in
the Borders to make his protest about the role of the authority.
Mr Norman Walkins, from Edinburgh, strode through the door, shouting: ``Bah!
Humbug! Don't pay for the fat cats. We are not paying for water boards in
Scotland - you are unelected, and we don't want you.''
Mr Walkins was backed up by 14 people already in place in the public benches.
Banners were unfurled, a whistle was blown, and various chants were made. Dr
Ian Preston, chairman of the authority, called the meeting to a halt.
Some of the protesters carried Scottish Militant Labour badges.
Only two items of business were concluded in the public session. One was that
staff would be fully consulted about the new water authority set-up, with a
``hot line'' established for guidance. The other was that its new headquarters
would be located in Pentland Gate office park on the west side of Edinburgh,
with the intention of moving in before April 1.
The authority had met in private session earlier, and the chairman said after
the interrupted meeting that no decision had been made on the fixing of charges.
</TEXT>
