<HEADLINE>The last straw for the Palace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST year Prince Charles appeared on ITV and admitted being unfaithful to his
wife. Last month the Princess of Wales confessed on BBC to adultery. Last night
the Queen urged that the couple seek an early divorce.
The Queen's no-holds-barred intervention goes way beyond the ``no constraints''
interviews which involved her son and daughter-in-law.
Presumably, the last straw was the princess's private thoughts in her first
solo television interview.
The Panorama broadcast took place almost three years after deep divisions
emerged in what was once seen as a ``fairy-tale'' marriage.
Now the conversations with reporter Martin Bashir, covering every stage of her
life, take on even more importance.
Because, regardless of constitutional questions raised by the Queen's
intervention, the princess cast doubts in front of 15 million viewers on
Charles's suitability to be king.
She even hinted that it might be better if Prince William succeeded the Queen.
In a key passage, she said that being king, or the ``top job as I call it,''
could be ``suffocating'' for Charles.
And, asked if she would accept a divorce - if her husband wished it, she
replied: ``I would obviously discuss it with him, but up to date neither of us
has discussed this subject.'' Asked if it was her wish to divorce, she replied:
``No, it's not my wish.''
The princess was also asked if it was her wish that Prince William should
succeed the Queen, rather than her husband. Her reply: ``My wish is that my
husband finds peace of mind, and from that follows other things, yes.''
</TEXT>
