<HEADLINE>A very public romance: the road to the altar and the beginnings of a family life The way they were . . .</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Roger Williams</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
It started with a kiss: the Prince and Princess of Wales on the balcony of
Buckingham Palace on their wedding day in 1981.
It was hailed as the `wedding of the century', but cracks appeared in the royal
marriage almost from the beginning, reports Roger Williams
THE fairy-tale marriage between the Prince and Princess of Wales started with
the ``wedding of the century'', but soon became a public prison for both
partners trapped in a loveless union.
Cracks appeared in the early 1980s, and after Prince Harry's birth in 1984 the
couple drifted irretrievably apart.
But the split was acknowledged only in December 1992, when their formal
separation was announced.
The last few years have seen a succession of claims about the troubled
marriage, culminating in Andrew Morton's biography of Diana in 1992 and
Charles's authorised biography by Jonathan Dimbleby last year.
The revelations in the books show that the marriage which was sealed with a
kiss on the balcony of Buckingham Palace was difficult from the start and ended
in bitterness.
1981 - In February, after months of speculation, Buckingham Palace announces
the prince's engagement to 19-year-old Lady Diana Spencer. The couple marry on
July 29 at St Paul's Cathedral.
1982 - Prince William is born in June. Charles, away from the public gaze while
Diana basks in public affection, resents her skill at enchanting ordinary
people.
Their interests take them in different directions, and Diana has little time
for Charles's philosophic wanderings.
1984 - Prince Harry is born in September.
1987 - A rift in the marriage becomes increasingly obvious, prompting furious
media speculation about a possible split. The prince spends more than a month
at Balmoral, apart from his wife and family.
1991 - Relations are said to be so cool between Charles and Diana that they are
reported to have separate rooms during a State visit to Czechoslovakia.
By their 10th wedding anniversary, the relationship has died altogether. They
have separate holidays, separate friends, separate and rival households, and
almost, but not quite, separate homes.
But they still portray a semblance of unity in front of the cameras and in the
eyes of the public.
1992 - Andrew Morton's book Diana: Her True Story, is published in June. It
says the princess feels ``trapped in a loveless marriage'', suggests she
suffered from the slimmer's disease bulimia nervosa, and that she made a number
of suicide attempts in the early 1980s.
In August the ``Squidgygate'' tape scandal breaks, giving details of an
intimate telephone conversation said to be between Diana and long-standing
friend James Gilbey, in which he professes his love for her and calls her
``Squidgy''.
In November comes the ``Camillagate'' tape - allegedly a highly personal and
intimate conversation between the prince and Camilla Parker Bowles.
That same month, during a four-day visit to Korea, the prince and princess are
dubbed ``The Glums'', with reports that they are apparently unable to bear
being in each other's company.
The press unites to declare the marriage a sham and for the first time the
truth of the couple's unhappiness together begins to gain wide acceptance.
In December, the Prime Minister announces to a packed House of Commons that the
couple have agreed to separate.
1993 - In March an Australian TV company broadcast fresh extracts from the
Squidgygate tapes, alleging that the relationship between Diana and Gilbey was
much more intimate than previously claimed.
Charles and Diana attend some functions together - but mostly lead separate
lives.
In December the princess announces her withdrawal from public life and asks to
be allowed to live away from the media spotlight.
1994 - In June Charles admits to Jonathan Dimbleby, in a television
documentary, that he has been unfaithful to his wife. He says he has no
``regrets'' about the admission and believes he will still be crowned king.
In October Anna Pasternak's book about former Army officer James Hewitt's
alleged five-year affair with Diana is published, fuelling speculation that the
royal couple will divorce. But through their lawyers they deny plans for a
settlement.
Later in the month, the Sunday Times starts serialising Jonathan Dimbleby's
biography of Charles, which goes far further than the television interview,
giving an unprecedented insight into the prince's private life.
1995 - In August, Diana is linked with another man, England Rugby captain Will
Carling, after they become friends while training at an exclusive gym in
Chelsea, west London, and Mr Carling visits her at Kensington Palace.
The rugby player and his wife Julia later separate.
In September the prince and princess put on a public display of family unity
when they join Prince William on his first day at Eton.
But within a few weeks, the prince appears in public at a high society party at
London's Ritz hotel attended by Mrs Parker Bowles, refuelling speculation about
their relationship.
In November, an unprecedented interview with Diana is broadcast on the BBC's
Panorama, in which the princess reveals that she often feels herself under
attack from her husband's party, but insists that she does not want a divorce.
Earlier this month, it is suggested that Diana will be spending Christmas with
the royal family at Sandringham, but a few days ago it is announced that the
princess has changed her mind.
The decision is interpreted as a snub to the royals, but it is not yet known if
the princess had received the Queen's letter before deciding to stay away.
</TEXT>
