<HEADLINE>She will never be Queen, says constitutional expert</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF the Prince and Princess of Wales divorce, Diana would not become Queen,
according to a constitutional expert.
Laws and customs meant even if Diana's popularity and worldwide fame made her
ideal for the role, she would still be barred, said Dr Rodney Barker.
For a king could not choose a queen other than his wife.
But the royal family had enough power over titles to agree that Diana could
retain the title ``princess'' and perhaps that she remain ``Her Royal
Highness''.
The Prime Minister was unquestionably right when he said - announcing the
Wales's separation in December 1992 - that Diana could still be crowned queen,
according to Dr Barker, of the London School of Economics.
But divorce was a different matter.
Even if Charles renounced any intention of remarrying, he could not agree that
Diana could be queen to his king.
``It is inconceivable and constitutionally out-of-court that a person called
queen has neither succeeded to the throne in her own right nor is married to
the person who succeeded in his own right.''
By custom, said Dr Barker, a king's wife was crowned queen but queens - such as
Elizabeth II and Victoria - refrained from having their consorts crowned king.
``That is probably because of the ridiculous assumption that if there is a king
and a queen, the king is the important one.''
A divorced Diana could perhaps retain the title Princess of Wales, but that
seemed unlikely, he said.
Whether or not Charles had any intention at present of remarrying, allowing a
divorced Diana to retain the title would be seen by advisers as risking
confusion if, at some later stage, the prince took a new bride.
``You can hardly have two princesses of Wales,'' said Dr Barker. ``But one can
speculate that the palace could allow the use of the title Princess Diana.''
The title ``Her Royal Highness'' - famously denied the Duchess of Windsor after
the abdication of Edward VIII - was an honour for closely defined members of
the immediate royal family.
But, particularly as Diana was mother of Princes William and Harry, the Queen
could use her wide discretion to allow her to retain the style HRH.
Dr Barker said a divorce would not affect the rights of the young princes to
succeed to the throne.
Their father would remain immediate heir to the throne.
A divorce would have no direct constitutional significance, partly because the
eighteenth century Act of Settlement and Royal Marriages Act made no mention of
it. ``I imagine that was because in those days such a possibility wasn't even
considered.''
The way to divorce is clear. Just like thousands of unhappy couples who divorce
each year, the royal couple's names would be added to the list of individuals
parted on the nod of a County Court judge.
If both parties reach an amicable agreement, the whole process could be
concluded within a matter of weeks without any need to involve solicitors.
Under current law, all that is required is for the necessary legal papers to be
completed and a payment of #40.
A judge will then normally grant a provisional decree nisi, allowing the
parties a breathing space.
Six weeks later, unless the couple have changed their minds, the decree
absolute will automatically be granted and the marriage legally terminated.
Divorce can only take place if a marriage has irretrievably broken down.
To support this, at least one of five grounds must be proved: adultery,
unreasonable behaviour, desertion of two years or more by the respondent or two
years continuous separation - in which case a judge may refuse a decree if he
feels divorce might adversely affect the children - and a separation of five
years, which allows either side a decree without the consent of the other.
</TEXT>
