<HEADLINE>Cheating chief of law firm jailed for 10 years</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE former head of a large law firm was jailed for 10 years yesterday for
plundering more than #5m from dead clients and charities, including Guide Dogs
for the Blind.
Graham Durnford Ford, 52, carried out ``substantial and systematic thieving''
over a two-year period, the court heard.
He paid himself almost #900,000 in four years and used the rest to prop up his
law firm, one of the largest in the South-east of England.
Judge David Croft at Maidstone Crown Court called it ``cheating the dead''. He
added: ``What you did was build a dung hill for you to crawl upon.''
His plundering was often to such an extent that beneficiaries of wills were
left with virtually nothing to inherit after they were fooled by ``grossly,
almost ludicrously, excessive fees''.
Durnford Ford, described as a tyrant by his senior partners, headed a law firm
in Hastings, Sussex, with branches in Battle, Bexhill, Eastbourne, Hailsham,
Polegate, Rye, Seaford, Ashford, in Kent, and London.
He used most of the money to keep his company afloat and to give the appearance
of a successful businessman enjoying ``a very good living''.
Following his arrest by the serious fraud office, his firm collapsed with the
loss of 230 jobs.
Durnford Ford admitted 10 specimen charges of theft amounting to #148,700. He
was jailed for one year on every charge, to run consecutively.
Mr Timothy Barnes, prosecuting, said it was not in the public interest to
divulge the exact amount stolen. But he added: ``The extent of the losses is
not less than #5m.''
The total losses paid out by the law society in compensation are #8.7m, the
court was told.
Other former directors now have to pay 50% of their salary, plus any windfall
payments, to the Law Society. Contributions by other solicitors throughout the
country to the Law Society compensation fund have also increased.
One estate of #33,800 was reduced by Durnford Ford to #530. Another fell from
#62,000 to just #9200 and a bequest of #140,000 to the Guide Dogs Association
plunged to #13,500.
Durnford Ford, of South Lodge, Saxon Hill, North Trade Road, Battle, Sussex,
denied four charges of furnishing false information and these were left on file.
His co-accused, William Bew, 38, of Cirencester, also denied four charges of
furnishing false information.
He was found guilty of all four charges by the jury after an eight-week trial.
He was given 15 months, suspended for one year.
Bew resigned just five days before the firm collapsed. He chose not to give
evidence during his trial.
He was a junior partner and was worried about the way the company was being
run, but was too timid to tackle his chief.
The court was told insurance policies of more than #70,000 were cashed to pay
advance school for Durnford Ford's daughters.
Mr Peter Hilton, defending, said: ``As a fraudster Mr Durnford Ford is in the
upper league. His conduct has had a crippling effect on his partners.''
Judge Croft told the court Durnford Ford was one of the most devious conmen he
had come across.
``Bew was one of your direct victims. You corrupted him and you caused him to
be in the dock today,'' he said.
Durnford Ford has been struck off.
</TEXT>
