<HEADLINE>Monklands council cleared of `jobs for the boys' Inquiry fails to silence critics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter and CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONKLANDS District Council was cleared yesterday of providing ``jobs for the
boys'' by an independent inquiry set up by the Government, but critics refused
to let the matter rest.
As Labour leader Jim Brooks and his colleagues celebrated, political opponents
pledged to continue their campaign over allegations of nepotism and religious
bias.
The next step in the saga is likely to come from Labour's own hierarchy next
month.
The party's national executive committee is due to consider its unpublished
report into the allegations and the suspension of some 15 Labour councillors in
Monklands since June.
Mr William Nimmo Smith, QC, in an 83-page report, found no evidence to support
any allegation of religious bias or nepotism in making job appointments within
the council. He also found no evidence to support allegations that Labour Party
connections or membership had a material effect on appointments.
However, the QC said the council's previous employment procedures had given
rise to the perception that appointments had been made for improper reasons.
Mr Nimmo Smith, who described Councillor Brooks as ``a strong-willed man who
liked to control the exercise of power'', went on: ``I think that much of the
trouble which has arisen, and in particular the allegations with which I am
concerned, stem from the insensitive exercise of power. If power is exercised
in such a way as to lead to a sense of exclusion, suspicions are more readily
aroused and rumours and allegations gain currency.''
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth said the report concluded that the council
had not failed to comply with requirements of Section 7 of the Local Government
and Housing Act, 1989. He added: ``No further action is therefore required by
me.''
Councillor Brooks said: ``I am delighted with the report. It is a vindication
in detail of the people of Monklands.''
However, English Tory MP David Shaw, who was castigated in the official report,
last night insisted his campaign would continue regardless of the findings.
Mr Shaw, whose attitude on giving evidence was described as irresponsible by Mr
Nimmo Smith, said: ``It is not irresponsible to raise matters of amazing
concern to people. No one will be satisfied with this report, apart from those
with vested family and financial interests in the outcome.''
The Dover MP added: ``As far as I am concerned, this matter will never be
over.''
He argued, as did Scottish Tory chairman Sir Michael Hirst and rebel Monklands
Labour councillors, that the terms of the inquiry had been too narrow.
The council's SNP group spokesman, Mr Neil Douglas, dismissed the report as a
Scottish Office-prompted sham, and also complained the inquiry should have
extended beyond employment practices.
Critics were also unhappy that the inquiry had been legally restricted to
investigating events after 1990. Some allegations of ``jobs for the boys''
dated before then. In addition, job application procedures had been altered
since 1994.
The Government inquiry followed allegations that people could get jobs with
Monklands if they were relatives or friends of councillors, or connected to the
Labour Party, or were of a certain religious persuasion.
However, the remit did not cover other allegations: including a spending bias
in favour of Coatbridge by Roman Catholic councillors against the mainly
Protestant town of Airdrie.
The inquiry also followed another, commissioned by the council itself and
chaired by
Professor Robert Black, whose findings failed to eliminate public concerns that
the council was run by a ``Monklands Mafia''.
His report coincided with the entire Monkland ruling group being suspended by
the Labour Party pending its investigation into the allegations.
Professor Black's report was described by Mr Nimmo Smith yesterday as ``a
disappointment''. So far as employment issues were concerned, it did ``no more
than repeat allegations which were already current''.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said: ``This report is a vindication
of the Labour Party's demand two years ago for this kind of inquiry to get at
the truth.``
He conceded there were strong criticisms in the report of councillors and
council procedures which gave rise to the allegations. But he was adamant:
``The wilder allegations of Ministers and David Shaw have been firmly
rejected.''
Monklands West MP Tom Clarke welcomed the ``thorough report'' and the
conclusion that there was no evidence to substantiate the claims.
Scottish Conservative chairman Sir Michael Hirst said: ``It should be
remembered that the terms of reference were very narrow. Notwithstanding the
findings, the council accepted and implemented a number of recommendations from
consultants to improve their recruitment and employment methods. This all came
about only after the Monklands stooshie blew up.''
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said: ``No democrat could have
taken any consolation from a finding there had been malpractice in Monklands.
The report is therefore a timely reassurance that the council did not fail to
comply with its duties.''
</TEXT>
