<HEADLINE>Judge admonishes wife who killed husband</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN abused mother was admonished by a judge yesterday after she killed her
husband with a single stab wound through the heart.
Mother-of-two Jean Digney, 44, was allowed to walk free from the High Court in
Edinburgh by Lord Abernethy.
She was originally charged with murdering her husband, Mr James Digney, but her
plea to the reduced charge of culpable homicide was accepted when she appeared
in court last year.
The couple's son had found his father dead in a chair and his mother weeping in
their home in Wallace Road, Irvine, Ayrshire.
Lord Abernethy deferred sentence on her for a year to be of good behaviour. He
admonished her yesterday.
The judge heard at the earlier hearing at the High Court in Glasgow that she
had been terrorised by her husband and that he had demanded sex from her at all
hours.
The stabbing victim suffered from polio and was taking steroids which
heightened his sexual demand. He made obsessive sexual demands at all times of
the day, it was alleged.
The court heard that on the fatal night in September last year the couple, who
had an 11-year-old son and an eight-year-old daughter, had been arguing and
drinking.
Mrs Digney later told police: ``I didn't mean to kill him. I just got hold of
the knife. I killed their dad.''
The court was told that Mrs Digney's son Keiran was a diabetic who had had to
go into hospital while his mother was remanded in prison before her initial
appearance in the High Court last December.
Lord Abernethy originally agreed to defer sentence on her for a year because
she was needed at home to care for her son. He decided she was not a threat to
the public.
Last night the dead man's widowed mother Mrs Mary Digney, 66, said from her
home at Dunton Knoll, Irvine: ``I don't think justice has been done, although
for the children's sake I'm glad she's free. I'm not fit to look after them.''
</TEXT>
