<HEADLINE>Family to sell their home over ban on pets</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH family have put their house on the market to save their pets from a
builder's ban on animals.
Ralph and Anna Baillie moved into their new, #145,000 home four months ago with
their three children and their three pets.
But now, the family are having to sell up so that the children can keep their
pets.
Muir Homes Ltd has threatened legal action unless the Baillies get rid of
Guin-Guin the guinea pig, Bun-Bun the rabbit, and Shamu their Samoyed dog. The
Inverkeithing-based firm has told the family that it will act to enforce a
clause in the title deeds which prohibits the keeping of ``livestock''.
Now, after heartfelt pleas by their children - Charles, 11, nine-year-old
Miranda, and six-year-old Henrietta - the Baillies have opted to sell their
three-bedroom, detached house in Bridgewater Avenue, Auchterarder, Perthshire.
Guin-guin belongs to Henrietta, Bun-bun has been Miranda's since he was a
bunny, and Shamu is the favourite of all the family.
Charles, Miranda, and Henrietta are so devoted to their pets that they even
told their parents to forget about presents this Christmas and let them keep
the animals instead.
Mr Baillie, 38, a post-graduate business student at the University of London,
said, ``The animals are a part of this family and the children would be
devastated if we had to get rid of them.
``This was supposed to be our dream home but Muir Homes have left us with no
option but to move.'' He added, ``It is a ridiculous situation. The children
will need to be moved to new schools and it will take time to settle in to
another house.
``But it is the only way to keep the entire family together, including the pets.
``Muir Homes has an annual turnover of #32m. I can't believe they are being so
strict about something so minor.''
The family's rabbit and guinea pig are kept outside in a hutch and the dog also
spends part of the day in the back garden in his kennel.
The Baillie's home is part of a development of a dozen new homes with several
still for sale, and is next door to the scheme's show house.
Muir Homes maintains neighbours have complained about the animals but the
Baillies have been around all of their neighbours and claim that none have
admitted to objecting to the pets.
An offer by the Baillies not to replace the existing pets as they died off was
rejected by the builders which threatened legal action unless the animals are
disposed of by the end of this week.
Mr Ian Steven, conveyancing partner at Rollo, Steven and Bond solicitors, said:
``On the face of it, this does seem fairly mean of the builder.
``But they want to sell their houses and most modern schemes now do have
clauses limiting pets to one dog or one cat. It is to stop people breeding
animals and is a universal clause in most modern developments.''
The Baillies previously lived in the countryside, outside Crieff, with no
neighbours.
Last night Mrs Baillie, 33, a jewellery designer, vowed that she would ``never
live in a modern housing estate again.
``Our solicitor pointed out the clause in the deeds to us but we didn't think
that `livestock' meant the childrens' pets,'' she said.
She added: ``There is no way we can get rid of the animals, it would be
heartbreaking. If the animals go, we go.''
A spokesman for Muir Homes said that the matter was in the hands of the
company's solicitors and it did not wish to discuss the situation further.
