<HEADLINE>Queen orders divorce Dilemma for Diana as Charles agrees to the final parting</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen has urged the Prince and Princess of Wales to seek ``an early
divorce'', and Charles has agreed.
Buckingham Palace said last night that the Queen made her dramatic intervention
in a letter to each of them this week.
Her move came amid continued public debate about the effect of the marital
disagreement on the future of the royal family and the monarchy.
A Palace spokesman said the prince responded to the letter by indicating that
he agreed with his mother, but the princess's response was not known.
``After considering the present situation the Queen wrote to both the prince
and princess earlier this week and gave them her view, supported by the Duke of
Edinburgh, that an early divorce is desirable,'' the spokesman said.
``The Prince of Wales also takes this view and has made this known to the
Princess of Wales since the letter.
``The Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh will continue to do all they can to help
and support the Prince and Princess of Wales, and most particularly their
children, in this difficult period.''
There was no indication how soon a divorce could take place, and how imminent
any further announcement might be, he said.
The Queen's action came weeks after the public debate about the future of the
marriage was heightened dramatically by the princess's interview on Panorama.
In it she said she did not want a divorce, but was repeatedly critical of her
husband, his family, and their advisers.
Constitutional experts have said that a divorce would mean Diana could never be
queen.
When asked on Panorama if she wanted to be queen, she said that she was more
interested in being a ``Queen of Hearts'' by developing her role in public life.
The Palace spokesman declined to say when the Queen's letters were sent, other
than earlier this week.
He said there was no connection between the letter and the princess's
apparently sudden decision not to join her estranged husband and the rest of
the royal family at Sandringham for Christmas.
It is understood the princess told the Queen on Sunday that she had changed her
mind about Christmas, less than a month after letting it be known that she
would be at Sandringham.
The Prime Minister and senior Privy Councillors have backed the Queen's
decision after prolonged private talks over the last two weeks.
The Buckingham Palace announcement last night followed discussion between the
Queen and her Prime Minister after the Princess of Wales spoke on Panorama of
``enemies''.
The Prime Minister will undoubtedly welcome the prospect of an apparent end to
the ``War of the Waleses''.
He has long believed the present situation was unsatisfactory and untenable,
especially when there appeared to be no immediate prospect of a complete split.
Mr Major, who announced the couple's original separation in the Commons, will
make a further statement to MPs once divorce proceedings are in train.
The news broke hours after the princess met Mr Major at her home in Kensington
Palace.
He is thought to have discussed her known wish for an officially recognised
role in public life, probably as some kind of goodwill ambassador. Mr Major,
who is understood to have met the Princess privately two or three times a year
at Kensington Palace, has been a strong supporter of her desire for such a role.
It seemed certain that she would have raised the question of divorce in the
light of the Queen's letter.
Mr Major has given his consent to a royal divorce as he was obliged to do as
Prime Minister at the Queen's bidding. The issue was not handled at Cabinet
level but on a one-to-one basis when the Prime Minister saw the Queen at a
weekly audience two days ago.
Constitutional experts have been working on this scenario for several years and
Prince William remains, after his father, successor to the throne.
In her Panorama interview on November 20, Diana said she did not want a
divorce. She told interviewer Martin Bashir: ``I don't want a divorce but
obviously we need clarity. I await my husband's decision of which way we are
all going to go.''
She described her feelings on her separation from her husband: ``Deep, deep,
profound sadness. Because we had struggled to keep it going, but obviously we'd
both run out of steam.
``And in a way I suppose it could have been a relief for us both that we'd
finally made our minds up. But my husband asked for the separation and I
supported it.''
She said she had not asked for a separation: ``I come from a divorced
background and I didn't want to go into that one again.''
Constitutional expert and former Conservative Cabinet Minister Lord St John of
Fawsley said: ``I think it is extremely sad that events have come to this.
``I feel, however, that the Queen was quite right to intervene and to say they
must now make up their minds to divorce, or make a go of it. Clearly they are
not going to make a go of it.''
Lord St John said a divorce
Continued from page 1
would have no constitutional effect on the Prince of Wales. ``But it will have
an effect on the Princess of Wales because when the divorce goes through she
will not become queen. But it has no effect on his position under the Act of
Settlement.''
Constitutional expert Vernon Bogdanor also said there were no constitutional
implications in a divorce.
``We have had a divorced king before,'' he told Newsnight.
``Once the divorce has gone through, Diana is no longer the wife of the heir to
the throne, so she no longer becomes queen and that is an important resolution
of the problem, because as long as they are not divorced she would become Queen
as soon as Charles ascended to the throne.''
A Tory Minister applauded the Queen's decision to call for an ``early divorce''.
Sir John Wheeler, a Minister in the Northern Ireland Office, said: ``As one of
Her Majesty's Privy Councillors, I welcome the decision.
``It is a good thing to clear the air in the interests of constitutional
monarchy and for the good of the two people concerned.''
Senior Tory MP Sir Teddy Taylor, a strong supporter of the princess, said:
``What is most unusual is the fact that this information had been made public.
``It is disappointing that this kind of intervention in a highly charged
situation between two young people has been made public.
``Whoever made it public should be locked in the Tower or thrown in the
Thames.''
Conservative MP James Hill, chairman of the Commons Constitutional Committee,
said: ``I think it is excellent news but as I have said for some months that
family and domestic problems should be resolved and I am very pleased that the
Queen has acted. I think this has been in my mind for some months now but the
problem of young children has to be clarified.
``As far as the end of the affair I hope it is amicable and there is no longer
any tit-for-tat. I think it will be the best thing for the nation.''
Senior Tory MP Sir Patrick Cormack said: ``Sadly I believe divorce is
inevitable.
"It would be unthinkable to have an estranged, but still married, king and
queen.''
He suggested the princess's Panorama interview, in which she said she was
opposed to the idea of divorce, had hastened the issue.
``That interview was a very sad and sorry performance in many ways.
``She did everything to demonstrate that the marriage was over, everything to
question her husband's fitness to be king.''
</TEXT>
