<HEADLINE>Brown expects coach's dismissal to unsettle Swiss Hodgson can become a secret agent for Scots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTER-Milan manager Roy Hodgson, newly sacked as coach of Scotland's European
Championship opponents Switzerland, could become a soccer spy for Craig Brown.
Brown has spoken to Hodgson and has already asked him to visit the Scotland
training camp during the championships next summer. He believes Hodgson can be
an important aid as he plans for the final match of our three-country section
against the Swiss.
Said Brown yesterday: ``I know Roy very well and I was speaking to him on the
telephone just after he was told that the Swiss no longer wanted him to look
after the national team. Obviously, he was upset, because it had seemed that
the Swiss FA had agreed to a dual role for him, one which would have allowed
him to coach Inter-Milan and remain with the Swiss for their European
Championship games.
``Even after the draw at the weekend, Roy was under the impression that he
would remain in charge. Then on Tuesday, he was told that Artur Jorge from
Portugal was taking over.
``I don't think the Swiss players will react too well to this change. Roy was
highly respected by them and, after all, it was under his guidance that they
went to the World Cup finals for the first time in nearly 30 years.
``Now he's gone and I have to admit that this is a boost for us. It will
unsettle the Swiss and upset their planning and organisation, and they have
been major components in their recent successes.
``I know, too, that if I ask Roy a straight question then he will give me a
straight answer. If I want to know anything about his former team then I am
sure he will tell me, and he will be honest.
``We will be looking at all the teams in the group ourselves, but I believe Roy
will be able to give us some valuable insights.''
Enlisting Hodgson's aid, even in a modest manner, could add substantially to
Brown's dossier on the Swiss. He knows them already, of course, from the last
World Cup qualifying campaign, when they were one of the teams who prevented
Scotland from reaching the United States.
Brown insists: ``We have arranged for videos of all the recent games played by
our three opponents in the European finals and we will look at all their games
from now on.
``If I cannot see them myself, then Alex Miller or Frank Coulston will go to
see them. Our preparations must be as thorough as they were during the
qualifying period - and they will be.
``The England game will be particularly intriguing, of course. We have the
prospect of clashes between team-mates to look forward to - Colin Calderwood
could be asked to take care of Teddy Sheringham, Colin Hendry versus Alan
Shearer, and even Stuart McCall against Paul Gascoigne. All of them will want
to get the better of the lads they train alongside every day.
``That is going to add a bit to a game that really doesn't need any more
ingredients to whip up interest.
``The Dutch are liable to miss Danny Blind through suspension and he is the man
who organises their defence. He is the main inspiration at the back and the
young players in the team look to him for guidance. So that could help.''
The Scots' team manager has now agreed with the International Committee that
only two warm-up games will be played before the end of the season. One of
these will be at home against a major European country in March - and the
opponents will be announced later this week.
The other is the game against reigning European champions Denmark in Copenhagen
in April.
Following that, the Scottish squad will travel to the United States in May to
play two more games. Both are likely to be in New York, one against the United
States and the other could be against Chile.
These will be Brown's final opportunities to get the squad ready for the games
in England in June.
Meanwhile, the players that Hodgson had moulded into one of the most dangerous
international sides in Europe were indeed angered by the Swiss football
federation's treatment of the Englishman.
``I am very, very disappointed,'' Bayern Munich forward Ciri Sforza told a
Swiss newspaper. ``I just don't understand why they made the decision.''
``It would have been better to hold our team together until the finals,'' said
captain Alain Geiger.
q ANOTHER manager whose position is under threat is the Republic of Ireland's
Jack Charlton, who will meet Football Association of Ireland officials today
with speculation mounting that his nine-year reign will come to an end.
It is believed the Republic are anxious to have a new man installed by January
23, when the dates for the World Cup fixtures will be sorted out.
The FAI yesterday refused to elaborate on the Dublin meeting, saying only: ``It
is purely speculation in the papers. There is no news conference planned.''
Millwall manager Mick McCarthy, who played for the national side with
distinction, is among the front-runners to replace Charlton.
Charlton was hoping to celebrate 10 years in charge by leading the Republic in
the European Championship finals next summer, but those dreams were dashed when
they were outclassed by Holland in the play-off at Anfield last week, their
fourth defeat in five games.
The manner of that 2-0 defeat by the Dutch not only disappointed Charlton but
many of the FAI hierachy, who now feel a change is essential if they are to
progress.
Charlton, 60, has dragged the Republic up by their bootlaces during his time in
charge. Under his unique style of management, Ireland have lost only 17 times
in 93 matches.
</TEXT>
