<TEXT>
KEVIN Francis struck twice to send first division Birmingham into the
quarter-finals of the Coca-Cola Cup south of the Border, ending Juninho's hopes
of a Wembley cup-final appearance.
Francis flattened Middlesbrough's Premiership high-fliers with a double in the
first 17 minutes at St Andrews to give the Brazilian, Juninho, his first bitter
taste of a giant-killing defeat.
The 6ft 7in former Stockport striker gave the Blues the lead after 11 minutes,
and before Bryan Robson's side could recover, Francis grabbed a second six
minutes later.
At Burnden Park, Gary Megson, No.2 at Bradford but fancied to take over as
manager of Norwich, watched City take on Bolton.
The match ended 0-0 after extra time, with Norwich winning the tie on penalties.
q WIMBLEDON striker Dean Holdsworth has been advised to see out the remaining
18 months of his contract with the London club. The advice comes from his
agent, Eric Hall, who believes it is in the player's best interests following
the judgement in the Jean-Marc Bosman case.
Players are now free to move at the end of their contracts with no fee involved
in cross-border transfers within the European Union. ``Dean might move abroad
and I know I could fix him up with a super, super deal,'' said Hall.
``I have already had inquiries about him from clubs in Spain and Italy. For
that reason it would be in his best interests, for the time being, to stay at
Wimbledon.''
Top players, like Holdsworth, could be set for rich pickings when their
contracts end. Money that would have been used to finance transfer fees will
now be used to line their pockets - and those of their agents.
q FLU victim Duncan Ferguson could be struggling to make Everton's team for
Saturday's Premiership trip to Coventry. The former Rangers striker has been
confined to bed since being sent home from training on Monday.
Ferguson, who has made two substitute appearances since his release from
prison, had to pull out of Tuesday night's reserve clash with Sheffield
Wednesday, missing out on vital match practice.
q FALKIRK midfielder Steve Kirk's move to East Fife is off. The Fifers agreed a
fee with Brockville manager John Lambie, but the 32-year-old player could not
agree personal terms with the second division leaders.
q MATTHEW Wicks is at the centre of a tug of war between three London clubs
after having decided that he wants to leave Manchester United. Alex Ferguson is
having talks with Tottenham about the young defender, the subject of an FA
inquiry into ``poaching'' allegations by Arsenal.
The Gunners would like him back and Chelsea also are said to be interested in
Wicks, who is unsettled at Old Trafford and wants to return to his London home.
