<RECORDNO>974782583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Capital
not in
the fast
lane
THE only opportunity to see Britain's leading athletes in Scotland next year
will be at the Kelvin Hall on February 24, because Edinburgh cannot afford the
cost of hosting a             major track meeting.
The capital's inability to find at least #10,000 towards competitors' assembly
costs for a summer match means Glasgow's indoor McDonald's International will
be Scotland's only Olympic year track-and-field spectacular.
``We hoped Edinburgh would pick up a European permit event,'' said British
Athletics Federation spokesman Tony Ward.
``It's a disappointment that when there was scope for such a meeting in
Scotland, it will now go ahead at Crystal Palace. In future we hope it can be
restored - or, of course, Glasgow could build a suitable standard arena and we
could bring it here.''
Edinburgh, forced on financial grounds to spike a planned UK match against the
USA this year, will have competition should it try to pick up the baton again.
By this time next year a new       stadium with a 10-lane straight will be
completed at Scotstoun, where plans include an 8000-capacity stand.
``Our position is that we were willing to host the event, which to us means
offering a free            stadium, and providing a civic reception and
marketing support,'' said an Edinburgh Dis-trict Council's spokesman.
``Unfortunately, the council has had to make considerable cuts in the
recreation budget for civic amenities and is unable to offer direct financial
support of the kind BAF wanted.''
Sally Gunnell, the grand       slam Olympic, World, European, and Commonwealth
400 metres hurdles champion, confirmed yesterday that she will compete for
Britain against France in Glasgow, possibly facing Scotland's Europa Cup
one-lap champion, Mel Neef, over 200m.
The meeting will be the last before the European indoor championships in
Stockholm, and UK team places will still be at stake. Gunnell, who plans to
miss the Europeans, said: ``I may do the 200 or 400m in Glasgow, I am not 100%
sure which yet and won't decide until nearer the time.''
BAF confirmed they are to ask the French to send as strong a team as possible
in the face of complaints by Glasgow that recent visiting teams have been
second rate. It also is a disappointment that, as yet, there is no agreement
between the promoters and 'Nuff Respect, the agency whose principal assets,
Linford Christie and Colin Jackon, declined to run in BAF outdoor events this
year.
Spokesman Ward insists BAF is ``hopeful,'' but it is perhaps significant that
the pair have been omitted from publicity material which features sprinter
Darren Braithwaite and hurdler Tony Jarrett, both of whom will run in Glasgow.
The event will rely on such as Mark Hylton, the 18-year-old European junior
400m champion who surprised Scotland's Brian Whittle when beating him for the
AAA senior indoor title last winter. Such is the depth of British one-lap
quality that he could win a European indoor medal, yet struggle to make our
Olympic relay squad.
Ward is encouraged, meantime, that Christie, despite repeated vows that his
cham- pionship career is over, this week confirmed he will compete in the AAA
championships, from which the first two past       the post will be selected
for the Olympics.
Neef, who will have her first outing of the winter a week on Saturday in
Edinburgh's New Year Sprint meeting at Meadowbank, said: ``I plan to race 60
and 200m indoors most of the winter, then switch to 400m for the AAA and
European indoor.''
She added that she will have to make Britain's team on merit at the shorter
distances against France. ``I was running fast enough to do that last year, and
hopefully can do so again. With the Olympics, I don't want a long indoor season
of 400m running. But I recognise I have a responsibility.
``Not many Scots make the British team, but those who do, like Yvonne Murray
and Liz McColgan, Tom McKean and Brian Whittle, have a tradition   of winning
medals. It's time I       did that, and hopefully the             European
indoors will give me the chance to do so.''
Tickets for the Glasgow event (#9 and #5 for children and   senior citizens)
are on sale at      the arena, or call the ticket hotline: 0141 337 1806.
</TEXT>
