<HEADLINE>Hawick back district challenge in Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAWICK have given public, but qualified backing to the Scottish Rugby Union's
recommendations that districts and not clubs should represent Scotland in
Europe next season.
In a statement released yesterday Bob Chrystie, the vice-president of Hawick,
said: ``Scottish clubs are not strong enough to take on the Baths and Cardiffs
of this world. Going in as we are would do Scottish rugby's image no favours,
and while it might strengthen the bank balances of a few clubs, it would
certainly be at the expense of the game in Scotland.
``If clubs go into Europe then they will be faced with strengthening their
teams with outsiders - something that would not be good for the game in
Scotland - or by trawling other clubs.
``Scotland players whose clubs were not involved in Europe would seek new
stages for their talents and that in turn could take them to England, Wales,
or, further afield seeking remuneration.''
The Border club, which won a record 11 championship titles in a 14-year span,
rejects the idea being banded about of hybrid districts being formed next
season and instead thinks that the SRU should devolve power to existing
autonomous regions.
``Full-time professionals - in rugby development, administration, and marketing
- would work from within each district with overall responsibility for rugby at
all levels from mini through to representative games and this structure would
be funded by the SRU,'' said John Thorburn, the Hawick secretary.
Thorburn believes that players are unlikely to be released by clubs south of
the Border for district representation, but suggests that both parties will
have to come to a contractual accommodation.
``It would be a pretty stupid player - or agent - who did not have this built
into his contract with a new club,'' said Thorburn. ``Players will soon realise
that they are in demand and it is up to them to strike the best deal in a
spirit of give and take.''
Thorburn suggests that failure by players to represent their district should
automatically exclude them from national representation. ``With lucrative
contracts at international level, that might make some players consider that
their best future lies in Scotland,'' he said.
Despite their backing of the SRU, Hawick remain critical of the union's lack of
consultation with clubs. ``There are too many rumours flying around and anxiety
breeds fear,'' said Thorburn. ``The present district structure is not perfect,
but where there exists an obvious indentity, as with the South, then that
should be seen as the way ahead.
``Hybrid teams will prove nothing and it is questionable if they would be
allowed into the competition anyway.''
