<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALBERT Craig yesterday turned his back on Partick Thistle and headed up the A80
to team-up again with John Lambie, now manager of Falkirk.
Craig, plus #10,000, was part of the deal which takes striker Nicky Henderson
to Firhill, and the new man at Brockville was hardly in the door when Falkirk
assistant manager Gerry Collins was tipping Craig to play a big part in helping
his new club ease their way off      the bottom rung of the premier division
ladder.
``We're well aware of Albert's capabilities as John worked with him at both
Hamilton and Partick Thistle,'' said Collins. ``The type of quality Albert has
is hard to come by and we're delighted to have brought him here.''
Falkirk have found goals hard to come by this term and Collins reckons Craig
can help solve that problem. ``Albert gets himself into the box well for a
midfield player,'' said Collins. ``By his standards, last season was a bad year
for him yet he still managed seven goals. He may be 32, but he's a fit lad who
takes care of himself.''
And Henderson may not be        the only new face in the Thistle team in the
near future. Steve McMahon, a 25-year-old striker who has spent two years in
China, is now on trial at Firhill. ``I've been training with Thistle for three
weeks,'' said McMahon. ``Last season I scored nine goals in 22 league games and
the lad I played alongside was top scorer.''
However, Thistle manager Murdo MacLeod issued a note of caution. ``He's done
well in training, but I need to see him play a few games to get a better idea
of his ability.''
q.MARTIN O'Neill is expected to    be confirmed as Leicester's new manager
within the next 24 hours. The club have been given permission to talk with the
Irishman following his recent resignation from Norwich after only six months in
charge.
Leicester chairman Martin George is negotiating a compensation deal with the
Carrow Road side, thought to be around #500,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Good form now has Celtic at the races</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC'S good recent form has attracted the attention of punters, and as a
result leading bookmakers have the Parkhead side at the shortest Christmas odds
to win the premier division title for years, with one large layer contemplating
a #300,000 loss.
At the start of the season, Rangers were expected to make it eight title
successes in a row. However, Tuesday's goalless draw at Motherwell has left the
champions only two points clear of Celtic at the halfway stage.
While the Ibrox club remain championship favourites, the Old Firm have still to
meet twice, with the first showdown at Parkhead on January 3.
Corals had Rangers at 1-6 in August, with Celtic 6-1. Before the game against
Motherwell the league leaders were 2-7, with Celtic 5-2, but yesterday the odds
were 4-11 Rangers and 2-1 against Tommy Burns' team. ``We've trimmed the odds
again on Celtic after the Rangers result,'' said a spokesman for Corals.
``These are the shortest odds I can remember on Celtic winning the league at
this time of year since Graeme Souness became Rangers' manager in 1986.''
Ladbrokes appear confident that Rangers will see off their city rivals. They
offered the same pre-season odds as their rivals but now have cut them to 1-5
Rangers, with Celtic at 11-4.
``Celtic have received more backing for this season than for many years,'' said
a Ladbrokes spokesman. ``A lot of cash went on them in August, but the
bookmakers still expect Rangers to win the league. If Celtic do it, we will
have to pay out around #300,000, so from that point of view we're cheering
Rangers.''
q.FORMER Aberdeen player Willem van der Ark has been ordered to give up
football or run the risk of being crippled. A recurring groin injury has forced
the 32-year-old striker, now with Camburr, to retire.
Van der Ark, the only foreigner to score a hat trick in the Scottish Cup,
revealed: ``It has been a long-standing problem which surgery has failed to
clear up. When the medical people ask you to choose between a career or a
wheelchair there is no decision.''
q.SCOTT Booth, missing since a thigh injury forced him out the Coca-Cola Cup
final last month, is now back in full training.
``I am aiming to use him in a reserve game against Falkirk on Saturday,'' said
Aberdeen manager Roy Aitken. ``This means that I will have available all my
first-team squad apart from Colin Woodthorpe.''
Pittodrie chief scout Jimmy Carswell is making progress in a Glasgow hospital,
where he has been detained after having suffered a stroke earlier this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Raith have a history goal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAITH Rovers play against Celtic on Tuesday knowing that success will move them
into the history books. Three points for the men from Stark's Park would put
Raith into third top place in the premier division, their highest position in
113 years.
It is a far cry from 21 months ago when the club were close to bankruptcy, but
were saved when chairman Alex Penman stepped in. He took over the reigns at
Kirkcaldy and now Penman, with a little help from Jimmy Nicholl and his
players, has turned the club around.
``We have made great strides as a club and most of that is down to the players
and the manager,'' said Penman. ``But we are not content to settle for what we
have. Permission has been granted for us to build three new stands at our
ground. This will bring the capacity of the stadium up to 10,400.
``We will continue to try and build this club because there is massive
potential.''
q.HIBERNIAN have gone back       to school and become the envy        of Craig
Brown, the Scotland manager. Brown, a former teacher, was at Easter Road
yesterday to lend his support to a new scheme linking Hibs with 10 local
primary schools.
Hibs have started an education pack for schools which involves pupils doing
projects on the club. ``We have been planning a similar schools pack with the
SFA but Hibs have beaten us to it,'' said Brown.
``I commend this scheme and we'll be pinching some of the ideas for the SFA
pack.
``In my experience if there is more interest, there will be better learning.
Ask school children to spell ``Wednesday'' and ``Thistle'' and they will find
some difficulty. But they have no problem if you stick ``Sheffield'' and
``Partick'' in front of the words.''
Aberdeen have a similar schools scheme running and other clubs in Scotland are
likely to follow suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Put a stop to talk of change</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Players' Union yesterday suggested that an independent review is
needed to decide on the best league structure for football, and union secretary
Tony Higgins claimed: ``That would stop the hardy annual each year of people
putting forward ideas for change.''
The Scottish League management committee meets today in Glasgow with first
division clubs pressing for a 16-club premier division next season. But the
indications last night were this would not gain the necessary support.
Even if the clubs are successful in calling an extraordinary general meeting,
they will require 75 per cent backing for a new set-up next season, or
two-thirds backing for a change the following year.
There is also a fear that the major sponsors in football would be unhappy at a
major change in the structure, after being assured the present four leagues of
10 clubs would run for a minimum of five years.
Higgins is a member of the Ernie Walker ``think tank'' at present investigating
Scottish football, but stressed that the make-up of the leagues does not come
into their remit.
Said Higgins: ``A straw poll of players would probably find they agreed with
the managers that they would like a bigger premier division. But the issue is
much wider than that.
``I feel independent research is required and that might mean an investigation
lasting up to a couple of years.
``An independent commission would look into the issue of full-time football,
quality of stadia, commercial activities, television, and much more.
``We understand the difficulties for our members are right across the range of
the clubs, taking in full-time and part-time players, and we know that it is
particularly difficult for any one club to speak conclusively for the whole of
Scottish football.
``But an independent body could put forward a plan. The clubs could accept or
reject it. But, either way, we would know where we stood and annual discussion
about change could be brought to an end.''
q JAMES TRAYNOR'S VIEW - Page 31
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Finance is the key to change in the top league Two-times table would add up for premier clubs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR-Chief sports writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish League's management committee will assemble this morning, and at
some point of their meeting, they will discuss a proposal to dismantle the four
divisions of 10 clubs each. The move for change is being driven by the first
division members, who feel the interests of the game are being undermined by
the current set-up, which was supposed to run for at least five years.
Even though they will be opposed by the might of the Old Firm, and at least
four of the other premier division concerns, they are determined to press
ahead, believing that when details of their proposal have been examined by the
second and third division clubs, they will win greater backing.
Rangers, Celtic (whose chairman Fergus McCann made his views known in
yesterday's Herald Arena column), and the others who are against, believe the
current format to be better than the proposal to change to a        16-club
premier division and two divisions, each of 12 clubs.
They also feel the quality of the football would suffer, because an increased
top division would inevitably mean a number of meaningless matches between
sides who neither were challenging for promotion, nor trying to beat relegation.
There are arguments on both sides which make some sense, but perhaps it should
be remembered that the bottom line is a top division of 10 clubs playing one
another four times each season is not healthy. There are too many matches, and
meeting the same players regularly breeds a familiarity which does not do the
game any good.
Players are too aware of the strengths and weaknesses of their opponents and
matches can be stale. Also, there is something to be said about the demands
placed on players and managers - let us not talk about pressure, because that
is something experienced by people trying to support families while out of
work - and they have to be protected. There is little point in abusing and
neglecting assets, even if those assets are modest in terms of real worth.
The Scottish League should change, and the top division should have at least 12
clubs who should not be required to play one another more than twice, home and
away, in the league. Some clubs will be       appalled at the thought of only
11 home matches in the league, but it is time the game's finances were
restructured in tandem with ways   designed to improve the       quality of
play.
McCann, and Murray - a prime mover behind the push for a Super League - are
correct in their belief that clubs who wish to play at the top should have
proper facilities and sound finances, and it is also difficult to disagree with
them over the number of clubs who have professional status. It really was a
nonsense to increase the size of the Scottish League from 38 clubs to 40 when,
if harsh realities were being faced, the membership would be reduced.
There are too many seeking a share of too little, and sooner or later the
league will be streamlined. In fact, the decision might be made for the
Scottish clubs because UEFA are still running scared of Europe's big clubs, who
are always seeking ways to win more sponsorship money.
One of the main reasons for the successful Champions' League format was to head
clubs with rebellion in their minds off at the pass, and when clubs like Milan,
Juventus, Barcelona, Real Madrid, Ajax, Bayern and Dortmund feel they want
more, they will threaten the establishment again. Murray, for one, remains
convinced a European super league will be in play        by the year 2000, or
soon after, and Scottish clubs will be recruited.
He is not saying they will be in the top division, but places in, say, a
northern league, could be awarded to the Old Firm and perhaps one or two other
Scottish clubs, who might meet the entry requirements.
UEFA cannot afford to allow their big clubs to get away, and they may be forced
to introduce their own super league to keep everyone satisfied. When they make
a decision, Scottish football will have to fall in       line. Perhaps the
members of the management committee should be aware of the wider picture when
they come to consider their own little problems today.
Above all, the main consideration should be the wellbeing of the game and its
development. Instead of talking about what sponsors or        individual clubs
might feel would suit them, everyone at the meeting should do what is best for
the game, and to my mind, that means a slightly larger top division with
ambitious clubs committed to improving standards of play.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Three vie for FIFA award</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BAYERN Munich's Jurgen Klinsmann and AC Milan team-mates Paolo Maldini and
George Weah are the candidates for FIFA's player of the year, soccer's world
body announced yesterday.
Some 100 national team coaches from around the world were polled for the
survey. The winner will be announced on January 8 in Milan during a gala
evening attended by FIFA president Joao Havelange.
Klinsmann has been scoring regularly for club and country since he returned to
Germany after a successful spell in England with Tottenham Hotspur.
Defender Maldini and striker Weah have been outstanding in Milan's revival in
Italy's Serie A this season. Liberian-born Weah is reported to have won the
prestigious Golden Boot award in a poll conducted by France Football magazine,
although an official announcement won't be made until December 26.
</TEXT>
