<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clinton and Republicans face off in budget crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN ,</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington Wednesday
TALKS on the budget crisis broke down today in a bitter dispute between
President Clinton and Republicans in Congress.
The outline agreement reached yesterday between the president and party leaders
was rejected by extremists in the House of Representatives, and a large part of
the federal government therefore remains closed for the sixth day.
Mr Clinton appeared in the White House press room to denounce his opponents:
``Yesterday, Speaker Gingrich, Senator Dole, and I reached an agreement to work
together in good faith to balance the budget and reopen the government,'' he
said.
``Today, the most extreme members of the House of Representatives rejected that
agreement.
``These Republicans want to force the government to stay closed until I accept
their deep and harmful cuts in Medicare and Medicaid, in education, in the
environment.''
He insisted: ``I won't yield to these threats. I'm determined to balance the
budget but I won't be forced to into signing a budget that violates our values,
not today, or tomorrow, nor ever.''
He claimed that ``a small minority of the House is determined to keep the
government closed until they get their way''.
He made a persuasive case of it, and the Republicans are in serious danger of
losing the whole debate on the budget.
Their leaders look suddenly weakened as they have lost control of their troops.
Senator Dole and Mr Gingrich were defied by their deputies earlier today, who
both said that they would not agree to providing the money to reopen the
government until the president accepted their budget terms.
When the president met Senator Dole and Mr Gingrich yesterday, the three agreed
on the outlines of negotiations that were to resume today. That meeting was
cancelled at the last moment, after members of Congress, chiefly newly-elected
ones, balked at the appearance of concessions by their own leaders.
The current game of chicken began in October, when Congress failed to pass both
the overall budget for the next seven years, and the Appropriations Bills that
would finance the 13 departments of government in the current financial year.
It passed a temporary measure, a ``continuing resolution'' to keep the
government funded, which expired in mid-November.
The government then closed for a week. Congress passed a new resolution,
providing funds for another month, and negotiations with the president were
meant to conclude a budget agreement in that time. Congress finally passed its
seven-year plan, and the president vetoed it. Congress also passed seven
Appropriations Bills, which the president signed, and three that he has vetoed.
So far, there has been no agreement, and the president has dug in his heels on
a few key issues while the Republicans continue to push for their version of a
balanced budget by 2002.
The current shut-down effects less than half the government. That means 280,000
civil servants are out of work.
They include most of the State Department, stranding Americans overseas who
need new passports or consular help. The Interior Department is also closed, so
national monuments like the Statue of Liberty, the parks like Yellowstone, and
the museums like the Smithsonian and the National Gallery are all closed.
If Mr Clinton succeeds in making his charges stick, he will deal a lethal blow
to his Republican rivals, making them look weaklings dominated by the
extremists in Congress. Those same extremists delight in the role, oblivious of
the harm they may do to the party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CALA gloomy about earnings prospects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CALA, the Edinburgh-based builder, warned yesterday that poor house sales in
the South-east of England and lower profit margins throughout the UK would
prevent any profits growth this year.
CALA shares plummeted 24p to 87p after the firm said pre-tax profits before
exceptional items would be similar to the #4.1m achieved in 1994-95.
CALA said trading had been weak since its annual results announcement in
September.
``In particular we have experienced low levels of visitors and sales
reservations in the south-east of England since mid-October and, as a result,
we expect unit sales for our operation in that area to fall short of budget for
the year to June 30, 1996,'' the company said.
South-east England generates about 40% of CALA sales, but operations there have
been running at a small loss for the last two years.
``We have been selling about half of what we would like to in the south,'' said
executive chairman Geoff Ball. ``November and December have been very poor.''
Business in the Midlands and Scotland remains satisfactory, but the cost of
offering part-exchange facilities to house buyers is eroding profit margins
everywhere.
Mr Ball said the part-exchange scheme was knocking about 1.5 percentage points
off CALA's usual 14% gross margin.
It is too early to say whether the bottom line will be boosted by any
exceptional items, after benefitting from a #2.8m exceptional profit on land
sales last year.
Despite the gloomy profits outlook, CALA expects to maintain the full-year
dividend at 3.2p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CalMac's hope in Sunday ferry poll</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CLEAR majority of the
people of Lewis and Harris still oppose the introduction of a Sunday ferry
service, but the idea finds favour with the younger islanders and some
churchgoers, according to a System Three Poll.
Caledonian MacBrayne's managing director, Mr Colin Paterson, said it confirmed
his view there would be a Sunday sailing some time, although not in the
immediate future.
The poll was conducted for BBC's Eorpa programme and its results will be
debated tonight.
The survey of 400 islanders showed 60% opposed the idea, 34% supported it, and
6% did not know. Among the under 44s there was a clear majority in favour. In
the 16-19 group, 48% were in favour, 39% against. In the 30-44 group, 52%
supported it with 45% opposed.
The different views do not divide neatly along lines of church attendance, with
29% of those who support the Sunday service attending church, while 31% of
those who oppose it are not churchgoers.
When asked why they opposed the service 40% said to ``keep Sunday special'';
37% because it would destroy the culture or way of life; 8% because it would
force people to work on the Sabbath; and 3% because other businesses would
open. There was also a range of reasons accounting for support: 43% giving need
to travel to work/family visits; 23% convenience; 10% as an emergency; and 8%
to help business/ tourism.
In 1989 CalMac introduced the first Sunday sailing to North Uist but the
Government intervened and the company abandoned plans to introduce one to
Harris in 1991 when it looked likely that local fishermen, with church backing,
would blockade Tarbert.
Mr Paterson said: ``There is clear demand for the service amongst those who are
most likely to travel, the younger islanders and eventually we will have take
note of that demand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Death row convict wins doctorate</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris, Wednesday
A FRENCH convict once on death row has won a doctorate cum laude in history
from Tours University with a brilliant study on family life in the 15th century.
Philippe Maurice, 39, whose death sentence was commuted to life imprisonment by
President Francois Mitterrand in 1981, went to the university in handcuffs on
Monday to receive the award.
The head of the university jury, Professor Bernard Chevalier, said that
Maurice's thesis - Family life in 15th-century Gevaudan, the archives of Lozere
solicitors 1380-1430 - was an exceptional work by any standard.
Maurice had been sentenced to death for killing a security guard and a
policeman. He later seriously wounded a prison warder.
After his sentence was commuted a few months before Mitterrand finally
abolished the guillotine in 1981, Maurice tried to strangle another prison
guard, bringing widespread criticism of the presidential pardon.
Chevalier, his professor of mediaeval history, said Maurice turned to study in
prison although he had no academic training.
In 12 years he went through secondary school and university curricula, writing
his thesis in prison from 22,000 folios of microfilmed archives sent by
regional authorities in central Lozere, his home region.
``Studying was the instrument of his own reconstruction,'' Chevalier said.
``This condemns the death penalty. No man is beyond redemption by
society.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crash kills woman and unborn child</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782596</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOCTORS at the Royal Infirmary, Glasgow, battled in vain for more than three
hours to save the lives of a woman and her unborn child yesterday after she was
seriously injured in a head-on crash between two cars.
The woman, who was nine months' pregnant, was a front-seat passenger in a car
being driven by her husband when the crash happened at an accident blackspot
near Summerston, Glasgow.
Strathclyde Police said the woman, Mrs Helen Howe, 32, of Bilsland Drive,
Ruchill, Glasgow, died from multiple injuries. The baby was stillborn.
The news was broken to her husband, Mr Charles Howe, 33, at the same hospital,
where he underwent an operation for serious leg injuries. He was later said to
be in a comfortable condition.
The couple's nine-year-old son James, who was a passenger in the rear seat of
the car, was also injured and taken to the same hospital before being
transferred to Yorkhill Hospital in Glasgow. He sustained a broken forearm.
The accident happened on a narrow stretch of Blackhill Road near to Blackhill
Farm Cottages, a row of three houses surrounded by fields on the edge of
Summerston.
One of the residents, Mrs Janet Monteith, 51, was among the first on the scene
and spoke yesterday of how she comforted Mr Howe while ambulance staff worked
on his wife.
``He was talking and asking what had happened and then told me that his wife
was pregnant and overdue.''
Fighting back the tears, Mrs Monteith added: ``I didn't realise just how
serious it was. His wife was just sitting as if in a trance. I didn't think she
was going to die. It's very, very sad.''
Police investigating the accident were yesterday searching for the driver of
the other car involved and said they were following a definite line of inquiry.
Mrs Howe was travelling in a Ford Fiesta being driven by her husband when it
was in collision with a Vauxhall Corsa car travelling in the opposite direction
at about 9.50pm on Tuesday.
It is believed that the couple had two other children, a girl of about 13 and a
boy of about 12.
A spokesman at the Royal Infirmary said yesterday: ``A medical team tried for
more than three hours to save Mrs Howe but, despite their best efforts, the
injuries she suffered were simply too grave.
``This is an absolutely tragic situation which has affected many people in the
hospital who are very shocked by it and our hearts go out to the family.''
The three male occupants of the other car were not being named by police for
operational reasons but two teenagers were traced and allowed home after
receiving hospital treatment.
Police declined to talk in detail about the incident yesterday and Chief
Inspector Alistair Anderson, the officer leading the inquiry, would say only
that it was a ``horrendous'' accident whose dreadful consequences were made
worse by the approach of Christmas.
Neighbours of the Howes, who live in a second-floor tenement flat overlooking
Ruchill Park, described them as a quiet family who kept themselves to
themselves.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What a lot of dosh for such a load of old tosh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Douglas Thompson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOUGLAS THOMPSON talks to Jim Carrey,
the man whose sense of humour took him from cleaning toilets to top dollars
HE IS all about figures including his own which he can turn into a wind tunnel
of contortions and thrust into outrageous situations. The other figures which
run into tens of millions of dollars have made Jim Carrey the toast - and livid
green envy - of all Hollywood - and the town's highest paid screen comic ever.
Ol' Rubber Face who used to clean toilets in Toronto's public lavatories goes
into 1996 as the star of the moment. His physical humour - a throwback to the
silent movies' slapstick set - is turning on giant audiences from teenagers to
veteran funnymen like Jerry Lewis to whom he is often compared - but this is a
new, wild and crazy guy. Well, wild maybe, but not so crazy. He has managers
and advisers but mostly he needs accountants and bankers.
``I went through periods when I had nothing, so somebody in my family had to
get stinkin' wealthy,'' says Carrey who is enjoying his fame - and fortune: ``I
refuse to feel guilty. I feel guilty about too much in my life but not about
money . . .''
You'll want to know the figures. His latest movie Ace Ventura: When Nature
Calls - it opens in Britain on Boxing Day - earned $37.8m in its first weekend
in America last month. Already it has easily overtaken the magic $100m mark.
It is Carrey's fifth box office blockbuster in a row. It began with the
original Ace Ventura: Pet Detective in the spring of last year - he was paid
$350,000 to play the title role - and then soared into orbit with The Mask,
Dumb and Dumber and this year's Batman Forever in which he played The Riddler
to Val Kilmer's Caped Crusader.
With each film his money increased by $1m to $2m increments. That was until
Cable Guy came along. He is being paid $20m to play a television cable
technician who ``terrorises'' Matthew Broderick. Next he's starring in Liar,
Liar as a pathologically dishonest single father who promises to tell the truth
to his son for 24 hours. It's another comedy - and another $20m. Is he worth it?
The man who has made his money out of laughs is serious: as much as anybody
else who brings that many people in. Movies nowadays make so much money with
all the tie-ins that a hit makes $300m overseas.
``The things in the Hollywood trade papers saying it's ruining the business is
basically the studios not wanting to pay the money.''
He says the cash bonanza is certainly not ruining his attitude: ``When the
first big pay-cheque with Dumb and Dumber hit I went, `Gosh I wonder if this
will affect my peformance. Will I do a take and think, was that worth $7m?' But
that never happened.
``If anything, it made me rebel against that thing when people who get rich
start playing safe. With Dumb and Dumber I put a bowl cut on my hair, took a
tooth off, went against the leading man star thing. It was a good test for me.
``The money - if I sit and think about it - is great. But if it's not good work
it's not going to be worth anything. I'm glued to my work - probably in an
unhealthy way.''
Of course, like all clowns, he wants to be taken seriously. Which brings us to
more figures. He is being paid $12m - his agent calls the fee ``low'' - to star
in The Truman Show. Its antecedents are promising. The director is Peter Weir
(Dead Poets Society, Witness) and the producer is the veteran Scott Rudin.
Carrey will appear as a New York insurance adjuster whose life veers off the
tracks. He says it's ``something more grounded in reality for me''.
But audiences go to see him for laughs, for movies like Ace Ventura: When
Nature Calls which is a lowbrow comedy which raises its sights when it goes for
the jokes about bodily functions. But no matter what the critics make of his
cerebrally challenged films, his audience just gets bigger and bigger. This
time he's back with his Hawaiian shirts and jet stream pompadour and trying to
make the world safe for animals in a cartoon Africa. It's tens of millions of
dollars of total tosh.
Will his fans love a ``reality'' Carrey? Can he move on to drama? ``I always
want to put a little humour in it. I'm not a James Dean guy but I see myself
more as a James Stewart character. There is a certain plan that has to happen.
``Can't bang them over the head with Shakespeare all of a sudden. People don't
like change. A lot of my stuff is dumb but there's smart stuff in there too.
I've been dubbed responsible for the dumbing of America.
``It's not up to me to educate America. I'm trying to give them relief. Ace
makes fun of the leading man and that's what I wanted to do.''
He's also always wanted to be a star. At 33, he's made it.
He began trying 16 years ago wearing yellow polyester and appearing at Yuk
Yuk's comedy club in Toronto, where he was born the youngest son of an
accountant.
When his father Percy, who died last year, lost his job, the family ended up
living in tents and working as a cleaning crew. His youngest son saw
showbusiness as his way out. He moved on from one set of stalls to another -
but his first stand-up comedy shows went down the toilet. Now he's worth
millions.
``That's always been my pattern. I try something, totally suck, go away, come
back and I totally kill.''
In between there were the comedy clubs, a couple of television and movie tries
and marriage in 1987. He was divorced from his wife Melissa this year (he now
lives with actress Lauren Holly who worked with him on Dumb and Dumber). His
former wife revealed another side of the usually publicly smiling tall
``funniest man in America''. She was going through their divorce when she said:
``Jim is an extremely depressive person. I would sit up counselling him through
it until four or five in the morning on many, many nights.''
Her former husband's reaction without explanation is simply: ``She's lucky to
be out of my life.''
Actress Courtney Cox who co-starred with him in the original Ace says: ``There
are two Jims but not a terribly dark one. He has a very serious side. He did
have a hard time and he is very sensitive and there's definitely a deep side.
But it's that way with all comedians. Jim couldn't be that funny without the
pain on the other side.''
During one of the difficult ``painful'' periods in 1987 Jim Carrey took a drive
up Mulholland Avenue which has spectacular Tinseltown views of Hollywood.
In one of those silly dream moments he wrote a cheque to himself. It was
post-dated November 23, 1995. It was for $10m. For once he got his figure
wrong. By then he was the $20m man.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
