<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Exports rise 9% to record level</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE UK'S visible trade with non-European Union countries enjoyed a significant
improvement in November, with the deficit narrowing to #496m, down from
October's #1183m and less than market projections of around #950m.
Exports rose 9% over the month to a record #5777m while imports dipped 3% to
#6273m, taken as an indication that manufacturers are no longer rebuilding
stocks but will meet demand from their shelves. This helped the pound to
strengthen a little against the mark. It was also in line with a relatively
firm dollar.
About half the rise in exports was due to erratic items, mainly the export of a
warship to Saudi Arabia. But after excluding oil and erratics - the gap still
fell from #962m to #525m.
On the same basis, exports rose 6.6% in the three months to November and
imports by 5.9%.
The Treasury said: ``Strong growth in export volumes is contributing to
narrowing in non-EU-visible trade deficit.''
However, the Central Statistical Office makes the point that the pattern of the
deficit over the last three months has been erratic, making estimation of the
trend particularly difficult. Bearing this in mind, the addition of the
November figures has led to a flattening in the estimate of the latest trend,
with exports rising faster than imports.
James Capel's Adam Cole considers that the most encouraging aspect of the
November trade data was the sharp fall in imports - the first significant
evidence that manufacturers have stopped rebuilding stocks. The trend in
exports remains surprisingly good, but it is thought unlikely to be mirrored in
trade with the EU countries when data becomes available.
</TEXT>
