<HEADLINE>Famous name returns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sally Thomson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<FLAG>Advertising Feature</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE name Balbir (as every devotee of Indian food will know) is practically
synonymous with curry in this city, and with Indian cuisine of the highest
standard. Balbir's first restaurant was the legendary Ashoka in Argyle Street
which he opened in 1973. Almost a decade later he bought a restaurant in
Elderslie Street, changed its name to Ashoka Tandoori, and for the first time
introduced a lot of Punjabi and other regional dishes from the Indian
sub-continent, to Glasgow.
The Ashoka Vegetarian across the road was a logical step forward, and Balbir's
huge success resulted in a lot of other Indian restaurants up-grading their
cuisines. Glasgow is now without doubt the ``curry capital of Europe'' boasting
more ``quality'' Indian restaurants than any city outside India.
It was a sad day for fans when Balbir decided to sell up in order to spend more
time with his family, because although the name remained, the standard was not
quite as he'd have liked it. However, after a short break, he was back in
action with a new restaurant, Ali Baba's Balti Bar in town, and just three
weeks ago, in the heart of Partick, he opened Balbir's Balti &amp; Dosa House in
Hyndland Street, for the convenience and gastronomic delight of a West End
clientele which likes to have good food on the doorstep.
You will find that dining in the Balti &amp; Dosa House is superb value, as well
as being a tremendously satisfying gastronomic experience.
For the uninitiated, ``balti'' means, literally, ``bucket'' and is in fact the
Birmingham version of the ``karahi'' or Chinese wok.
As for dosas, Glaswegians probably first tasted these in the Vegetarian Ashoka
(1987-92). The dosa is a South Indian crepe made with ground rice and daal.
Scrumptious! But the range is now extended for non-vegetarians too, and
includes an exciting variety of meat and fish. As you might imagine though, the
vegetarian menu at the Balti &amp; Dosa House is more extensive than in other
restaurants, considering Balbir's credentials in that department.
The restaurant is at the bottom of Hyndland Street (No. 11/13) close to
Dumbarton Road, and is particularly handy for Hyndland and Partick residents.
But it's well worth making a special trip from further afield not only to
sample Balbir's excellent cuisine, but because the parking is so easy. Balbir's
also have a home delivery service (5pm-11pm, no charge for delivery).
</TEXT>
