<DOCNO>GH951221-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forte's US chain sells for #108m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Sims</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORTE has sold its Travelodge chain in the US for #108m - a little more than
had been expected - and the deal brings total receipts in its disposals
programme to #1100m, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
The latest sale does not represent a scorched earth policy, as the business was
put up for sale in September, well before the Granada bid.
The transaction followed a competitive auction process which was won by a
consortium led by HSF Incorporated, one of the US's largest budget hotel
franchising companies, with brands such as Ramada and Howard Johnson.
It will have exclusive right to the Travelodge name in North America and
Mexico. Forte is retaining the right in the UK, Continental Europe and most
other areas.
Travelodge has not been Forte's best performer but finance director Keith
Hamill attributed the satisfactory price obtained to the hard work put into
improving the performance of the business.
The money will go towards reducing debt and funding capital investment and
acquisitions to develop the core interests.
The disposal progamme has included a variety of transactions this year, ranging
from the sale of the remaining stake in Gardner Merchant and the Harvester pub
chain to odd hotels in Spain and Ireland, and Lillywhites, the sports equipment
retailer.
Forte is also trying to sell 60 of the 72-strong chain of White Hart hotels in
the UK and there are two possible buyers, but the sale has hit snags and may
not be completed.
Granada has attacked Forte for continuing with disposals while the subject of a
bid because potential buyers will press for a lower price as a result.
In another development yesterday, the High Court confirmed that the Council of
Forte was entitled to retain or sell its shares as it might think fit. Run by
eight trustees, the council has just 0.08% of the shares but effectively
controls half the votes.
</TEXT>
