<DOCNO>GH951221-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ree drinks blamed for mid-air mayhem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FAMILY caught up in a violent disturbance on a transatlantic flight yesterday
arrived back in London, and criticised the airline for handing out free drinks.
Northwest Airlines had said drunken British and Irish tourists wreaked havoc on
the flight from Gatwick to Los Angeles on Monday until the worst offenders were
tamed by American Olympic wrestlers and handcuffed to their seats.
Seventeen people from three families - ranging from men in their 60s to
children as young as two - were taken off the plane at Minneapolis and
arrangements made to return them home, said airline spokesman Doug Killian.
An 18th person, Michael Purcell, 25, was remanded in custody in the US on
charges of assaulting and intimidating a crew member and flight attendant.
The airline claimed the families began throwing food, shouting and swearing
when flight attendants refused to serve them more alcohol.
However, one of the families returned to Gatwick yesterday and insisted they
had been treated unfairly.
Grandmother Eileen Cash, from Kilburn, north London, said: ``We were going on
holiday, and feel ashamed and embarrassed over it but we never did anything.
``They gave us drink on the plane, they shouldn't have.''
</TEXT>
