<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nigerian given present of his freedom</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON and CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NIGERIAN asylum seeker Peter Nwokoye was freed from Saughton Prison yesterday
to celebrate his first Christmas with his wife Tracy at their Edinburgh home.
Mr Nwokoye, 35, who has spent the past six months in jail awaiting judicial
review of the Home Office refusal to allow political asylum, said: ``I just
thank God I am free. I have never been in jail before and, although some people
were kind, it was a really horrible experience.''
Lord Milligan ordered his interim liberation at the Court of Session until the
judicial review hearing, on condition that #1000 was lodged as security and he
reported to police three times a week.
Mr Nwokoye fears political persecution if he is sent back to Ogoniland, a
homeland he shared with Nobel Peace Prize nominee Ken Saro-Wiwa, whose
execution by the Nigerian authorities shocked the world. According to
television reports, Mr Nwokoye's home village has been razed to the ground.
Mr Nwokoye, who arrived in the UK in 1991, studied at Stevenson College and met
Tracy, 26, a bank clerk, at a disco.
He had wished to train to become a minister, but was unable to obtain the
necessary extension to stay here. The couple were married in September at an
Edinburgh registry office.
``She came in every day to see me in prison, and all the family have been very
supportive. I am so happy to be out and going home with my wife for Christmas''
he said.
Mrs Nwokoye said: ``I am just delighted that he is out.''
The couple, whose home is in the Dalry area of Edinburgh, are now awaiting the
judicial review which could take a six months before coming to court.
A Home Office spokesman said he could not comment on specific cases, but powers
to detain under the Immigration Act were not exercised lightly and only used in
a small minority of cases.
</TEXT>
