<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why there's not a ghost of a chance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Features</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT HAD been a long week; the fishing vote had been lost and the men in the
white coats had still not come to collect the Eurosceptics; the Lottery
regulator was warned to keep away from airports, Mr David Ashby from double
beds, and rail privatisation was proving about as popular as the flu virus. The
Prime Minister took a deep slug of his cocoa and his eyelids became very heavy
. . .
A handbag bashed into his left ear. ``Pull yourself together man. I didn't get
where I am today - able to command #25,000 for a single, boring speech - by
sitting sleeping in the chair.'' It was the Ghost of Christmas Past.
``Oh no, when I was in power I hardly slept at all and neither did anyone else.
Sent doddering old Foot back to walking his dogs, punctured the Welsh windbag,
destroyed the Argies, smashed the unions, and that was all before lunch.
Rejoice, I cried, and people did.''
Cried or rejoiced, wondered the PM, silently. He attempted a defence. ``In your
day, Maggie, we had big majorities, the Whips could put the fear of God into
them, threaten to have them deselected. Now they are deselecting themselves in
huge numbers, scared to stand again.''
``Bah, humbug!'' came the riposte, ``it is not about the size of your majority,
it is about leadership, the firm smack of government, the pleasure of power. If
you don't pull your socks up and get stuck into Pretty Boy Blair you are going
to be an ex before your time.
``Think of the miners' strike, think of Wapping, think of Goose Green, remember
the poll tax - well, maybe not - and remember I picked you as my successor. And
I don't like losers.'' There was time for one more blow with the bag and she
was off.
The PM tried another snooze but a blast of cold air troubled him and he awoke
to face a tall man with a long nose and a permanently sneering expression.
``You are not trying to tell us you are doing well, are you? demanded the
visitor. It was the Ghost of Christmas Present.
This time the PM was not going to give in without a fight. ``Just you hang on a
minute, Jeremy (Paxman), I am the leader who is always being written off but
keeps going. Oh, yes.
``Who else could have achieved 16 months of peace in Northern Ireland? Who was
it who persuaded President Clinton to send troops to Bosnia? Who faced up to
his critics by resigning and then got elected again?''
The ghost's lip curled: ``Who else could lead a party 30 points behind in the
opinion polls? Who else could manage to make the public so hostile to the
Tories when there is good news to tell? When are you going to quit, give Tony
his rightful place, let John and Gordon and all the other talents on the
Opposition benches have a go at facing me?''
``Never!'' The PM was becoming quite animated now. ``Just wait until the
interest rate cut starts to filter through, until they have had my next round
of tax cuts, when their mortgage payments fall, then they will all come back.
``Mr Blair will not be able to hide the cost of his policies forever. I shall
expose them, tell the people that his devolution proposals will lead to the
break-up of the United Kingdom. I will give them a triple whammy . . .''
The ghost held up his hand. ``I'm sorry - that is all we have time for tonight.
I would like to thank me for coming and wish me and all my fans a Merry
Christmas.''
The PM was left wrestling with the sheets again.
Could things become any worse? Could there be another dry summer in Yorkshire?
Could Cedric Brown be given a #1m pay rise? Will we discover we have sold
British Rail to Colombian drug barons? He bit his lip.
The Ghost of Chrismas Yet To Come smiled. ``Did I tell you about the time I was
captain of the R and A and lost all my balls? Most people thought it had
happened years ago.'' His big frame heaved with mirth.
``Willie,'' gasped the PM, ``is it you, Willie?'' ``Yes, it's me, old boy, not
pushin' up the daisies quite yet. Still time for a few noggins and a bit of
advice like I used to give to Herself. But first I have to show you what could
happen to you if you do not change course.''
He grasped the PM by the hand and they soared away together over the rooftops
of London. They came to rest in a large chamber with red seats.
``This is what awaits you, PM, a seat in the old Lords' home. You can find a
place between Buffy and Bunter - both deaf as goalposts so it won't matter what
you say. Grub's not bad, drink cheap, but Gawd, it's really boring.''
``Must I be confined to this awful place, Willie?'' ``Perhaps not. Look here -
you are just a slip of a lad, really, not even 60, Winnie was still in the
wilderness at your age. Plenty of time for a comeback - know what I mean?'' ``I
should give up?'' ``Yep, for the moment. Resign. Say you want a break. Want to
retire as undefeated champion. Handin' it over to Heseltine.''
``But you always said you could not trust Heseltine.''
``Who needs to trust him? He will galvanise the troops, put the boot into
Blair, resign from the European Union if he thinks there are votes in it, bring
back hangin' and floggin' and that's just in schools. In the meantime, as old
Charlie de Gaulle used to say, you wait.''
``But I just don't understand, Willie, if I hand over to Hezza and he is
victorious how does that help me to make a come-back?'' The old ghost grinned.
``Did I say anything about winning, John? Ghosts are not into miracles.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Girl dies in third suicide attempt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 16-YEAR-OLD girl killed herself yesterday, only days after two previous
suicide bids failed.
Miss Jessica O'Riordan was persuaded not to jump from a river bridge on Monday.
Later that day she survived leaping in front of a train. She was allowed home
after seeing a doctor. Yesterday she died when she jumped from a fourth-floor
fire escape at a hotel.
Miss O'Riordan, who lived with her social worker mother and two older sisters
at Brockenhurst, Hampshire, had attended a concert hours earlier by the band,
Pulp, in Bournemouth, with a 19-year-old friend, Miss Sally Smith.
The teenagers had been spotted by a policewoman sitting on the edge of the
Itchen Bridge in Southampton on Monday evening.
Later that evening they went to Southampton rail station, where Miss O'Riordan
jumped in front of a train. She landed between the tracks and escaped unhurt.
Yesterday the two girls climbed up to the fourth floor at Marsham Court Hotel,
in Grove Road, Bournemouth.
Staff heard screams and ran outside to see Miss Smith, hysterical, at the top
of the fire escape and her friend's body on the ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lord Jacques of Portsea Island</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lord Jacques of Portsea Island, born January 11, 1905, died December 20, 1995
LORD Jacques of Portsea Island, who died yesterday, started his working life as
a teenage miner and then a grocery apprentice and rose to become a Government
whip and deputy speaker of the House of Lords. He was 90.
Virtually his entire working life was associated with the Cooperative movement
and he was elected President of the Co-operative Congress in 1961. He also
served as chairman of the Co-operative Union.
Lord Jacques, a Labour life peer, entered the House of Lords in 1968. He twice
served as a Government whip, first between 1974 and 1977.
Then, early in 1979, only a day before his 74th birthday, he was reappointed a
Government whip, an indication of the difficulty the then Prime Minister, now
Lord Callaghan, was having in filling junior posts in the House of Lords.
He served as deputy speaker in the Lords from 1978 to 1985. Lord Jacques was
last seen in the Lords as recently as last month for the State Opening of
Parliament.
His service to the Co-operative movement was probably unrivalled. He was, in
fact, known as Mr Co-op for many years.
After working as a miner, John Jacques became a grocery apprentice at the
Co-operative Society at Ashington, Northumberland, near his birthplace.
He spent 20 years as chief officer of the Portsea Island Society, raising
turnover from #2m to #22.6m and paying his 200,000 members in the Portsmouth
area a regular dividend of 1s 6d in the #1.
And he was the man behind the ambitious regional plan to group the 467 retail
societies into 50 regional trading units.
His colleague, Lord Graham of Edmonton, said yesterday: ``He was the Mr
Reliable and never ever let down either the Co-operative Movement or the Labour
Party. His record as the eminence of the Portsea Island Cooperative was
unrivalled.''
Lord Jacques, whose first wife Constance died in 1987, is survived by a widow,
Violet, two sons and a daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kelso in the deep freeze</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOPES of racing at Kelso this afternoon were frozen solid yesterday and the
Border track's stewards called off the fixture because of frost.
After having inspected the track, clerk of the course Johnny Fenwick-Clennell
said: ``It was frozen solid. We had no problems early this morning but things
have got worse through the day.
``The forecast is for sub-zero temperatures and with racing scheduled to start
at 12.20, we have no chance of going ahead.''
But punters should not fret because hopes are high that Lingfield and Uttoxeter
will survive to provide a final chance of action before a three-day yuletide
break in the fixture list.
Clerk of the course David McAllister was ``cautiously optimistic'' that today's
meeting at Uttoxeter will go ahead. ``We had half an inch of rain last night
and the forecast is a mixed bag,'' he said.
The cold snap is threatening next week's action. Ayr, due to race on Boxing
Day, and Edinburgh, where a meeting is planned the following day, were frozen
yesterday.
Manager Mark Kershaw said: ``We have had quite a lot of frost and we look set
for a severe frost tonight. No inspections are arranged yet but we will be
making plans as we get nearer the weekend.''
q TRAINER Jonjo O'Neill was fined #400 and jockey Alan Roche suspended for
seven days for schooling and conditioning Princess Maxine in public at Hexham
yesterday.
The mare looked tenderly-handled when staying on to finish fifth in the
novices' hurdle. Roche told officials that his instructions had been to ensure
that she got the trip.
O'Neill said he was satsified with Roche's riding, although he would have
preferred him to have had the horse in a more prominent position coming down
the hill in the back straight.
However, one trainer with a large smile on his face at the course was Steve
Kettlewell, whose late gamble on Easby Joker paid dividends.
The gelding wrapped up his third success from four outings this season with a
comfortable defeat of Lupy Minstrel in the Santa Claus Chase.
q MASTER Oats, the Cheltenham Gold Cup winner, has been withdrawn from
Wednesday's Welsh National at Chepstow.
Kim Bailey's gelding, pulled up in the Rehearsal Chase on the same course on
his reappearance, now will go for the Ericsson Chase at Leopardstown the
following day.
Without Master Oats, Miinnehoma has been left to shoulder top-weight of 11st
7lb in the Welsh marathon. The 1994 Grand National winner has been the main
market mover and is now a 10-1 chance from 16-1 earlier in the week.
</TEXT>
