<HEADLINE>Council drops case against Lanark Blue</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLYDESDALE District Council environmental health committee announced yesterday
that it would take no further court action against Lanark Blue cheese-maker
Humphrey Errington.
The council faces a legal bill of #350,000 spent in pursuit of the Dunsyre
cheese-maker, one year after ordering 44 batches of his soft cheese destroyed
because of alleged listeria contamination.
The council's statement reiterated the case it had put before Sheriff John
Allan at Lanark Sheriff Court, and regretted that the sheriff had not accepted
its evidence.
In his judgment, Sheriff Allan had said the cheese was not unfit to eat and
refused the council's request that #27,000 worth of it should be destroyed. He
was also critical of the environmental health office's ``combative and
confrontational manner''.
In a statement following the in camera meeting at the council's Lanark
headquarters, department director Duncan McDougall said: ``The committee
totally rejects the criticism of the district council staff and fully supports
the action taken by staff who followed nationally agreed guidelines throughout
the case.''
The council, he said, had consulted a great many experts before taking action
against Mr Errington: ``These experts presented the overwhelming opinion of the
medical and microbiological professions that such gross contamination of the
food rendered it unfit for human consumption.''
The sheriff's decision, he said, therefore appeared to be contrary to expert
microbiological and medical opinion.
``However, it is not the intention of the council to take any further legal
action in respect of the case, but the matter shall be pursued with the
appropriate bodies, including Cosla, the Scottish Office, and the medical and
microbiological authorities.''
Mr Errington had a mixed reaction to the statement.
``I'm very relieved they are not going to take any further action,'' he said.
``It would have cost us a lot more money to defend ourselves in the Court of
Session.
``Looking at the statement it's difficult to know what to say because some of
the statements are totally untrue. It's a partial account of events.
``Our lawyers are beginning to draft a complaint to the Local Authority
Ombudsman. It seems to be the only way to achieve an inquiry into this.
``If the council would do it themselves I wouldn't need to bother. Our case is
that there has been severe maladministration.''
Mr Errington said he was taking legal advice about suing Clydesdale for his
#120,000 court costs.
Mr Fergus Ewing, SNP business spokesman, said last night: ``What must happen
now is that Mr Errington should receive his legal costs and compensation.
Clydesdale District nearly bankrupted Mr Errington. They lost the case.
``They appear unable to accept defeat. Apparently to their way of thinking even
the sheriff was wrong. Isn't it unbelievable that the councillors condemn the
judgment of the sheriff when none of them bothered to turn up to hear a word of
evidence in the 19 days of the hearing?''
</TEXT>
