<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Features</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WAS the lie, not the lifestyle, that ruined David Ashby. After the grotesque
libel case which, it must be confessed, added enormously to the gaiety of the
nation, here is a man humiliated and weeping. This is not to gloat, well not
much.
It's hard not to feel something for a man broken on the wheel of hubris, even
one whose ego, matched for monstrosity only by his seriously weird wife, led
him to gamble all for his sexuality.
Maybe he thought the stakes were worth the enormous risk. Perhaps if he'd let
the Sunday Times story pass and quietly forgotten his legal action he could
have blustered on with his life. Instead, he staked all on opening up the
shaming family secrets to a raucous public.
Oh how we all chortled over the Christmas Eve row, when his wife was chanting
``poofters, poofters'' through the letterbox. Who can forget, we asked, wiping
our eyes, the couple wrestling each other to the ground, firing off bilious and
spittle-flecked salvoes of contempt while attempting a half-nelson 'neath the
festive mantelpiece?
What a merry image that was, of Silvana teetering round his study on her peery
heels peeling off the wallpaper with bare nails. Such a giggle when she claimed
to have learned her bad language from Channel 4. What a laugh, eh? Of course we
can mock. Why not? It was Mr Ashby, after all, who chose to expose the entire
cast in this steamy satire on a Greek tragedy to public hilarity. (Interesting
to note, don't you think, that the word tragedy derives from the Greek for
goat?).
What? You think I'm being unseasonally cruel? Well, look at it this way. Do you
think Mr Ashby expected to get away with preaching the importance of family
values, as he did in his election literature, to carry on spouting
double-standards, one morality for us MPs, and another for them feckless poor,
while leaving his wife in the circumstances we have read about?
Mr Ashby needs to grasp that, despite the best efforts of the homophobic
tabloids, people can and do put up with, forgive, even admire the courage of
people who take the honest but hard decision to come out as gay - Michael
Barrymore, Chris Smith MP, former Tory MP Matthew Parris. What they won't
tolerate is arrogant hypocrisy. It was the cant the jury rumbled in Mr Ashby's
case.
Although the case is over the hypocrisy won't go away. It seems now that senior
party figures are rallying round, trying to salvage Mr Ashby's perilous
financial state. Michael Heseltine and millionaire peer Lord Archer - just the
man don't you think to offer consolation? - are tipped as those to pass the top
hat round. It would be heartwarming to report that their concern is for a man
down on his luck at Christmas.
It wouldn't be true though. If there is a whip-round to raise half a million to
stave off Mr Ashby's bankrupcy, it won't be to salvage his brass neck, rather
it will be to save their own thick skins.
If Mr Ashby is bankrupted he can't continue as an MP. It would shave another
wafer off a transparently thin majority of two. Think about it. Only one MP -
and envision all those doddering, sickly looking old buffers with pacemakers
stumbling about on the backbenches - would then stand in the way of a general
election.
If one positive thing could be salvaged from this whole gruesome tale it would
be to still the sermonising of the high-Tory-muck-a-mucks. What joy no more to
hear the preachings of those smug, purse-lipped inhabitants of the moral high
ground who rejoice in pontificating about the superiority of the traditional
family unit, shaped in their own image, over any other.
By virtue of my education and career I may have achieved a middle class gloss.
But my early allegiances return with a vengeance when I hear some Tory gasbag
spouting heartless nonsense which equates poverty and single parents with moral
failure, compounded by the bone-headed brutality that denigrates any variant on
the nuclear family.
How much self esteem can the children of single parents have when they are
constantly called a social problem?
Dysfunctional? The Ashbys make the Buck House Windsors seem like positive role
models of emotional health and familial stability.
So I'll drop my scorn and offer seasonal goodwill to fallen Tories when they
stop blaming poverty on the poor and acknowledge their own moral obligation in
its spread. That might take a miracle. But it is Christmas.
</TEXT>
