<HEADLINE>Loyalist politician jailed for 10 years Gang convicted of conspiracy to run guns to UVF</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOYALIST politician Lindsay Robb, a peace negotiator for the Progressive
Unionist Party while a member of the outlawed Ulster Volunteer Force, was
jailed for 10 years at the High Court in Edinburgh yesterday for conspiracy to
acquire and run guns to the UVF in Northern Ireland.
Two of his Scottish followers, John Johnston, of Campbell Crescent, Laurieston,
Falkirk, and William McArthur, of Ure Crescent, Bonnybridge, who were also
convicted of conspiracy after trial in Glasgow, were jailed for 10 and eight
years respectively.
Other members of the group, loyalist sympathisers from central Scotland who
were caught in a police and MI5 operation, and a Liverpool publican who stored
a handgun and a machine pistol for them, received shorter sentences from Lord
Sutherland.
The judge told the gang: ``Northern Ireland has enough troubles of its own
without interference of a deadly kind from anyone else outside.
``At a time when all sensible people are seeking peace in this unhappy province
it must be made clear that attempts to enlarge the arsenals of paramilitary
sectarian forces cannot be tolerated and the sentences to be passed must
reflect that fact.''
As he was led from court, Robb shouted defiantly: ``Up the UVF.'' A small group
of republican demonstrators chanted ``Free Colin Duffy,'' a reference to the
part Robb played in the jailing for life of an IRA murderer in July. Robb was a
witness to the killing of a former UDR officer in Lurgan, his home town, but
was allowed to give evidence anonymously by the Crown.
It was claimed yesterday that Robb, 28, told that trial he had no knowledge of
links between the Progressive Unionists and the UVF and that he condemned
violence. The demonstrators said yesterday that the trial judge in Northern
Ireland had commended Robb, by then a PUP peace negotiator, for the
impartiality, honesty, and credibility of his evidence.
The PUP said yesterday that it had had observers present throughout the trial
in Glasgow who had expressed concern at the ``concealed MI5 witnesses, the
dubious evidence that was allowed to be presented which prejudiced the minds of
the jury and Mr Robb's case''.
Members claimed there was no direct evidence to connect Robb to any offence and
said there would be an appeal against the conviction.
Earlier, Mr Donald Findlay, QC for Robb, said that his client continued to deny
that he had had any involvement in obtaining guns.
The group was arrested in a armed swoop in an Airdrie street.
Johnston, who received concurrent sentences totalling 11 years for other
offences, was said in court yesterday to still dispute he was a UVF member.
Publican Francis Hives, 45, was said by his counsel, Mr Charles Boag-Thompson,
QC, to have lost everything he had ever worked for. Hives had insisted there
were to be no gun deals within his premises. He had been swept along by events.
However, Lord Sutherland said that Hives had played a material part and jailed
him for five years.
William McArthur, 41, of Bonnybridge, was said by the judge also to have been
convicted of conspiracy but, although playing a lesser part than Johnston, he
still had been a major force. He was jailed for eight years for conspiracy and
received lesser concurrent terms for the other offences.
Lord Sutherland accepted that David White, 29, of Northburn Avenue, Airdrie, a
taxi driver, had played a lesser part in collecting the weapons and he jailed
him for five years for possession of the two guns with two lesser, concurrent
sentences on other charges.
Alexander Davidson, 23, who was found guilty of possessing two bullets at the
Seacat terminal in Stranraer, was jailed for two years.
</TEXT>
