<HEADLINE>Money supply figures hint at housing upturn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE depressed housing market received a boost yesterday from the M4 money
supply, the wider monetary aggregate taking in bank and building society
lending and deposits, as well as from building societies' own lending figures
for the month.
Money supply grew by 1% in November to give a year-on-year increase of 9.3%,
topping the Government's 3% to 9% monitoring range for the first time.
The figures provided some encouragement that the housing market was at last
showing signs of moving. This was supported by the Building Societies
Association's own mortgage figures for the month which revealed a sharp upturn
in net lending to #865m from just #295m in October.
Actual M4 bank/building society lending rose #3400m in the month.
City economists were playing down the rate of expansion in M4, pointing out
that the strong growth was caused in part by under-funding of the public sector
borrowing requirement (PSBR). During the course of a financial year this
influence should unwind.
Goldman Sachs' economist Martin Brookes said that although M4 growth picked up
strongly throughout this year, in coming months slower M4 and M0, the narrow
definition, should add to other data evidence of easing inflationary pressures.
Meanwhile, the Building Societies Association reports that, aside from net
lending, gross mortgage lending rose from #2624m to #2947m in November, while
net new commitments were also substantially ahead of October at #3216m, up from
#2887m.
Adrian Coles, director-general of the Building Societies Association,
commented: ``While this strong increase may well represent increased building
society share, it is also to be hoped that it signals the start of a modest
recovery.
``The unilateral action by building societies to reduce mortgage rates,
followed by a further reduction after the fall in base rates last Wednesday,
means mortgage costs are at their lowest level since 1968. With tax cuts in the
pipeline, prospects for a modest recovery in the mortgage market in 1996 are
good.''
The British Bankers' Association reported buoyant credit demand in November.
While consumer credit fell back its October record, mortgage lending was higher
at some #700m.
</TEXT>
