<HEADLINE>Nato takes up mission in Bosnia `We are not here as cowboys looking for a fight' - Admiral Leighton Smith</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Wednesday
NATO took over the peacekeeping baton from the UN today after a shaky handover
and moved quickly to sweep away key roadblocks in Sarajevo and put the first
British troops in Serb-held areas.
Nato commander Admiral Leighton Smith formally took overall command of a
60,000-strong force to police a Bosnia peace treaty and insisted: ``We are not
here as cowboys looking for a fight.''
However he also made it clear that his forces had clear instructions to use
their awesome firepower if they felt threatened.
The day started badly for Nato's much-heralded mission as fog prevented Smith
from landing in Sarajevo for the handover, bringing wry smiles from UN
officials who have been a butt of endless criticism for their performance
during the war.
Nevertheless Nato quickly got into its stride after the change of control was
done without ceremony but on schedule, at 10am. Troops moved at once to
dismantle two Serb roadlblocks on the main road to Sarajevo's airport, which
has been closed for much of the war.
Shortly afterwards British forces pushed across a former front line in Bosnia
to become the first foreign fighting unit to be stationed on Serb-held
territory.
They were welcomed by local Serbs who offered them glasses of home-made spirits.
``We will accept any friends who will help to end this war,'' one Bosnian Serb
soldier said. ``This is the best moment in four years of war.''
Some 60,000 troops with heavy equipment and backed by formidable air power and
an array of spy satellites will fan out across Bosnia in the coming weeks as
the world's most powerful military alliance ensures that Bosnia's warring
parties implement last week's Paris peace treaty.
Meanwhile, American generals deployed in Bosnia and neighbouring Croatia linked
up for the first time today across the Sava river which separates the two
countries.
And an advance party of Russian troops arrived at the main US base at Tuzla,
bringing them together with American soldiers in a potential combat zone for
the first time in 50 years.
``I don't know what to think,'' said Craig Johnson, a member of the US team
flown into Tuzla to take over the base from Swedish UN troops.
``They have trained us and trained us back in the States that the Russians are
the enemy. Well, now they're no longer the enemy,'' he said with a laugh.
Russia, not a Nato member but worried that it has lost Soviet-era superpower
clout in foreign affairs, agreed to send 2000 combat troops and 2000 support
staff to join the 20,000 American Nato soldiers based at Tuzla.
Despite the arrival of the advance party, Russia's role in the multi-national
peacekeeping operation is still being discussed.
``They are waiting for a political decision from Moscow to see whether to join
the Nato force or not,'' said a Nato press officer.
``If they get a positive answer, the Russian contingent will be a brigade-sized
unit with three battalions. Its task will be the same as that of Ifor and they
will be working under US troops and not separately at all.''
In Sarajevo, Bosnian Serbs, who have been the most resistant to the peace deal
because it will mean their suburbs of the city returning to government control,
were resigned to the arrival of a Nato force they see as an occupying army.
``They won't protect us. They've been fighting against us since the beginning.
But what can we do?'' said Janja Mandic, a 49-year-old woman in the Serb-held
district of Grbavica as she carried home an aid package of canned meat.
In Washington, the International Monetary Fund said that it had approved
Bosnia's membership and granted the war-ravaged country an emergency #30m
credit.
q.A German sailor died today in an accident on a frigate helping to enforce the
arms embargo against the former Yugoslavia. Steffen Behrens, 25, was the first
casualty in Germany's Balkan deployment, the first combat role undertaken by
the country's post-war armed forces.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
