<HEADLINE>Chernobyl aid pledged</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>Foreign Digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Chernobyl
aid pledged
OTTAWA: Ukraine and the G7 industrial democracies yesterday signed an agreement
on the closure of the Chernobyl nuclear power station, nearly a decade after
the world's worst nuclear accident.
The memorandum of understanding involves #1533m in aid from the G7 to support
the closure of the Chernobyl power plant by the year 2000.
Plane skids
NEW YORK: Kennedy International Airport was closed for four hours last night
and 45 flights from Europe were diverted after a Tower Air Boeing 747 skidded
off a runway while taking off in a snowstorm, injuring 12 people.
Dinosaur riddle
MIAMI: One of the world's most sophisticated research ships is set to sail from
Miami this week, seeking proof for a theory that the dinosaurs were killed off
by a cataclysmic explosion when an asteroid or comet smashed into Earth 65
million years ago and radically changed the environment. Scientists will drill
into the Earth's crust near the site of a giant crater seeking the answers to
the riddle of what killed the beasts.
Star `was eclipse'
NEW YORK: The three Wise Men who travelled to Bethlehem to see the new-born
Jesus were attracted to Israel by a double eclipse of Jupiter and not, as the
New Testament says, by a dazzling star, a US astronomer claims. Michael Molnar
linked astronomical events at the time of Christ's birth to astrological
symbolism on Roman coins to help him formulate his startling claim, published
in the New Scientist.
Shutdown urged
TOKYO: Calls for Japan's nuclear reactor to be closed down increased yesterday
when nuclear bosses admitted they had lied about film footage showing a serious
accident 12 days at the plutonium-fuelled Monju plant.
Miro vandalised
BRASILIA: A Brazilian artist desperate to promote his own work vandalised a
##fm painting by Spain's Joan Miro. Janr Reis, 27, told he slapped a handprint
of black glue on Miro's Women in the Street at a Rio exhibition because he had
could not sell his own paintings.
Soldiers plea
NAIROBI: Yemen urged Eritrea to free nearly 200 Yemeni soldiers captured last
weekend during fighting on a disputed island in the Red Sea. Eritrea had
pledged to release them two days previously.
Jail a monument
PRETORIA: South Africa yesterday declared Robben Island, the prison where
President Nelson Mandela was locked up for 18 years, a national monument.
Junior mafiosi
BARI: Four teenagers, two aged 14 and the others 17, have been arrested for
running a Mafia clan. They are suspected of the attempted murder of another
minor, extortion, theft, and illegal arms possession.
Reeve offered job
LOS ANGELES: Actor Christopher Reeve, paralysed from the neck down by a riding
accident in May, says he has received several acting and directing offers and
will start to consider scripts next year.
Briton held
MADRID: A Manchester couple who fled to Spain to escape British justice are
both behind bars. Linda McNelly, 45, absconded from prison in Staffordshire in
1992 while serving three years for cheque fraud and was held at a road block
near Alicante yesterday. Her husband Wally was arrested when he recently
returned to Britain and is in an Aberdeen prison charged in the theft of
#50,000 worth of antiques from a furniture van in the city in 1992.
Barbie in Africa
NAIROBI: Toy retailers in Kenya are doing a brisk trade in Christmas sales of a
black, Maasai Kenyan Barbie doll, the first in Africa. The doll wears a
traditional dress, beads, shawl, head-dress, and anklets.
</TEXT>
