<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>It's the mad, mad world of politics</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jimmy Reid</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Features</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR some time now there has been serious disquiet among those who study the
British political scene at the behaviour of Members of Parliament. We've always
had eccentrics, in this context a euphemism for being daft, but the
contemporary phenomenon is different and much more widespread, as if a
collective daftness has descended on the place.
We all know the background. Through the mists of time MPs have roamed the
badlands of Wild Westminster, massing in rival herds, bellowing and pawing the
ground in jousts of ritualised and feigned belligerence. The promised mayhem,
like most other things, didn't materialise, but bullshit did. Mounds of the
stuff, casting shadows o'er the parliamentary landscape and bringing to
Parliament that distinctive odour or flavour for which it is famed.
To be more precise it was mad bullshit, which experts in the field, lobby
correspondents and media political analysts, fussed over, probing for the inner
truth they believed was secreted somewhere in the shit, and whose discovery
would somehow justify their work. Alas without success.
I remember one old scribe, as urinated as a newt, in Annie's bar, one of many
watering holes in the Palace of Westminster, musing into his cups and
muttering, ``there is no inner truth, it's all shit. My monthly pay cheques
were nothing but a series of excremental payments''. He then took another long
sip and started muttering again. ``There is no inner meaning . . .''
The old scribe was being too sensitive. Sewage engineers handle the same basic
material as parliamentary correspondents but have no such feelings of guilt.
Somebody has to do it, and our scribes are our eyes and ears in the badlands.
They warn us of impending or potential disasters like Michael Portillo. It was
a venerable scribe who first alerted me to the dangers of parliamentary mad
bull's disease.
He had long ago identified the symptoms. Unsteady pins, an ungainly gait, a
tendency to fall over, a propensity to strike policemen and members of the
public, when returning to the cloisters from a reception where the bar was
free, and furiously blinking eyes, which seemed to be trying to focus or
re-focus, on something important, like your next drink.
Now these characteristics are not uncommon in the Houses of Parliament with 21
bars and cafes providing round-the-clock booze. An alcoholic, it is reckoned,
could live in Parliament for years, flitting from bar to bar, like a sort of
phantom of the opera, without anybody being any the wiser.
Once upon a time Winston Churchill, striding through the corridors, needed a
telephone, saw this guy using one and told him forcibly that this phone was
reserved for Members of Parliament. The guy retorted: ``I've been a Scottish
Labour Member for 20 years.'' Churchill looked at him intently, still knew him
not from Adam, and asked: ``Which bars have you been hiding in?''
Though the victims of mad bull's disease look as if blootered by bevvy it's a
different malaise, only contractable through exposure to parliamentary offal,
which has been recycled from debates past, and becomes more awful offal, each
time it's used and reused.
It should have been removed years ago, treated with chemicals to break it down
into constituent parts, then incinerated, placed in titanium tubes, and buried
in a remote part of the Himalayas for at least 1000 years, protected by a
special regiment of Gurkhas, led, of course, by white Anglo-Saxon officers, or
dumped in the ever-willing Dounreay.
This would have ended the unedifying spectacle, of poor mad bulls driven into
corrals or division lobbies by bulls, more mad, called Whips. How many more
times are we to witness the sordid relic of what was once a man, slither to his
feet at Prime Minister's Question Time, and say those dreaded words: ``Would my
Right Honourable Friend agree with me that . . .'' without taking action, like
putting him down.
There was concern that wives and families might be affected by exposure to
parliamentary offal. MPs are given relatively large sums of money for
secretarial, office administration, and research. An MP's wife who might before
his elevation have been a bingo caller or a double-glazing saleswoman, is then
discovered to have outstanding secretarial abilities, and put on the payroll.
Their child who might have left school with an O-level in domestic science is
often found to be a genetically programmed research genius, and put on the
payroll.
Thankfully the staff of MPs seem unaffected except for the odd research
assistant desperate to be a career politician. Funnily enough women MPs also
appear unaffected. No, dear reader, you're wrong, that lady MP is not a mad
cow, she's just mad.
As a General Election approaches the anxiety spasms associated with the disease
become more severe. Some MPs become completely deluded. The most afflicted talk
possessively of ``my seat'' as if current occupation bestows a property right
for all times to come.
When in danger of being dropped by their local party they wail, ``but it's my
career''. It's no good saying that if they wanted a career they should have
been a lawyer or a dentist, some of them are, as well as being MPs.
They view political parties as employment agencies for the likes of themselves.
Tell them that politics is about serving the people and they laugh like
demented coyotes.
Many MPs do have a sickness, but it's in the mind, which doesn't make it less
serious. They're only interested in their careers. They say what has to be
said, or do what has to be done, to safeguard their careers. The truth becomes
expendable, and a bit of a nuisance.
Imagine living that way. Career self-survival at all costs. No issue bigger
than yourself. No wider picture, only a small picture, a self-portrait. Such
self-obsessed priorities do induce a kind of madness, as we saw last week in
the Govan Labour Party. And it is said: ``Those that the gods would destroy,
they first make mad.''
</TEXT>
