<HEADLINE>City positive on Bank of Scotland plan to realise #211m from 49% flotation of Australian subsidiary BankWest warns of profit squeeze</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANKWEST, Bank of Scotland's new Australian subsidiary, expects profits growth
to slow as competition in the financial sector Down Under squeezes interest
rate margins.
The likely impact of competition on BankWest's profits was revealed in the
prospectus for Bank of Scotland's flotation of 49% of the Perth-based bank,
which only last month announced record earnings.
However, Bank of Scotland bought BankWest with an eye on the ``New Tiger''
economies of Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, and Taiwan, and some
industry-watchers are confident about the longer-term benefits of the
acquisition.
BankWest, whose year-end is being brought into line with that of its parent
company, forecasts that net profits will advance only 6% in its next full
financial year to end-February 1997 to A$100m (#48.2m). This would represent a
marked slowdown of the growth in profits which it has enjoyed during the past
three years. The predicted advance is based on an adjusted prior-year net
profit figure of A$94.5m (#45.5m).
Last month, BankWest announced a 20% increase in net profits to A$99.2m
(#47.8m) for the year to end-September. Its strength in business lending helped
it weather a downturn in the Australian mortgage market and, stripping out
exceptionals, underlying net profits were up 38%.
The prospectus says: ``Continued competitive pressure, particularly on interest
margins, combined with a number of external factors, including the increased
tax rate, will, in the directors' opinion, constrain the bank's capacity to
increase profits after tax in the 1997 financial year as strongly as in the
previous three years.''
Bank of Scotland, which acquired 100% of BankWest for A$900m (#434m), aims to
raise A$438m (#211m) before expenses from the sale of 213.5 million shares in
the Australian bank at A$2.05 (99p).
Details of the flotation emerged yesterday, when the prospectus was registered
by the Australian Securities Commission. However, Bank of Scotland declined to
comment on the prospects for the flotation, on the grounds that Australian
stock market regulations prevented it from so doing because the prospectus had
not yet been issued.
Bank of Scotland had previously undertaken to float 49% of BankWest, subject to
it realising a minimum consideration of A$#416m (#200m).
If the net proceeds of the sale exceed A$416m the balance will be payable to
the Western Australian state government, which sold BankWest to Bank of
Scotland.
When the Scottish bank initially mooted the flotation plans, the City was
sceptical about its ability to sell 49% because it considered the proposed
public offer price was on the high side.
However, industry experts seem encouraged by the way the flotation is
progressing.
Michael Lever, banking analyst at broker James Capel in London, said there was
a slight sense of relief that Bank of Scotland looked like selling the 49%.
He said there were no indications that the flotation would not be a success.
BZW analyst Hugh Pye is extremely bullish about the BankWest purchase, Bank of
Scotland's biggest since it took over British Linen Bank in 1971.
He said: ``I think it is a good bank and a good acquisition. I would quite like
it if Bank of Scotland ended up owning the whole thing forever but they have
had to agree to sell down.
``However, they will still own 51%. On a long-term view, I think it is going to
prove very successful for them.''
Touching on the scepticism with which the announcement of the BankWest
acquisition was greeted back in September, Mr Pye said he believed a number of
observers had come round to a positive view.
He added: ``I think there are still some doubters but I think they will be
proved wrong in time.''
The BankWest offer will open on January 8 and close on February 9, with shares
expected to begin trading on the Australian Stock Exchange the following week.
</TEXT>
