<DOCNO>GH951221-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Puppy-killer sentence signals explosive future for US jails</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782617</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Wednesday
A FLORIDA dope-head was sentenced to nine-and-a-half years in prison yesterday
for killing a puppy. The average American murderer serves about seven years in
prison, though the courts are trying to raise that.
Allan Laboy killed the dog because it woke him in August last year. He ran out
of his house, grabbed the animal, and beat its brains out on the pavement. The
judge concluded that he had a record of abusing animals and sent him away for
five years for cruelty to animals, plus four-and-a-half years extra for
violating his parole on other crimes.
He had been released early from a sentence for burglary, and killing the dog
was apparently considered a violation of his promise to behave.
His defence lawyer explained that Mr Laboy was a drug addict who was spaced out
on cocaine and alcohol when he killed the dog.
Jury and judge all agreed that this was not a mitigating sentence.
The judge said that he had received hundreds of hand-written letters, chiefly
from children, from all over the country demanding a condign sentence on the
defendant. He was glad to comply.
There is a strong tendency in the United States to increase sentences,
particularly for drug offences. There are now more people in jail in America
than in any other country, well over 1.5 million, and prison-building is a
growing industry.
Mr Leboy's lawyers are to appeal against the sentence: if it is upheld, and the
precedent is followed, the prison population will explode yet further.
q.The Library of Congress, the world's largest depository of knowledge, has
scrapped an exhibition on the lives of plantation slaves because some black
members objected.
No-one will explain what has sent the library into a crisis of political
correctness. The exhibition had already toured the country, without protest,
for several months.
Plans for a more ambitious exhibition on Sigmund Freud ended in a 1982 law suit
alleging discrimination against blacks in promotion decisions at the library,
which agreed to pay $8m (#5.3m) in back pay to plaintiffs.
A member of staff said: ``There is an atmosphere of fear at the library now.''
</TEXT>
