<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Robert Parrish</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Robert Parrish, film director and child star, born Columbus, Georgia, January
4, 1916, died Southampton, Long Island, December 4, 1995
ROBERT PARRISH worked with everyone in Hollywood during a long career which
began as an extra and a child actor in the silent era. He was an extra in
Murnau's Sunrise, made in 1927, a powder monkey in The Divine Lady, a saga
about Nelson made in 1929, and was the boy who blew the peashooter at Charlie
Chaplin in City Lights in 1931.
He became one of the children in the Our Gang films, but although he was a
handsome man his real career was behind the scenes. He graduated to film
editing, and during the war while serving in the navy edited John Ford's
Oscar-winning documentary, The Battle of Midway.
His first film, Cry Danger, made in 1951, was a gangster film starring Dick
Powell and Rhonda Fleming, which received decent notices and he worked
regularly thereafter. Parrish was not one of the great directors, but he made
some good films which pulled in the punters, including The Purple Plain, made
in 1954, in which Gregory Peck played a Canadian fighting the Burma campaign
with the help of a British supporting cast.
Others were Fire Down Below (1957) in which Rita Hayworth played a lady no
better than she should be who caused trouble on a south sea island between
Robert Mitchum and Jack Lemmon, and The Wonderful Country, (1959), in which
Mitchum rode the range. In 1962 he made In the French Style, a romantic comedy
starring Stanley Baker, one of many films which failed to make Jean Seberg a
star, while in 1967 he was one of several unhappy directors involved in Casino
Royale, the all-star, all-flop Bond movie everyone tends to forget.
</TEXT>
