<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Troubled Rodime considers restructuring</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOUNTING debts, negligible revenue and prolonged legal battles in the US have
forced computer disk drive company Rodime to consider restructuring its bank
debt and share capital.
The Scottish registered company pioneered the development of computer disk
drives in the eighties and once owned factories in Glenrothes, Florida and
Singapore.
But today Rodime consists of little more than a board which hires lawyers to
fight long and costly battles to defend its patents in the US.
Debts have mounted to $47.2m (#30.6m) and it no longer has sufficient income to
pay dividends on its Preference shares or interest on its $33.9m (#22m) of bank
borrowings.
``The board is currently in discussions with its bankers regarding a possible
reconstruction of the company's share capital and indebtedness,'' Rodime said
in a statement accompanying its latest annual results.
Last September a US federal appeals court threw out its test case against the
computer firm Quantum for alleged infringement of a patent on 3.5-inch disk
drives.
The ruling has damaged Rodime's chances of obtaining royalties from other
manufacturers and of winning a second test case against another US firm,
Seagate Technology. This has already dragged on for three years without coming
to court.
Rodime shares have fallen from just over 11p to just 1p this year and
Scottish-based director David Mathewson said the board hoped to put its
restructuring proposal to shareholders in January.
This could take several forms, including a debt-equity swap to help compensate
Preference shareholders and a debt restructuring to capitalise interest arrears.
Rodime's pre-tax loss fell to #4.1m from #7.0m in the year to September 30,
reflecting lower payments to the company's US lawyers.
``The previous year there had been a tremendous activity on the Seagate case
and that was slowed down last year,'' Mr Mathewson said.
Rodime hopes this will come to court in the second half of 1996. But it is
still awaiting a pre-trial conference which has already suffered 10
postponements.
Even if Rodime loses the Seagate case, it still hopes to generate revenue from
patents being sought on other types of disk drive which are less used than the
3.5-inch type.
Revenue from royalties rose to #318,000 from #33,000 last year, but no new
agreements have been signed since 1993.
</TEXT>
