<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Santa must pity those living in land of make-believe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Feature diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE most sensible people, the Diary was moved to outrage by the English vicar
who recently took it upon himself to tell 50 small children that neither Santa
nor the tooth fairy exist.
``It's your mum and dad,'' he allegedly alleged. Who could believe such arrant
nonsense? Wanton cruelty aside, we could only marvel at the logic of Canon
Brian Andrews, of Abbots Langley, Herts, who has since apologised for his
``ill-judged remark''.
He said he had simply been trying to show children that, while the story of
Santa Claus was a fairy tale, the story of the birth of Christ was not. Small
wonder the little ones were reduced to hysterics.
Ignoring the simple fact that presents actually turn up under the tree each
year while the Big Man remains, 2000 years on, a tad overdue for his
appointment, the vicar's claim strikes us as a philosophical strategy akin to
arguing that pixies are real because the Wizard of Oz has been exposed as a
hoax.
According to the Diary's department of Berserk But Deeply Systematic Theology,
however, the canon's condition is not so very unusual. Known as the Pull the
Other One Syndrome, it is a growing social problem. Today, as a guide to
readers, we bring you the latest research.
The Marriage of the Prince of Wales. A widespread delusion, belief in this
``fairy tale'' afflicts entire countries. There is no such thing.
The European Triumphs of Glasgow Rangers. Thousands have travelled to the ends
of the earth in the hope of witnessing one of these miraculous events, last
believed to have occurred in the distant past. Researchers have yet to confirm
a sighting.
Britain's Economic Recovery. The so-called Feel-Good Gnome who appears once a
year with a red box full of ``goodies'' is in fact a fat bloke hired for the
occasion by the Bank of England. The box, children, is empty.
The Lottery Regulator. Believed to fly around the world with no assistance
whatever, the Lottery Pixie is thought only to hand out huge amounts of money
to nice little companies who have been good all year long. In fact, as any
expensive legal team could prove, he does no such thing.
The Four Wise Beatles. Contrary to all appearances, only Saint John Lennon is
now accepted as authentic by students with ears.
The Labour Party, otherwise known as the Social Democratic Brunch. Scholars are
divided. Some point to the Miracle of Labour's Second Coming as proof this
otherwise unbelievable entity actually exists. Others point to Tony Blair as
proof that the opposite is, in fact, the case.
Free no more
HIGH jinks in the House of Commons, where the Government, in the shape of the
mean and moody Michael Forsyth, was moving the other night to give still more
power to the mighty Scottish Grand Committee. Commons Leader Tony Newton told
the House the plans had been ``widely welcomed north of the border'', which may
well be true, depending on which Tory you talk to.
Labour, predictably, demurred just a bit. It was thus left to Sir Hector Munro,
elder statesman of Scottish Conservatism, to put the matter in perspective.
Welcoming the reforms, he said the plans were ``a major step forward in
bringing government to the people of Scotland''.
In sharp contrast, presumably, to what we enjoyed hitherto.
Stable condition
A PARTY of Edinburgh primary school children (we declare an interest in this
one) is hauled along to a local hospital, there to bawl carols and impose some
Christmas cheer on defenceless senior citizens.
``And how did it go?'' we inquire afterwards of Deeply Callous Child. ``Not
bad,'' he offers. ``One old dear in tears and three fast asleep inside 20
minutes.'' And that was after he had learned all the words, too.
SOME readers may have noticed the American legal system holds an entirely
unhealthy fascination for this Diary. We can't think why, but can only report
that in 1992 a federal jury in Montgomery, Alabama, found that a group of fuel
retailers had conspired to fix prices, as alleged, but decided on balance that
the plaintiffs had been damaged only to the tune of $1 (tripled, by anti-trust
law, to a whopping $3).
Finishing up the case last month (American courts being about as speedy as
ours) Judge Myron Thompson nevertheless ordered the losers to pay the fees of
the opposition's 19 victorious lawyers - fees totalling $2,035,658, and not a
cent more.
Jurists among you will also be pleased to hear that earlier this year the
Louisiana legislature closed a decade-old loophole in its drinking law. From
1985 until June 1995, the legal age for buying or drinking liquor had been 21,
but it was illegal to sell liquor only to those under 18.
A sporting nation
THOSE who were wondering how Scotland ended up in the same group as England for
next year's European Championships should have looked no further than the
sports section of Monday's Daily Telegraph, which carried the non-aligned
headline: ``Scots march on Wembley to add spice to England's task''.
Good to know your place, don't you think?
Ask a silly question
MEANWHILE, Edinburgh's Evening News, perhaps the finest evening newspaper in
the entire capital, runs a ``fun daily quiz''. Earlier this week its ten
questions were aimed at those sad people proud to be known as ``telly addicts''.
Question Four: ``Which spoof chat show host revels in the company of a group of
Manchester senior citizens and is otherwise known as Mrs Merton?'' Answer:
``Mrs Merton.''
</TEXT>
