<DOCNO>GH951221-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE US Senate voted tonight to use legal action to force the White House to
release documents in the Whitewater investigation.
The Senate passed a resolution to seek a court order enforcing a subpoena by
the Senate Whitewater Committee for notes made by former White House counsel
William Kennedy at a 1993 meeting on Whitewater, involving President Clinton's
lawyers and White House aides.
The White House and Mr Kennedy are refusing to comply with the subpoena, saying
release of the notes would violate the president's lawyer-client privilege.
If the legal action takes place, it could lead to a constitutional
confrontation that might have to be decided by the US Supreme Court.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>British Nato forces first into Serb country</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RICHARD MEARES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782623</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bocac, Wednesday
BRITISH Nato forces pushed across a former front line in Bosnia today to become
the first foreign fighting unit stationed on Serb-held territory.
Just a couple of hours after the United Nations formally handed responsibility
for keeping the peace in Bosnia to Nato, some 100 British soldiers swept past
Serb checkpoints to venture where UN peacekeepers had never been allowed to go.
B Squadron of the Light Dragoons headed in armoured vehicles up the narrow
Vrbas river valley in western Bosnia to set up camp at Krupa, a village some 18
miles south of their ultimate destination, the Serb stronghold of Banja Luka.
``Our aim is to make our presence felt as quickly as possible,'' said spokesman
Major Alastair Ross in Gornji Vakuf, headquarters of Nato's British-led
division South-West.
The Dragoons crossed the line just past a ruined medieval castle and the Bocac
hydro-electric power station, the only thing working for miles around in a
snowswept no-man's land.
Trees, snow, the emerald river, and villages destroyed by fighting or burned
out of spite were all they saw on the way.
This area, around Mrkonjic Grad, is to pass back to the Serbs, who lost it only
two months ago, under the Bosnian peace treaty signed last week in Paris. All
the residents have fled.
The Dragoons had swopped their blue UN peacekeeper berets for regimental ones
and set out before dawn in UN vehicles once painted white, now green and black,
from their base in government-held Bugojno.
The 13,000 Britons, the second biggest Nato contingent after the Americans,
will keep the peace in Bihac, Prijedor, Jajce, and other Bosnian towns which
have all become bywords for death and degradation in Europe's worst conflict
for 50 years.
With one-third of their troops already on the ground serving under the UN, the
British had a head start over the 20,000 Americans arriving in Bosnia for the
first time, and managed to deploy more quickly across central Bosnia.
Nato's Implementation Force (Ifor) is the first outside force the Serbs in the
Banja Luka area have seen during the war, but it is just the latest foreign
army to pass through the region over the centuries.
The Romans, Ottoman Turks, Austro-Hungarians, and Nazi Germans have all marched
through an area which once stood on a main trade route between Europe and the
Orient.
In Croat and Muslim-held areas of Bosnia, people have grown used to a foreign
presence through UN peacekeepers over three years of war. In more hostile Serb
areas unsure of outsiders, however, Ifor will have to tread more carefully.
Banja Luka, ``cleansed'' of virtually all non-Serbs to become an ``ethnically
pure'' region which aid officials have dubbed an intolerant ``Heart of
Darkness'', could pose problems, although British officers said they had been
pledged co-operation.
The town is a base for General Ratko Mladic, the Bosnian Serb commander whom
Ifor members will be obliged to arrest should they see him. Nato officers say
they will not seek him out.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lord Younger sells shares</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Bank of Scotland chairman Lord Younger yesterday sold nearly
threequarters of his shareholding, although he could have realised an
additional #35,000-plus if he had taken profits at the height of Friday's
takeover speculation.
Lord Younger sold 40,000 of his 54,655 shares at 565p, well adrift of the 658p
intra-day high to which Royal Bank surged on Friday amid fevered speculation
that Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Banking Corporation was about to launch a #6100m bid.
His sale realised #226,000.
The chairman's office said there was nothing significant or untoward about the
transaction.
Royal Bank directors were prevented from dealing in its shares between the end
of September and November 29 because of the two-month ``close period'' ahead of
the announcement of final results.
Hanson disposals
HANSON has decided on two major divestments which will go much of the way
towards achieving the #2000m disposals target it has set itself. It is
proposing to float off Suburban Propane, the third-largest distributor of
propane in the US, which will realise about #500m, and it has earmarked the
sale of Cavenham Forest Products for at least #1000m. The company owns
1,750,000 acres of forests in North America and a number of sawmills. Other
assets in the out-tray include the stake in National Grid which Hanson acquired
with its takeover of Eastern Electricity, and Seven Seas, a manufacturer of
vitamin supplements.
Flotation plans
INCHCAPE has decided to press ahead with the flotation of its insurance broking
business Bain Hogg. The group said in April 1994 that it intended to float the
business eventually but it has received a number of approaches to buy it in
recent months. It has concluded that flotation remains the best option.
Murray trust lags
MURRAY Split Capital Trust lagged behind its main benchmark indices in the
three months to November 30, but said this was just a ``blip'' in an otherwise
good performance. The #26.7m trust, which aims for both capital and investment
growth, saw net assets increase 2.3% during the first quarter of its financial
year. The FTSE All-Share Index rose 4% and the Kleinwort Benson TOPSI-100
Index, which tracks higher-yielding shares, rose 3% over the same period. The
dividend was increased 3.8% to 2.75p from the first quarter of last year as a
sign of confidence. The net asset value of the income shares barely rose to
51.8p from 51.6p at the end of the last quarter of 1994-1995. The NAV of the
capital shares increased to 219.0p from 213.5p.
Shields on track
GLASGOW'S Shields Automotive yesterday announced its #500,000 acquisition of a
south Glasgow-based Toyota car and van dealership from Lex Service. The two
dealerships, which sit next to each other on St Andrews Road, employ about 80
people and offer full after-sales facilities such as bodyshop, MOT, service and
maintenance, parts and paint ovens. ``Our mid-term goal is basically to build
up a dealership group,'' the company said. ``We're aiming for having five
dealerships with a combined #50m-plus turnover.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Reprieve for `sick building' school</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Ayrshire mother was last night celebrating after Strathclyde Regional
Council decided to delay a decision on closing her daughter's school.
Mrs Jean Kerr was about to fight a decision by the region to close a special
needs school attended by her daughter, Helen, eight, because it suffered from
``sick building syndrome''.
The region had decided to shut Craigpark School, Ayr, despite local pressure to
keep it open backed by a 10,500-signature petition supporting the pupils'
parents.
Strathclyde's decision to close the school followed numerous complaints from
staff and pupils about suffering nausea. Yesterday, before a hearing was due to
take place at the Court of Session, Edinburgh, the region agreed to a reprieve
for Craigpark, at least until the end of next month.
Mrs Kerr, of Portland Road, Dalrymple, was about to ask for a suspension of the
closure order, but the school board chairman, Mr Roy McHattie, said the school
had won a stay of execution.
Last night, Mrs Kerr spoke about the sick building syndrome: ``It didn't affect
all the children or staff. Some became nauseous, others had dry throats, skin
irritations, and dry eyes.
``No-one could find a cause for it. Strathclyde sent in their own regional
chemist twice and Dundee University came in to investigate the problem. That's
when they decided it was SBS. It's been going on for three years.''
Craigpark is for profoundly handicapped youngsters.
Floorboards were replaced and a new ventilation system installed at a cost of
#120,000 last year. The children went back for three days, but the problems
started up again.
``We don't say there is nothing wrong with the school. There's definitely a
problem. We just feel Strathclyde could investigate the problem a bit more
thoroughly,'' Mrs Kerr added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Recovery in sight</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782626</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE housing market is still deep in the doldrums as can be seen from continuing
poor results from the majority of housebuilders.
Yesterday's profit warning from Edinburgh-based CALA was a case in point. It is
suffering from a low level of visitors and sales in South-east England,
probably the hardest hit housing area. But there are now signs that the market
could at last be in sight of recovery, if only modest.
This at any rate was the message in yesterday's data from the Bank of England
and the Building Societies Association which showed mortgage lending pick-up.
Anecdotal evidence, so far, also suggests that the building societies
themselves are becoming more optimistic.
The societies and other lenders as well as members of the construction industry
had of course asked the Chancellor to try to kick-start the market by some
Budget initiative. He declined to do this but the trend of lower interest rates
with the societies and banks leading the way with further mortgage interest
rates reductions even before base rates were reduced. They then cut rates again.
This clearly is the best tonic to encourage house purchase. Many potential
buyers will anyway have held back until after the Budget. And if purchasers do
return in numbers it will still take time for this to work its way through to
housebuilders.
Moreover, the housing market should be wary of false dawns. There have been two
of them. That ``feel-good'' factor has proved very elusive and tax cuts and
lower interest rates in themselves may not be enough to counter job insecurity
and stressful working conditions.
Employment may be rising but the terms of conditions are not necessarily such
as to encourage long-term financial commitments. But for the moment mortgage
lenders appear to have taken an optimistic turn which is actually somewhat
ironic given their recent pleas to Mr Clarke.
New team
BT'S relationship with its regulator Oftel is edgy at the best of times but it
is likely to deteriorate as it battles to prevent Oftel's director-general, Don
Cruickshank, from achieving more wide-ranging powers against anti-competitive
behaviour.
Now BT is upgrading its compliance department to ensure it abides by its
various operating licences and with competition and fair trading law. A new
post of director of compliance is being created and the holder will head a
small department reporting regularly to the BT board's audit committee. At
present these functions are divided between a number of individuals, some of
whom have other responsibilities as well.
The new dedicated team will no doubt be more adept at countering arguments put
up by Oftel.
Even BT would admit that in an organisation of its size some lapses in
practices are bound to occur. Competitors who usually depend on it to deliver
calls, claim far worse things go on. For example, Keith Monserrat of Scottish
Telecom alleged BT was particularly unco-operative over value-added data
services which carry higher margins.
Mr Cruickshank wants the power to act quickly when anti-competitive practices
come to light. At present it is a lengthy process and rules are drawn so
tightly the practice can slip between them so is not dealt with.
If this happens it can only be corrected through an amendment to the licence
which has to be agreed with BT. If agreement cannot be reached the whole thing
is referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission for a ruling.
BT is wary about the regulator extending his powers and will almost certainly
force the issue to the MMC.
If it can delay this into 1997 it may avoid it altogether, because a Labour
Government would appoint a new regulator and it appears to be sympathetic
towards BT despite its continuing market dominance.
A team dedicated to the complexities of the licence and competition law will
help the group in the tussles to come.
Huge gamble
IF you want to buy a share at bargain basement prices, look no further than
Rodime, the one-time king of computer disk drives.
At 1p a share you won't find much cheaper on the stock market, but even then
you'd be taking a huge gamble.
The company has virtually no assets other than a set of patents which it is
fighting long and expensive court battles in the United States to enforce - so
far unsuccessfully.
The factories Rodime once owned on three continents are gone. Royalties from
licensing other manufacturers to make disk drives have been cut to a trickle.
The company's continued existence depends entirely on the generosity of its
bankers and its debts continue to mount.
Rodime is in heavy arrears on its interest payments and cannot even afford to
pay dividends on its Preference shares. Most other companies in such
circumstances would simply have folded.
But Rodime keeps alive a tiny flame of hope that by paying even more millions
of dollars to its US lawyers it will one day win a US court case to enforce
respect for its patents.
That could open up a new revenue stream that might yet be the company's
salvation.
But it's a long shot. Yesterday's news that Rodime may shortly propose a
restructuring of its capital and debt sent its shares down another !fp to 1p.
At that price they are hardly worth selling. But only a fool or a very brave
punter would buy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
