<DOCNO>GH951221-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Rev J Donald Smith</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Douglas Lister</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782628</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Rev J Donald Smith MA, BD, DD, who has died at the age of 79, was for three
years among the thousands of British Servicemen held in the notorious Changi
Camp and forced to work on the Siam-Burma ``death railway''. He later wrote a
book, remarkably free of rancour, about his experiences.
Donald Smith was born in Aberdeenshire in 1916. His father was dominie in the
village of Fintry, and his grandfather parish minister of Keith Hall. He was
educated at Robert Gordon's College and graduated with honours in French and
German from Aberdeen University in 1939. He intended to become a teacher but
when the Second World War broke out volunteered for service and found himself
attached to the Intelligence Corps.
Being fluent in modern languages, he was trained and equipped for desert
warfare, he thought, in Basra. But in 1941, he found himself posted to the 18th
Division, destination Singapore. The route there took him to Halifax, Nova
Scotia, in American ships. He sailed for the Far East by the South Atlantic in
mountainous seas to Capetown and then up to Mombasa.
Donald Smith and his comrades landed in Singapore on January 13, 1942. On
January 20, the Japanese attacked. ``The 14th of February we called black
Saturday,'' he said.
For the next three years Smith and thousands of gifted and dedicated servicemen
were prisoners in Changi Camp, working on the Siam-Burma ``death railway.''
They lived and nearly died there.
Donald wrote up the story in a book of quite splendid prose - as moving a
record of courage, faith, and hope - with never a trace or bitterness or hate,
as ever I have read. And All the Trumpets was published in 1954. It was written
on the Isle of Bute, where he stayed for seven years after his release.
He was community officer of Bute. The first time I met him was there, a shy,
self-effacing, and obviously highly gifted person. I had known nothing about
him and he did not say anything about himself or his experiences. He married a
Rothesay girl, Gina Cunningham. She was to become a great and gracious partner
and colleague in his ministries.
Donald was seriously weakened by his ordeal. His central vision had been
destroyed. But he fought on and in 1957 gained his second degree of BD. ``Gina
read so many books with me that she gained the B and I the D,'' he said.
Together Donald and Gina exercised great and good ministries in Errol, Cults
East, and in Auchtergaven; retiring in 1981 to Kintore. In 1978, Aberdeen
University honoured him with the degree of Doctor of Divinity.
He died of cancer, going as he lived, bravely and thoughtfully. A man of mercy
and truth. A great number of friends and members of his various congregations
gathered in Kintore Parish Church for his funeral service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
