<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Premier spy claim dismissed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782629</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Warsaw, Wednesday
POLAND'S Cabinet today dismissed allegations by outgoing President Lech Walesa
that ex-communist Prime Minister Jozef Oleksy had dangerous contacts with a
Moscow spy.
Walesa called a sudden meeting of the National Defence Committee last night to
say he had been given secret materials revealing a threat to state security.
A source said the allegation concerned Oleksy's past social contacts in Warsaw
with someone who turned out to be a Russian intelligence agent.
After an emergency Cabinet meeting yesterday, a statement said: ``The Cabinet
does not share the view about there being a threat to the State.''
However the pro-Walesa foreign, defence and interior ministers dissented from
the Cabinet judgment and Walesa left the meeting in silence.
Oleksy, who denied the claims, later said on television that he would not
``give in to blackmail'' or resign.
Walesa, who led the Solidarity union to victory over communist rule in 1989,
lost last month's elections to Oleksy's close ally Aleksander Kwasniewski and
is due to hand over power on Saturday.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
