<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Over the top in ape shape</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782630</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In William Russell's view the latest contender for Jerry Lewis's comic crown is
going off his chump
Ace Ventura: When Nature Calls (PG) directed by
Steve Oedekerk
On general release from Boxing Day
The Indian in the Cupboard (PG) directed by Frank Oz
On general release from tomorrow
IF YOU have ever wondered what an ace in the hole looks like now is your chance
to find out. Not that I recommend it, because there are better films to pass
your time with in the cinema this Christmas than Ace Ventura: When Nature Calls.
The hole the comedian Jim Carrey has dug for himself is exceedingly deep and
not worth exploring. The advice is not given lightly, because Carrey's first
outing as the manic investigator in Ace Ventura: Pet Detective was great fun,
suggesting that here was a fine new star comedian in the Jerry Lewis tradition,
but with more charm, adept at pulling both funny faces and physical comedy.
His promise was fulfilled in his next starring role in The Mask as a man
transformed, from time to time, into a cartoon character by an ancient Egyptian
mask, which he had carelessly put on his face. The dazzling special effects
could have swamped Carrey totally, but his comic personality proved strong
enough to overcome them and there was a flesh and blood comedian up there on
the screen as well as the cartoon character.
Admittedly, I was less entranced by his high camp Riddler in Batman Forever,
but there is no denying that he performed with abandon and got the laughs in a
film which, while it pulled them in at the box office, was very much a Chinese
meal of a movie.
His most recent hit, Dumb and Dumber, in which he starred with Jeff Daniels -
they played a dense twosome who ran a pet parlour - left me stone cold, but I
saw it on video on my own, not circumstances in which one should watch
brain-dead comedy. Such films must be seen in the cinema, preferably after a
couple of pints of lager, to achieve their effect.
By the standards of the genre - the Wayne's World and Bill and Ted films are
other notable examples - Dumb and Dumber was well above par, and while it may
not have made me laugh much, Carrey's comic personality remained appealing.
Alas, in this new outing as Ace Ventura things have gone sadly wrong. Ace, the
man with the Li'l Abner quiff, loves animals, and the opening sequence, a
splendid send-up of the opening scenes in the Stallone mountain drama, Cliff
Hanger, promises well.
Having scaled impossible heights to rescue a racoon lost in a mountain-top
plane crash, Ace sees it plunge to its death after the harness, to which it is
linked, gives way. There is a vintage gross moment when, on his way up the
cliff, he encounters a hungry baby eagle. In some comic scenarios Mummy eagle
would appear and attack him, but not in the world of Ventura. What happens I
will not reveal, but it has the right disgusting, no-holds-barred edge.
We next find Ace in a Buddhist monastery, where he has gone to find himself,
being asked by a British colonial official (Ian McNeice) to come to Africa to
help the local Consul General (Simon Callow) find a lost sacred white bat,
whose disappearance threatens to spark off a civil war between two tribes.
So far so good, but once in Africa the film goes to pieces. What is surprising,
given the politically correct climate in the United States, not to mention the
fact that black Americans are so proud of their African roots, is the view
taken of the natives. It makes that of the old Johnny Weismuller Tarzan films,
which today are frankly offensive, seem positively enlightened.
Carrey mugs frantically - as a face puller he is second to none - but he has
nobody to play off, and there is less of the physical comedy than before. Even
the animals he meets are given little scope, and his friendly monkey companion,
Spike, is no Cheetah. The fact that Callow, an actor who tends to go over the
top of the top at the drop of a false eyelash, looks positively staid is some
measure of how frenetic Carrey is in his search for laughs.
The plot makes no sense, and some of the stunts go beyond the bounds of
acceptable outrageousness. The sight of a naked Carrey emerging from the womb
of a rhino is not something I wish to see ever again. But I did laugh once. At
the end, Callow, the villain of the piece, flees into the jungle where he meets
the randy silver-backed lady gorilla we have been repeatedly told is lurking in
the bush and nature takes its course.
Carrey fans will ensure that the box office is good, but there are diminishing
returns and if his next films - there is to be another Mask - prove as dire
then that bright future will fade fast. On the other hand he got $20m for this
one so he can laugh all the way to the bank, even if the audiences do not do
much laughing. ``All-l-lRIIIGHTY then,'' as Ace would say? No, it is not.
A better bet, although well down the list of must-see Christmas movies in a
year that has the splendid tale of a trotter at large, Babe, and the witty The
Santa Clause on offer, is The Indian in the Cupboard. Directed by Frank Oz, of
Muppet fame, it is based on the book by Lynn Reid Banks in which nine-year-old
Omri (Hal Scardino), given an old cupboard as a birthday present, discovers,
when he puts another of his presents, a 3in-tall plastic Indian, inside it,
that the toy comes to life.
The Indian, played by a native American called Litefoot, turns out to be Little
Bear, a real Iroquois chief, and Omri forms a friendship with him which comes
under stress when his friend, Patrick, puts a cowboy in the cupboard.
This is the enchanting world of Mistress Masham's Repose, The Borrowers or
Gulliver's Travels in which getting to know the miniature people provides
lessons about life for the humans involved.
Oz and screenwriter, Melissa Mathison, have treated the book with respect, but,
for obvious box office reasons, the setting has been shifted to America, which
causes some of the adventures to lose their point. For all its timeless appeal
the story is firmly rooted in an English story telling tradition.
The British Tommy in a tin hat, for example, who administers first aid after
the Indian and the Cowboy (David Keith) fight, might conceivably be found in a
British toy box, but not in one in Manhattan.
There is also a scene in which Omri and Patrick, a really unpleasant brat, fall
out over their new friends - Omri sees them as people, Patrick as animated toys
- which rings very false. The special effects as little man steps into monster
hand are superbly done, and Hal Scardino makes an delightful Omri - bookish,
grave, and sensitive, but never a wimp.
Both Litefoot and David Keith make their 3in-high heroes the stuff of adventure
stories, but Oz has unaccountably made a rather dull film from Lynn Reid
Banks's celebrated, and far from dull, book.
Add Kenneth Branagh's In the Bleak Midwinter and Jean Cocteau's La Belle et la
Bete to your list, and there is plenty around in the cinema this Christmas to
make an outing worthwhile should what is on offer on television pall.
It makes the old Tarzan films         look positively enlightened
</TEXT>
