<HEADLINE>Corruption trial urged of Italy's Mr Clean</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From BEATRICE COLNAGO</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782631</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Milan, Wednesday
PROSECUTORS called today for the symbol of Italy's war on corruption, former
star magistrate Antonio Di Pietro, to be indicted on charges of extortion and
abuse of office.
The request, which could shatter Di Pietro's political ambitions, was lodged in
Brescia, northern Italy. It capped seven months of inquiries into bombshell
allegations that the man associated with exposing the political corruption
scandal that felled Italy's old governing class had himself engaged in corrupt
practices.
A judge must now decide whether to order a trial.
Di Pietro's lawyer insisted on his client's innocence and hinted that the
allegations had been fuelled by revenge.
``Antonio Di Pietro has been the target of allegations of all kinds. It is the
price he has had to pay for his stubborn pursuit of the `Clean Hands'
investigation,'' said Massimo Dinoia.
Prosecutors also requested a trial on charges of complicity in blackmail for
former Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi's brother Paolo, former Defence
Minister Cesare Previti, and two Justice Ministry inspectors.
They are alleged to have used information about Di Pietro's past to force him
into quitting Milan's elite team of investigators one year ago.
Di Pietro has played an increasingly high-profile role as a ``political
conscience'' in the four-year Italian corruption scandal.
With many opinion polls still identifying him as the man Italians would most
like to see as prime minister, commentators said that he had been awaiting the
outcome of the Brescia inquiry before deciding whether to enter
politics.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
