<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trust puts youth on first rung</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Mullins</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782632</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CATHERINE Rogan and Michelle Bergin are on the stairway to success as they
provide catering for the launch of a directory of Scottish young entrepreneurs,
writes ANDREW MULLINS.
The 1996 yearbook of the Prince's Scottish Youth Business Trust (PSYBT) was
unveiled at their Wholefoods and Sweet Nothings cafe in Glasgow's Princes
Square yesterday.
The cafe is one of 2800 small businesses in Scotland set up with the help of
#8.6m of loans and grants from the trust, whose patron is the Prince of Wales.
The yearbook is backed by Scottish Enterprise as part of its plans to make 1996
the Year of the Entrepreneur.
The book is intended to promote PSYBT and encourage networking between young
entrepreneurs aged 18 to 25 who have received help from it.
Publisher Caspian Woods explained that PSYBT had helped him with a low-cost
loan and a business advisor who provided three years of after care. The trust's
volunteer advisers are mainly retired business people.
Mr Woods, whose publications include the new PSYBT yearbook, said the
assistance he received was ``worth its weight in gold''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vivian Blaine</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Vivian Blaine (born Vivien Stapleton), musical comedy actress; born Newark, New
Jersey, November 21, 1921, died New York, December 9, 1995
BROADWAY stars seldom get the chance to recreate their greatest roles when the
film comes to be made, but Vivian Blaine was lucky.
The first and possibly the greatest lady to tell a man to take back that mink,
she played the floozie with a heart and a head cold - Miss Adelaide - in Guys
and Dolls when it was filmed in 1955 with Frank Sinatra as her reluctant
fiance, Nathan Detroit.
It is an indictment of the studio system that her best film role, despite a
miscast Sinatra, was one she had already played in the theatre, because during
the forties she had appeared in a succession of Fox musicals to little effect.
She began her career as a band singer with Art Kessel and his Kassels in the
Air, and was given a contract by 20th Century Fox in 1942. Four small parts
followed before Jitterbugs in 1943, a Laurel and Hardy comedy in which she was
billed as ``the Cherry Blonde'', a night club singer the two comedians helped
fight off gangsters.
The next year she had two leading roles followed in Greenwich Village, a 1920s
story about a classical musician who allowed his work to be used in a jazz
musical, starring with Don Ameche and Carmen Miranda, and Something for the
Boys, loosely based on a Cole Porter show.
In 1945 she appeared in State Fair, the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical,
opposite the crooner, Dick Haymes. But she did not unseat the studio's reigning
blonde, Betty Grable, and when she made Three Little Girls in Blue in 1946 it
was another aspirant to the throne of the leading blonde, June Haver, who got
top billing.
She recreated the role of Miss Adelaide when Guys and Dolls came to the London
Coliseum in 1954, and her career thereafter, once she had played the role for
the screen, was spent largely in the theatre and in television.
Her stage musicals included Say Darling, Company, in which she played the role
created by Elaine Stritch of the lady who lunched, Gypsy, Follies, and Hello
Dolly. A fine singer, who could belt a song and sing it sweetly, if she did not
make it into the pantheon of the cinema's great musical leading ladies, she
certainly did so on Broadway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yeltsin shrugs off old-guard comeback</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TIMOTHY HERITAGE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782634</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow, Wednesday
THE Communists and their allies will hold about 40% of the seats in the new
Russian Parliament, according to the latest projections.
However President Boris Yeltsin, breaking his silence over the Communist
revival, said that the outcome of Sunday's parliamentary election was no
tragedy and would not force him to dilute reforms.
``We have no reason for concern or to regard the election as a tragedy,''
Yeltsin told reporters at the sanatorium outside Moscow where he is recovering
from a heart attack.
The Communist Party, cashing in on discontent with hardships under
Western-style reforms, looked set to win one-third of the places in the
450-seat Duma.
However election experts said the Communists could control 40% of seats if they
managed to form an alliance with other left-wing groups.
Communist and nationalist forces together should have more than half the seats.
This would give them a majority if they formed an unprecedented alliance,
although parliament is much less powerful than the presidency.
Despite a disappointing showing by reformists, Yeltsin said Russia would
``manage to follow the same political course as before'' and expressed
confidence that the new Duma would continue democratic processes.
Yeltsin assured German Chancellor Helmut Kohl by telephone that the new Duma
would conserve the ``mood for reform'' and that he would establish
``constructive co-operation'' with it.
However the reformist former Prime Minister Yegor Gaidar, who expects to have
no seat in the new Duma, said the Communists risked creating ``a real mess'' in
the run-up to June's presidential election.
To avoid splitting the liberal vote for the presidency, Gaidar said his
Russia's Choice party would probably bow out.
The delay in announcing results prompted cries of foul play from two likely
challengers for the presidency, retired general Alexander Lebed and former
vice-president Alexander Rutskoi, although Gaidar said he believed the vote was
by-and-large fair. Foreign election monitors said they had no evidence of
widespread fraud.
Like Gaidar, Rutskoi and Lebed's nationalist parties failed to win the 5% of
votes needed to win seats in the half of the Duma allocated by proportional
representation.
Adding to Yeltsin's problems, a battle raged today in breakaway Chechnya's
second city, Gudermes. Refugees fleeing the fighting said Russian forces had
subjected it to the worst shelling they had seen in the year-long war. 10
Russian soldiers were reported dead in street battles.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Young business grows with demand</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Mullins</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782635</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUTHERFORD Manson Dowds, the rapidly expanding firm of Scottish accountants,
opened a new larger office in Glasgow yesterday, writes ANDREW MULLINS.
The premises in Blythswood Square are three times bigger than the old Glasgow
offices of the eight-year-old firm, which also has branches in Edinburgh,
Aberdeen and London.
It specialises in corporate finance, audits and accounts and takes an
aggressive approach to seeking out new business.
The firm has three partners and 24 other staff working in Glasgow, but
partner-in-charge Ian Steele said: ``We expect to double in size in the next 24
months.''
Rutherford Manson Dowds was founded in 1987 and expects to turnover #6m this
year.
The early years saw the partners eschewing existing large businesses to
concentrate on smaller companies with potential.
``We identified the David Murrays and Tom Farmers of tomorrow, and as they have
grown so have we,'' said founding partner Cahal Dowds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Absent MPs face Labour wrath</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782636</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO Labour MPs at the heart of last week's controversial Govan selection battle
face severe disciplinary action from the party for going off on holiday this
week and missing Tuesday night's crucial vote against the Government.
Glasgow Central MP Mike Watson last week narrowly defeated rival candidate
Councillor Mohammad Sarwar for the redrawn Govan seat. Mr Watson was strongly
supported in his campaign by neighbouring MP Ian Davidson, currently
representing the old constituency of that name but likely to contest the new
Pollok seat.
Neither Mr Watson, who is with his wife at an unknown holiday destination
abroad, nor Mr Davidson, who is in Sri Lanka with his wife and two children,
had prior permission to miss the crucial vote and will face the wrath of Chief
Whip Donald Dewar on their return.
London MP Brian Sedgemore also was absent, on a trip to Barbados, and what
rankles with the Whips is that the loss of these three votes cost Labour
victory on its own more critical motion. Fortunately for the three, they had
the consolation of the Government's motion falling by two votes.
Mr Watson, however, still must consider the party's national executive meeting
next month, at which there will be a demand for a rerun of the Govan contest.
One of Mr Watson's supporters in Govan, party activist Archie Graham, defended
him yesterday: ``Mike's voting record as an MP is second to none and I would be
absolutely amazed if Mike was somewhere and the whips could not get hold of
him.''
``I am assuming he advised them that he was going away for a few days for a
family holiday. If there has been any difficulty, I can only assume there has
been some sort of misunderstanding.''
``The man never had a family holiday in the summer because of all the stress
and strain and work that had to be done for the reselection battle. It was a
well-earned break.''
Critics from the rival Sarwar camp see it differently. Pollok party member
Stewart Daniels said he had begun as a Watson supporter but had changed to the
rival camp.
He said yesterday he would be writing to Mr Dewar expressing concern about time
off granted from Westminster for the selection campaign and the absences on
Tuesday night.
Two other Scottish MPs missed Tuesday night's vote but both had permission.
Pollok MP Jimmie Dunnachie was absent for health reasons and was paired with an
ill Tory MP, while Clydesdale MP Jimmy Hood attended a European engagement
accompanied by his Conservative counterpart.
One Labour MP said of Mr Davidson last night: ``It is inexplicable that a man
now relying on the goodwill of a Labour leadership seeking to end the year on a
triumph should have acted in this way.''
The SNP was quick to capitalise on events. ``If such an attitude is the best
that Labour can offer, then it simply underlines the need for change in Govan
and throughout Scotland,'' said the party's candidate in the constituency, Ms
Nicola Sturgeon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland gets 125m in awards for projects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782637</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND so far has received almost #125m in awards from the National Lottery,
Scottish Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton announced yesterday,
(writes Stephen McGregor).
He emphasised that the awards had ranged from the very small to the very big,
and that many organisations had benefited ``beyond their wildest dreams.''
The Minister told the Commons: ``The successful projects have ranged from small
but very important grants - such as #600 given to Gallowhill Elderly Forum -
right up to the #23m towards Scotland's Field of Dreams at Hampden Park.
``Other awards have included the #3m announced for a new Edinburgh Festival
headquarters; #10.2m to purchase the Mar Lodge estate in the Cairngorms;
#710,000 awarded to the Glasgow Film Theatre; #3m to the Scottish Gallery of
Modern Art to purchase the Penrose Collection; #660,000 for Strathclyde Poverty
Alliance and #1.5m to Tayside Regional Council for a sports complex.''
Lord James said: ``Many people may still be waiting for their first personal
success with the lottery, but one thing is certain - Scotland as a nation is
winning.''
</TEXT>
