<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Making an issue of it</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Keith Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782638</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
They were young, they were free. Now they're not but they're on
the road anyway.
Keith Bruce charts his band's charity efforts
THE story so far: Ten years after they were invented over a St Patrick's Day
pint in Jack McLean's favourite hostelry, Glasgow instrumental rock'n'roll
combo The Beat Poets acquire a conscience and release a charity single, Silent
Night, in aid of the Big Issue. Suddenly they are required to play in front of
people four nights in a row to promote it. Those ten years have not been kind .
. .
Thursday: Glasgow's Archaos Club. Student night. ``Why do they dress like
that?'' our cigar-chewing record company boss inquired of no-one in particular.
``Because they can,'' replied the guitarist in a moment of insight. The young
crowd dance enthusiastically but the Beat Poets then dissipate any popularity
they'd built up by electing to lug their gear across the crowded dancefloor.
Friday: Your diarist cannot remember playing Aberdeen's Lemon Tree, having
found it necessary to have a stiff drink after a white-knuckle ride to get
there. Chauffeur Caroline is an experienced rally driver, whose forest stages
career was brought to an end by a ``wee bump'', which left her sister in
hospital for six months. Ironically the band is late because of her inability
to start the van. After half an hour's anxiety, the guitarist had diagnosed the
problem. It was in gear.
Saturday: The Kaisers play a stormer of a set at Edinburgh's Music Box. The
Beat Poets are pleased to have got through theirs without any more disasters.
The first hint of trouble came when the Fife-based keyboard player turned up
with his Hammond organ in the back of a milk float. His car has died and he has
hired a second van. It is normally used by Lloyd the milk, as the side clearly
reads. It doesn't smell, but it's not very rock'n'roll.
The bass player gets call from home. His girlfriend has roused the neighbours
after lying on the floor of their flat for an hour unable to move. She's
trapped a nerve in her back and he goes off home to look after her immediately
after the gig.
As a dep. bass player is being contacted, it becomes clear that all is not well
in the other half of the engine room of the good ship Beat Poets. We watch
horrified as the drummer's left arm swells visibly until he resembles a
spinach-fuelled Popeye, only without the muscle-power. An infection in his
elbow is later diagnosed and treated with powerful antibiotics, but for now
every blow on that snare drum is agony.
Sunday: The road back from Newcastle at 3am stretches out in front of the
diseased sextet carrying equipment up the fire escape of the Riverside Club.
The drummer has his arm in a sling. The bassist looks confused. The keyboard
player is driving a milk float. The tenor saxophonist is chain-smoking Marlboro
and wondering why he, the owner of the second lightest instrument in the
line-up, is carrying all the heaviest equipment. The trumpet player is busy
oiling his valves.
Later the saxophonist cracks and lurches mad-eyed at the guitarist, armed only
with a crisp packet, wounding him on the top lip and ensuring that he will
never be able to play the trumpet. The trumpet player buys him a drink. The
promoter has added another band to the bill. His own. Their guitarist has a
vintage electric guitar which he destroys during his performance for no
apparent reason.
Monday: The men from Scottish Television are being very patient. They have two
hours to film a band in a Glasgow city centre church and concert venue. The
drummer has his arm in a sling. The bassist and guitarist are wearing dark
glasses, not to look cool but because their eyes would frighten young children.
The guitarist has a scar on his top lip. The trumpeter is late, having forsaken
this pantomime to play for Cannon &amp; Ball at the King's next door. Sound move.
n The Beat Poets can be seen, eventually, on Scottish Television's Don't Look
Down tonight at 7pm. They play Glasgow's Cottier tomorrow, if they're spared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
