<HEADLINE>Recalled convict Beattie to be freed for Christmas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRISONER George Beattie has been granted parole and is due to be released today.
Beattie, who has constantly protested his innocence since being convicted of
murdering typist Margaret McLaughlin at Carluke, Lanarkshire, in 1973, was
recalled to Edinburgh's Saughton Prison two months ago.
This is understood to have been as a result of an argument with his parole
officer over timing of meetings to fit in with his job as a bus driver.
The parole board met earlier this week and agreed to his immediate liberation
subject to satisfactory follow-up arrangements.
Beattie was first paroled in 1986 but was recalled to prison six years later
after admitting a breach of the peace at the office of his then social worker.
He was released in 1994 pending an appeal against his conviction but it was
refused and he went back to jail. In March this year, he was released on parole
amid intense media interest. To escape the attention Beattie moved to Slough,
where he took a job as a bus driver.
His supporters condemned his recall in October over what appeared to be a
simple argument between Beattie, who has a low IQ, and his parole officer, and
the manner in which Thames Valley police officers broke down the door of his
house in the middle of the night and arrested him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Operation Blade</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782640</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IRRESPECTIVE of police claims that the so-called Operation Blade has proved a
resounding success deserving of repetition on a wider perspective, the whole
ill-advised media exercise seems to exhibit little understanding of the
delinquent mentality.
Far from being dissuaded by brash publicity, the ubiquitous psychopath is
awakened to the desirability of the knife as a means of unprovoked offence.
Criminal use of a blade has ever been, and ever will be, part of a vigorous and
competitive society.
That such unwelcome media publicity is counter-productive has plainly been
shown in the recent wanton murder of otherwise innocent victims. These outrages
may well have been prevented if a hitherto stable situation had simply been
left alone.
John R Stephen,
76 Randolph Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Body bonus</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Deedee Cuddihy, Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782641</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n A NEW study on HRT, hormone replacement therapy, has found an unexpected and
beneficial side-effect: it reduces the risk of Alzheimer's disease by up to
40%. The study by the European Menopause Society and reported in the current
issue of GP, the doctor's magazine, suggested that the use of HRT could both
reduce the risk of Alzheimer's disease and delay its onset by up to 10 to 12
years. It also confirmed that HRT can prevent heart disease in up to half of
users while the risk of breast cancer increased only with long-term use, over
10 years. Meanwhile the use of HRT is well established for the control of
menopausal symptoms and the prevention of osteoporosis, or thinning of the
bones.
n HERBAL medicine, used since time immemorial, is one of the best known and
trusted of the alternative therapies. At its simplest it's a soothing cup of
herbal tea. But herbs can be used for a whole range of ailments, from chronic
fatigue syndrome to eating disorders. If you would like to find out more about
using herbs but don't know where to start, try The Women's Guide to Herbal
Medicine (Hamish Hamilton, #18.99), by Carol Rogers, a Glasgow author. It
explains how to use herbs safely in the home and under the guidance of a herbal
practitioner. A medical herbalist, Carol Rogers offers sensible nutritional and
lifestyle advice to complement herbal remedies and a whole section focuses on
health maintenance and the prevention of disease.
n SO you've had a heart attack and you want to avoid another. Then you should
read Heart Attack: How to Return to a Full, Healthy and Active Lifestyle
(HarperCollins, #6.99).
n WE are in the throes of a flu epidemic and this raises the question: how
effective is vaccination? Well, the results are encouraging. The latest
research from Britain, America, and the Netherlands shows that the flu vaccine
does offer considerable protection, particularly if it is an annual
vaccination. Deaths among the elderly can be reduced by as much as 40% and it
also reduces the number needing admittance to hospital by up to 60%.
n WHILE many of us view the approaching festive season with varying degrees of
dread and excitement, people who live or work with a problem drinker see it as
a time when their alcohol-dependent partner will be presented with even greater
temptations.
Now private alcohol counsellor and educationist Elspeth Harte offers the
following advice on How To Cope With Someone's Drinking.
``I am not anti-drink, but my experience as an addiction counsellor has shown
me that alcohol abuse has a knock-on effect, causing tremendous problems, not
just for the drinker but for their family, friends, and colleagues.
``This is particularly apparent in cases where someone who drinks too much
fails to acknowledge the fact and expects other people to fit in with their
behaviour.
``So you get wives altering the household routine, colleagues covering up at
work and so on.
``No-one should have to tie themselves in knots because of someone else's
drinking. It is possible to limit the damage.''
q-For further information on How To Cope With Someone Else's Drinking contact
Elspeth Harte on 01698 853041.
n HOW effective is nutritional medicine? Are you likely to improve your rate of
recovery by changing your diet? Find out more with a new book, Effective
Nutritional Medicine, a useful guide backed by scientific evidence. The report
covers the implication of food in disorders such as heart disease, cancer,
psychological disorders and reproduction. Copies cost #5, including postage and
package, from the British Society for Allergy and Environmental Medicine and
the British Society for Nutritional Medicine, PO Box 28 Totton, Southampton
SO40 2ZA.
n AMONG the plethora of Christmas cards on offer are those supplied by the
Mouth and Foot Painting Artists. These highly original cards, which provide a
much needed life-line for handicapped people, offering them a chance to earn
money and some independence, was started back in 1956 by the painter Erich
Stegmann as a self-help co-operative. A polio victim, he grew up without the
use of his arms yet he built a highly successful career in Germany by painting
with a mouth-held brush. Today this international self-help co-operative
produces Christmas cards and calendars. One such painter is Glasgow artist
Edward Rainery, paralysed from the neck down due to a diving accident. He says
the Mouth and Foot Painting Association helped to make him an established
artist. Further information from the Mouth and Foot Painting Artists, 9
Inverness Place, London W2.
Compiled by Deedee Cuddihy and Ann Shaw
</TEXT>
