<DOCNO>GH951221-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>End of bargain bonanza for Christmas shoppers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Buie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stand by for a return to the traditional `January sales'. Elizabeth Buie
explains why it is the end of the line for pre-festive season price slashing
COUNTING today, there are only four shopping days left till Christmas.
Unfortunately, you're not likely to pick up a last-minute bargain for Great
Auntie Jeannie or your nearest and dearest before the 25th.
For, unlike last year, virtually no shops are having pre-Christmas sales.
Instead, it is back to the traditional Boxing Day queues outside the shop
doors, with eager customers poised at the starting blocks ready to pick up the
``monster'' bargain of a living-room suite knocked down to #200, or a cashmere
coat for a tenner.
The question is whether this return to the traditional sales pattern is a sign
that the retail industry is returning to health after the long malaise of the
recession.
Most analysts believe that the industry is actually retreating from the
discount culture that has infected it for the past few years and, in trade
jargon, is going back to ``trading prime'' with seasonal stock clearances.
In fact, last year's rash of pre-Christmas sales was the result of poor stock
management throughout the year and a sign of trading distress. By the time
Christmas was beckoning, shops had found themselves over-run with goods which
they needed to clear as quickly as possible.
This year, however, according to Richard Perks, senior retail analyst with
Verdict Research, retailers have not had the capital to build up a large stock
of goods - and therefore have not been under pressure to clear their shelves so
quickly. In the case of others, the bitter experience of the past few years has
taught better stock management. In fact, in the case of some retailers,
business has picked up to the extent that they have come close to running
short.
In addition, many retailers may have discovered that early sales last year
proved counterproductive - they found that customers were waiting till the last
minute before buying anything, and ultimately buying less.
This season's sales, when they do come, are likely to offer fewer items than
consumers have come to expect in the past, but still good value and in some
cases with bigger discounts, largely because of stores' more-disciplined stock
management.
The Burton Group is a classic case of a retail company which has completely
reversed its sales policy. It felt that customers had come to perceive its
goods as ``always on sale'' and therefore reverted from discounting goods most
of the time to offering what it terms as a ``first price, right price'' policy
combined with genuine stock-clearance seasonal sales. Last year the Burton
Group spent 33% of its time ``trading prime'' compared with 68% this year. The
strategy appears to have been successful. Profits before tax in 1994 were
#41.1m compared with #98.6m this year.
Others are beginning to follow suit, recognising that year-round sales pull the
sector down. Customers begin to think they are not being offered a genuine
sale, just a general lowering of prices, and are not attracted into the shops,
defeating the very purpose of discounting merchandise.
While supermarkets can engage in a price war on key lines, such as bananas or
baked beans, it is harder for clothing retailers. Most men buy black socks, and
most women have a range of ``Marks &amp; Sparks knickers'', but these are not items
that have to be bought at a particular time of year.
Dr Steve Burt, acting director of the Institute for Retail Studies at Stirling
University, explained: ``If you have a sale all the year round or for five
months of the year, customers do not feel the urgency of buying in the three
weeks before Christmas because they know that the same prices will be available
in the New Year or Easter or summer.''
The hard times experienced by so many consumers in the 1990s appear to have
influenced their shopping habits. This Christmas, shoppers on the whole appear
to be looking for more value for money than before. Perfume, music and videos,
as well as small electrical goods are proving the most popular gifts, although
at the higher end of the market, there are some reports of personal computers
being bought for Christmas.
``They are not going so much for high-ticket items, but lower prices and better
value for money. The 90s say two things: we have had a very prolonged
recession, and although there has been an upturn over the past two years, there
has not been a feel-good factor; and there was a demographic peak hitting the
80s, so that the people who were in their 20s in the 1980s are in their 30s in
the 1990s and do not have as much disposable income,'' said Mr Perks.
According to James May, director-general of the British Retail Consortium, the
recent upturn in sales has come as a great relief to many clothing retailers
whose profits were badly hit by a long hot summer followed by a mild autumn.
The weak pound appears to be encouraging tourists to come to Britain for their
Christmas shopping. And while the excesses in luxury gift spending of the 1980s
have virtually disappeared, some of Britain's larger cities are reporting the
arrival of a new breed of high-rolling spender - the new capitalists from the
former Eastern bloc.
``In London we have seen some very funny money coming in from places like
Russia with people buying large quantities of jewellery and clothing and paying
for it with fistfuls of dollar bills produced out of rather grubby suitcases,''
said Mr May.
``But that is a small tip of the retail trade. I don't get the impression that
there is a lot of ostentatious spending going on at the moment,'' he added.
Dr Burt said that it would not be until next month that we could really gauge
how good a Christmas this has been.
``I think retailers would like to return to the traditional pattern. Possibly
they will go back to heavier discounts and sales lasting a shorter period,'' he
said.
``Retailers are becoming more realistic and they are also trying to recover
sales figures and margins in particular. It is much more in their interest to
get back to standard pricing and sales, rather than an incremental drift
down,'' he said.
If the post-Christmas sales also produce the bigger price cuts that are being
predicted, it will also be good for consumers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bottomley under attack for backing lottery watchdog</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782643</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Heritage Secretary Virginia Bottomley yesterday launched a strong
defence of National Lottery watchdog Peter Davis and accused Labour of trying
to hound him out of office.
Answering an Opposition emergency question in the Commons, Mrs Bottomley said
there was no question of Mr Davis's honesty or integrity being in question over
his acceptance of free flights from GTech.
She also announced that Anne Rafferty QC will head the inquiry into bribery
claims by Virgin Atlantic chief Richard Branson against Guy Snowden, chief of
GTech, a stakeholder in lottery operator Camelot.
Shadow National Heritage Secretary Jack Cunningham forced Mrs Bottomley to the
despatch box to make a statement on the affair after her decision on Tuesday
that Mr Davis could keep his #84,000 a year job as Oflot director-general.
Dr Cunningham accused both Mr Davis and Mrs Bottomley of showing ``an abysmal
lack of judgment'' and called for a code of conduct for regulators of private
monopolies to avoid further controversies.
However, Mrs Bottomley rounded on him, insisting Labour's ``victimisation'' of
the regulator, whom it had ``pursued and hounded'', showed it was ``unfit now
or ever to govern''.
Mrs Bottomley said she had met Mr Davis on Tuesday to discuss the free flights
provided for him and his staff in the United States.
To Opposition jeers, she said: ``My confidence in the director-general remains.
There is no doubt about his integrity.''
The visits to the United States had taken place some months after Oflot had
awarded the main licence to Camelot.
``The director-general considered the issues raised with care, recorded them
thoroughly and made no attempt to hide them.''
The Minister continued: ``I have told the Director General that I do not think
that his acceptance of the flights was wise in the context of his role as
regulator of the lottery.''
Mrs Bottomley said it was inevitable that Mr Davis needed to ``work closely''
with Camelot.
``I have told him that this fact makes it the more important that he should
maintain a proper distance from the company and its constituent parts and to be
seen to do so, taking all steps to guard against any possible misunderstanding
of his actions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland is a critical brand in the British mix</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782644</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DANIEL Clark mistakenly attributes editorial in the New York Times Magazine to
copy produced by the British Tourist Authority (December 16).
We do work closely with many American travel writers to encourage them to write
about travel to Britain but we do not, or wish to, have editorial control. As
your readers will appreciate, independent advice from a journalist is
invaluable when planning a trip, as indeed is a contact for more information on
Scotland for the rest of the UK, such as BTA's popular information service in
New York.
I would like to reassure your readers that we at the BTA in the United States
see Scotland as a critical brand in the mix that is Britain. A new advertising
campaign in partnership with the Scottish Tourist Board kicks off in the spring
to encourage more Americans to visit Scotland.
Two press trips are already planned for early next year to bring more American
journalists to Scotland - concentrating not only on your cosmopolitan cities
and beautiful countryside but also focusing on Burns and the Charles Rennie
Mackintosh anniversary celebrations.
Rest assured, we will continue to work closely with the Scottish tourist
industry, and with a little bit of help from Hollywood, promote Scotland
throughout the USA.
Jeff Hamblin,
Executive Vice President, The Americas,
British Tourist Authority,
Thames Tower,
Black's Road,
Hammersmith, London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Burns events planned</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782645</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAJOR celebrations to mark the bicentenary of the death of Robert Burns will
take place in London and Scotland next year, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
told the Commons yesterday.
He said there would be a major event in London on January 31. There would be an
event in Scotland during the year, probably in the South-west.
Mr Forsyth's announcement came after Labour's Brian Donohoe (Cunninghame South)
made an appeal for funds for the celebrations, which he said were a
``shambles'' because of a lack of private sponsorship.
He called on the Scottish Office to make up the shortfall, but Mr Forsyth said
he could not give such a commitment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why good businesses are going under every day</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782646</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM rather confused with reports on the economy, inflation, and tourism. As a
businessman, I find it very important that this information is correct so that
I can use it to gauge my performance and plan future strategies.
It has just been announced that tourism is on the up again by 9% in the latter
part of this year. This follows an announcement earlier that there had been a
16% increase in the first six months of 1995. However, like practically
everyone in the industry from hoteliers, shopkeepers, coach operators, and the
like, I disagree with these findings.
My latest venture, The Invernairn Mill Visitors Centre, which has only been
open a year, has no previous figures to compare with, other than these
statistics. As one of my sons remarked, using this information in our business
is like him using a Ford workshop manual to repair a Mercedes motor car.
I embarked on this venture because the Scottish Tourist Board insisted that
tourism was on the up year after year. Earlier this year, however, the new
chairman took over and announced that over the last five years tourism had
actually been on the decline, a welcome clarification of fact.
Good businesses are going under every day. More often than not it is not
through bad management or lack of effort. It is more likely to be things
outwith their control, such as ever-increasing rates and overpriced utilities,
all brought about to fund salaries of diabolical magnitude for top executives
incomprehensible to the ordinary working people, our customers, who find
themselves in an increasingly poor financial state with increasing lack of job
security being a major contributing factor.
If we as a nation are to survive, there has to be a massive change in the way
we think and do things. The establishment cannot keep biting the hand that
feeds it without dire consequences.
The business community supports the country but it would appear that no-one in
authority is hearing this. They are obliterating the workforces through
short-sightedness, self-centred monetary greed, which is projected towards
higher management with dire consequences for the working man struggling with
the machinations of politics with no reward.
I am of the firm belief that my views are widespread and that such policies are
having a devastating effect on people's lives.
R Henderson,
Invernairn Mill
Visitors Centre,
Balmakeith Estate,
Nairn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Camerata Scotland, RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kenny Mathieson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782647</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAMERATA Scotland is the new name adopted recently by the Chamber Orchestra of
the National Youth Orchestra of Scotland, for reasons which will be entirely
obvious. They began on familiar ground with an elegant, well-judged reading of
Haydn's Symphony No 96 under conductor William Conway. The bright, nicely
burnished strings, crisply pointed woodwind, and a small but sharply focused
brass section were all impressive, as was the finely controlled sense of
structural awareness in the unfolding music.
The strings responded equally impressively when called upon to produce greater
breadth and depth of sound in Sibelius's ravishing Pelleas and Melisande Suite.
The music is in a very different vein to that of Debussy's better known work on
this theme, and Conway drew taut, richly expressive playing from his ensemble,
enhanced by three excellent woodwind soloists.
They began the second half with a contemporary work by the Edinburgh-based
composer Edward Harper. Fiddler of the Reels is a highly effective short work
for string orchestra, in which Harper teasingly inserts snatches of a
reel-derived figure into a rather darker musical language, then allows the folk
idiom to emerge in a colourful sunburst before extending the original process
in more complex fashion.
The ensemble absorbed its challenging rhythms with great assurance, and that
confidence carried over into Dvorak's Czech Suite, a work which is something of
a rarity on the concert stage. It may be a relatively minor work in his canon,
but it is a substantial and highly idiomatic one, and the orchestra, with wind
and brass restored, gave a sparkling, highly sympathetic account of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cemetery check</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782648</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE body of Ukrainian emigre Iwan Romanowskyj, 74, stabbed to death in
Gloucester 10 years ago, is being exhumed from a cemetery today. John Evans,
36, of Gloucester, was remanded recently accused of killing Mr Romanowskyj.
Redwood raided
SUPPORTERS of Tory MP John Redwood could find themselves short of a bit of
Christmas cheer after thieves broke into his office in his constituency and
made off with whisky, claret, Champagne, and sherry. Each bottle has the House
of Commons logo on the label.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charity must mean business in the real world</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Michelle Hegarty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>open forum feature</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782649</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RECENT Herald Opinion article proclaimed charities had become ``warped by
association'' with commercial sector values, used doubtful fundraising tactics,
and employed (an obviously unnecessary) ``professional cadre'' of staff.
Unhappily, this served to reaffirm that the word charity, in itself, has become
synonymous with old workhouse and do-gooder connotations that bode no further
elaboration.
After all, everyone knows what a charity is. Goodness knows, there are enough
of them - approximately 23,500 in Scotland with research suggesting another
1000 formed each year. However, despite being pretty good at promoting their
causes, charities seem to be poor at improving general understanding of their
role.
Charities began as voluntary institutions raising alms for the disadvantaged,
but persistent erosion of the welfare state has meant an increasing reliance on
their role; not just as cushioning, but as specialist service providers filling
growing health and social care gaps. Subsequently, many charities, particularly
the large national and international ones, have developed into sophisticated
organisations managing substantial revenues and resources as part of their day
to day ``business''.
This year the Scottish Council for Spastics will spend #18m on direct provision
of services to some 2000 children and adults with cerebral palsy and other
disabilities. The range of specialist services provided by the organisation -
including education, therapy, employment, residential and day care - requires
sustained financial planning and development. In many respects, therefore, the
Council, as with other large voluntary organisations, is like a commercial
business and has similar assets, cash-flow problems and regulations to meet. In
order to function competently and fulfil its contractual obligations it
requires structure, planning, job division and secure funding.
General misunderstanding of the term charity masks a plethora of business-like
principles and attitudes which must exist in voluntary organisations if they
are to effectively match resources to the needs of their clients. It must be
recognised there is a vast divide within the charitable sector and that
not-for-profit voluntary organisations and one-off fundraising causes are two
ends of an expanding spectrum. Nevertheless, every type of organisation within
this spectrum has to adhere to the same stringent regulations and fundraising
legalities. For voluntary organisations, public perception is also a dominant
concern and the slightest sniff of bad publicity can rock the whole sector in a
way few commercial groups experience.
To sustain their role, therefore, voluntary organisations must have a
responsible attitude which seeks to educate, influence, and elicit support
without causing supporters to be turned off. This is a fine line. However, it
is not our business to hide the injustices of the world or the many needs which
society at large cannot or will not pay for. There will always be an element of
guilt in charitable donation, but that is not to say that with fundraising
tactics the end always justifies the means.
Real life images of despair, need or triumph are frequently used because they
confront people to think and act. But integrity has a large part to play,
because many voluntary organisations are ultimately seeking to change the
attitudes or rules which have made their role necessary. The Scottish Council
for Spastics seeks to influence and change attitudes through a positive
portrayal of disabled people. We take this so seriously we are changing our
name to Capability Scotland in order to more effectively facilitate integration
of disabled people into society. In a way we are trying to do ourselves out of
a job although the likelihood of that, in the light of dwindling state aid, is
slim.
One obvious implication of the increasing number of charities is the struggle
to secure voluntary income from an overcrowded marketplace which has many other
competing attractions, such as the National Lottery, for consumer spending.
Some charities are fashionable or appealing by their very nature but so many
more have to plan in advance where voluntary income can be secured from. For
big, well- established voluntary organisations the standard fundraising tools
are no longer enough on their own. The Scottish Council for Spastics will be
looking at methods which serve several objectives; the current business
breakfast series, sponsored by Scottish Airports Ltd, is an example of an
income-generating activity which also enables us to communicate our aims and
foster closer links with the corporate sector.
We have to constantly adapt and develop to know our supporters and cultivate
means of keeping them loyal. To many people this will sound like good customer
services and it is; the voluntary sector has not been slow to learn or
innovate, yet this persistent incompatibility between ``doing good work'' and
efficient management persists.
How would the public and corporate sector wish to see an organisation such as
the Scottish Council for Spastics spend its #18m on service delivery? If we are
to fulfil our role we must do it efficiently and effectively.
Michelle Hegarty is press &amp; public relations officer for The Scottish Council
for Spastics (soon to be Capability Scotland).
</TEXT>
