<HEADLINE>Action on chequebook journalism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782650</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOVES to curb chequebook journalism, particularly payments to witnesses in
criminal cases, were promised by Press Complaints Commission chairman Lord
Wakeham last night.
The Tory former Cabinet Minister told the Lords in a debate on the issue that
he was proposing a new protocol to the self-regulatory code of practice for
newspapers and magazines.
His disclosure follows public concern over the payments made by newspapers for
the stories of witnesses in the trial of mass murderer Rosemary West.
Lord Wakeham said he had begun discussions with editors and proprietors of
newspapers and magazines to find a solution to the serious issue which his
proposed protocol aimed to address.
He stressed he could not guarantee he would be able to negotiate a satisfactory
agreement but declared he would have ``a determined attempt'' to achieve one.
The Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay of Clashfern, responding to the debate for the
Government, said he ``warmly welcomed'' the protocol that Lord Wakeham had
offered to negotiate with newspaper and magazine proprietors.
He said if Lord Wakeham's proposals could be made to work, then it was a
preferable way forward than by legislation, which would be ``difficult''.
</TEXT>
