<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Flying start</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782651</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITHIN a fortnight of The Herald Foundation for Women's Health opening at the
Royal Infirmary, Glasgow, two cases of gynaecological cancer were detected. As
one nurse remarked: ``If we never detect another early case of cancer this year
the clinic has already justified its existence.''
Both women have already started treatment and are progressing satisfactorily.
Normally it would have taken several weeks, when symptoms would by then be more
obvious, for these patients to be diagnosed.
They would be logged for hospital visits then tests and treatment over a period
of months, often having to see a string of duty doctors in different locations.
Although cancer was not suspected by these patients' GPs, they did recognise
that each woman had a gynaecological problem.
Now, thanks to the innovative Herald Foundation Clinic for Women's Health,
women at risk undergo examination with the most advanced equipment and, if
necessary, receive a management-of-care plan in a single visit.
Referral to the clinic, which deals only with secondary investigations, must be
made through family doctors. Although it has been open for less than two
months, it is already fully booked, and there is a short waiting-list.
If the list should grow too long then an extra session will be added to cope
with the demand.
Response to the project is positive, with many women remarking on the
clinic's calming and visually pleasing atmosphere.
For the medical staff, the surroundings represent an amazing transformation
from their former use as a Victorian operating theatre. Paintings have been
loaned by a dozen Scottish artists, including Elizabeth Blackadder, June Carey
and Jacki Parry.
The decor, based on imaginative use of pastel colours and designed by Drew
Plunkett of Glasgow School of Art, has attracted comment. ``It's now a pleasure
to come to work,'' says one of the nurses.
In the majority of cases women need visit the clinic once only, hence the name
it has gained in medical circles - One-Stop clinic.
As Dr Helen McEwan, consultant gynaecologist and obstetrician at the Royal
Infirmary, says, this is the whole purpose of the clinic - to reduce the number
of visits women have to make, and to ensure that those visits are carried out
speedily in comfortable surroundings. The Herald Clinic for Women's Health has
certainly fulfilled that remit.
While more than #50,000 has been raised through generous donations from Herald
readers, we are still some way short of the sum required to cover running costs
for an initial two-year period. Those wanting to make a special Christmas gift
to the clinic should send their donations to The Herald Foundation for Women's
Health, 195 Albion St, Glasgow G1 1QP. Those who wish to donate by covenant
should write to the same address for details, including the word Covenant on
the envelope.
</TEXT>
