<HEADLINE>Agreement reached in principle with Scottish farmers over the purchase of their holdings End in sight for British Coal tenants</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782652</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE year-long saga over the sale of British Coal's farms in Scotland is finally
drawing to a close. According to estate agent Bell Ingram: ``Agreement has now
been reached in principle with all 57 of British Coal's agricultural tenants in
Scotland over the purchase of their holdings.''
David Gwyther, the director of Bell Ingram who handled the sale, added: ``It's
been quite a long and complicated process with a number of difficult issues
needing to be resolved. In particular, the valuation of milk quotas, treatment
of tenants' improvements, and British Coal provisions on future windfall gains
and environmental liabilities have all caused concern to prospective purchasers.
``However, we are very pleased that all of these issues have been resolved and
that every one of the farm tenants in Scotland has opted to buy his or her
holding.''
However, not all the tenants are quite so happy with the deal they have been
offered, and several are seeking amendments to the conditions of sale.
Jimmy Wilson who farms at Lumphinnans, near Cowdenbeath, and who is also
president of Fife and Kinross NFU, commented: ``We may have accepted in
principle and agreed a price, but there are a number of conditions which
individual farmers wish to have altered. In my own case the boundaries are
ill-defined and I am waiting to see the title deeds.
``I also have a neighbour where British Coal wants to retain the shooting and
fishing rights for 99 years at #1 per year.''
Other conditions include the proviso that the land should only be used for
farming purposes. Mr Wilson said he could understand British Coal wanting to
prevent anyone becoming involved in mining operations, but he felt that if
taken to its logical conclusion this would preclude letting holiday houses,
running a contracting business or taking horses at livery. No diversification
is permitted for a period of 20 years.
Mr Wilson remarked: ``It's belt and braces and just altogether too much.''
Originally British Coal, at the instigation of the President of the Board of
Trade, Michael Heseltine, planned to sell the farms in one lot believing this
would be the best and quickest course of action.
However, the tenants were outraged at not having the opportunity to bid for
their farms. An action committee was formed, questions were asked in the House
of Commons, most notably by the Labour MP Martin O'Neill, and the NFU was
called in to champion the cause.
Under pressure, British Coal relented and agreed to talk with the tenants, but
it soon became clear that the valuations of the respective parties were miles
apart, with the farmers arguing they were entitled to a near-50% discount on
open market value. This view was supported by independent experts and bankers.
Similarly, there were difficulties surrounding future pollution problems from
abandoned underground workings. The tenants took the line that British Coal
should remain liable.
If the tenants and British Coal can thrash out their remaining differences the
various deals should be signed and sealed by December 31, with payment for the
farms made a month later.
In England negotiations are still proceeding between British Coal and farmers.
</TEXT>
