<HEADLINE>Assault claim in `right to die' case. Lack of emergency means doctors require consent to continue feeding, says lawyer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN, Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782653</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOCTORS may be breaking the law by keeping the patient in the ``right to die''
case alive by artificial means, it was argued yesterday.
The present treatment provided for 52-year-old Mrs Janet Johnstone, food and
liquid through a naso-gastric tube, could amount to an assault, Ms Lynda Clark
QC, counsel for Law Hospital NHS Trust claimed.
This was because the patient, who has been in a deep coma for nearly four
years, cannot give consent to what is happening, there is no longer any
emergency justifying the treatment and no hope of recovery.
Ms Clark also argued that doctors would be acting lawfully if they withdrew her
treatment.
In the first case of its kind in Scotland, the trust has gone to the Court of
Session to ask Lord Cameron to declare that it can discontinue the artificial
feeding which is keeping Mrs Johnstone alive, without the risk of prosecution
for murder or culpable homicide.
The judge has been told that if the feeding tube was withdrawn, as doctors
propose, she would die of dehydration, possibly within 10-14 days.
Mrs Johnstone's relatives agree with the hospital and say that it would be
kinder to let her die peacefully and with dignity than keep her in her present
condition when there is no hope of recovery.
The action is being defended by the Lord Advocate, in the public interest, and
a guardian appointed by the court to represent Mrs Johnstone.
Ms Clark submitted that the underlying legal principles governing medical
intervention were relatively simple.
In the case of a rational adult, treatment, even to save a life, was lawful
only if the patient consented. However, in emergencies, treatment was justified
without consent because of necessity and in the best interests of the patient.
For example, if a patient was brought in unconscious with a heart attack, that
could be treated. But if doctors found a lump which they thought might be
malignant they could not operate to remove it unless it was immediately
life-threatening. They would have to wait until the patient became conscious
and consented to an operation.
In Mrs Johnstone's case there had been an emergency when she became unconscious
after being admitted with a drugs overdose. Doctors were justified in
continuing to treat her in until she was diagnosed by several experts as being
in a persistent vegetative state with no hope of recovery.
At that point doctors took the view that it was no longer in her best interests
to receive treatment, including artificial feeding, which was doing her no
good, although it was prolonging her life.
This threw into question the whole legality of continuing to feed Mrs
Johnstone, of Allanton, in Lanarkshire, artifically.
The question was, what was the legal justification for this? Ms Clark added:
``In my submission there is none in law. So, technically, it could be regarded
as an assault on Mrs Johnstone.''
Putting a tube down her throat was saved from being an assault initially
because of the emergency and because it was in the patient's best interests
when there was some hope of recovery. That was no longer the situation.
Ms Clark said her basic proposition was that, if treatment was not necessary in
the best interests of the patient, it must be lawful to stop it.
The question was not whether it was in the best interests of Mrs Johnstone to
die but whether it was in her best interests to have her life artifically
prolonged.
She went on to discuss the House of Lords case involving Tony Bland, who was
also in a persistent vegetative state following the Hillsborough football
disaster.
In that case the judges had ruled there was no absolute obligation on doctors
to prolong a patient's life regardless of the circumstances.
Ms Clark said, ``If the justification for intervening with a patient who lacks
the capacity to to consent lies in the fact that the treatment is provided in
his best interests, it must follow that treatment may and ultimately should be
discontinued where it is no longer in the patient's best interest to provide
it.''
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
