<HEADLINE>Now for a commercial break</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Stewart McIntosh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<FLAG>Feature commercial industrial property</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782654</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TAKE a measure of whisky, add a dash of incomprehension, then enrich with a
taste of Chicago - and you have the mix for an innovative way of marketing a
new building. Even although there is little to be seen but the scaffolding, the
canny Co-op is attracting interest for its redevelopment of No9 George Square -
where 65,000 sq.ft of new office space is being created behind the
``Chicagoesque'' retained facades overlooking the square and South Hanover
Street.
Its prominent site attracted a whisky firm whose advertising campaign plays on
braw Scots phrases like ``ilka dram a ferlie'' and ``unco sonsie''. Using the
scaffolding at No.9 as the backdrop, the first of the TV ads features a baffled
young man in a George Square phone box who is calling his granny to ask what
``unco sonsie'' means.
Bill Colville of letting agents DTZ Debenham Thorpe pulled off this free TV
marketing coup and claims that the completed project will be equally sonsie.
``The building has an enviable location - a factor which has led to requests
from organisations interested in using it as a focus for events. I was a bit
bemused when we were first approached for the TV advert, however, the filming
went smoothly and it's good to see the finished result on TV.''
Although filming requirements can be complicated, Colville reckons that letting
agents should seize any such opportunities of pushing their clients' buildings
into the limelight - or the TV screens of the nation. ``You have to consider
insurance as well as the possible delays to construction work - and you have to
get agreement from all parties involved. But if everything goes well it can
increase the profile of a scheme, which can't be a bad thing,'' he says.
Using photographs taken during the original film shoot, Colville carried his
marketing campaign a step further by organising a photo caption competition for
city agents - the people most likely to find tenants for the building. The
winner was the kenspeckle David Griffin of Griffin Webster partnership who came
up with the sleekit, but topical, caption: ``All this to avoid empty rates!'' -
which won him a 4.5-litre bottle of the hard stuff.
</TEXT>
