<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leaving for the hols, and a not-so-merry time is had by all</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782655</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WAS the kind of last day before the Christmas hols of which King Herod or
the unreformed Scrooge would have thoroughly approved.
Government whips were hunting down rebels, Labour its non-attenders who had
fled to distant parts like Barbados, Sri Lanka and a cottage in rural Ireland,
while Mr Mike Watson (Glasgow Central) had fled so efficiently that nobody knew
where he was. Both whips' offices are likely to give those concerned a horrible
1996.
As purely Scottish committees take over examination of more Scottish
legislation, the Tory whips have lost much of what used to be the dreaded
punishment of sentencing an awkward English Tory to service on a Scottish Bill
committee. A couple of months on, say, the Sewerage (Scotland) Bill committee
could break the proudest spirit.
Mr Michael Forsyth, Scottish Secretary, got nearest to being Christmassy,
promising the Scottish Opposition that some of them might receive invitations
to a grand bash he's having next month in honour of the bicentenary of the
national bard. Mr George Robertson made clear he would rather have a General
Election.
When the Rev. Martin Smyth from the Ulster Unionist bench suggested closer
co-operation in promoting tourism between Northern Ireland and Scotland Mr
Forsyth agreed, adding: ``We Unionists must stick together on this and other
matters.'' Ministers will doubtless be asking Santa if he can deliver them
Ulster Unionist votes in 1996.
The Opposition took off in full cry after the lottery watchdog, Mr Peter Davis,
rather in the style of wolves pursuing a sledge. The lovely Virginia must have
been sorely tempted to throw Mr Davis to them, the traditional Russian device
for preserving at least some of those on board. But, no. Virginia, looking ever
more like a former head girl at Enid Blyton's immortal Mallory Towers, kept Mr
Davis on board.
She did also carefully get it on the record that Mr Davis had assured her that
there were no skeletons in his cupboard and that she had advised him to
``maintain a proper distance'' from Camelot and its constituent parts.
In the eyes of her back benchers, a small halo appeared to encircle her golden
head and the chaps decided to gallantly ride to the rescue. ``Gutter
politics'', ``McCarthyite smears'' and other Yuletide greetings were lobbed at
the Labour benches who continued to decline to put a charitable construction on
Mr Davis's activities. Virginia's suggestion that he had saved the taxpayers'
money by not hiring a private jet for his tour of US state lotteries produced
only derision.
Even the Speaker, most charitable of ladies, insulted the Scottish Labour
Opposition for Christmas. Temporarily forgetting Ms Rachel Squire's name when
the Dunfermline West MP rose to ask a question, Ms Boothroyd said: ``I mean the
pretty one.'' Mr John Maxton (Cathart), Mr George Foulkes (Carrick) and others
sitting immediately adjacent to Ms Squire looked hurt.
The Leader of the House, Mr Tony Newton, announcing the business for the first
week back in the new year, said pathetically that no-one had wished him a merry
Christmas. ``I do,'' said Madam Speaker kindly. So does the Sketch to its
readers.
</TEXT>
