<HEADLINE>Cranberry co-op offers inspiration</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG> </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782656</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRANBERRY sauce, the traditional accompaniment for turkey, may be a special
topic of discussion over the dinner table in some farm circles this year
following a visit to the US under the aegis of the Scottish Agricultural
Organisation Society - the umbrella organisation for farm co-operatives.
The fish farming co-op Scot Trout recently completed a study trip to the Ocean
Spray Cranberry co-operative in Massachusetts and returned with more
information than most of us would appreciate on the history of the cranberry.
The North American Indians, for instance, mixed the berries with dried deer
meat and melted fat. The resulting concoction was used to poultice arrow wounds.
The Scottish visitors were more interested in modern applications and were
particularly keen to study marketing methods under a co-operative system. ``We
were looking for a co-operative whose members, like those of Scot Trout, are
totally dependent on the co-op for the sale of their entire farm output,'' said
James Graham, SAOS project director. ``We also wanted a co-operative which was
strong on value adding, operated in an international market, had strong brand
development, and was significantly more developed than Scot Trout.
``We couldn't find a co-operative with all these features in the UK so we went
to Ocean Spray which fitted the profile well.'' Ocean Spray was founded 50
years ago, has a membership of 750 cranberry growers and 150 grapefruit
growers. It generates annual sales of more than $1200m and enters the list of
America's top 500 industrial corporations as number 332.
The visit highlighted several issues related to developing and managing a
strong co-operative structure.
``The massive investment made to create and then protect the Ocean Spray brand
was impressive,'' said Mr Graham.
``At Scot Trout we don't have sufficient profit margin to allow us to go to
that level of branding. Our market place is also different. Major manufacturers
drive the US food sector, while in Britain we are much more in the hands of the
major retail multiples.''
The Scot Trout delegation also noted the level of profits retained by Ocean
Spray every year to finance re-investment and development. ``In our system we
tend to return profits to members each year - maybe we should adopt the Ocean
Spray approach and seek to build stronger businesses which will then be of
greater value to members,'' said Mr Graham.
When the Scots met some of the grower members they found real commitment to the
co-operative ideal. ``They knew they could often sell their crops for more
immediate cash than they would get from Ocean Spray, but they appreciated the
security of having a long-term market into which they could sell.
</TEXT>
