<HEADLINE>Lesson from students</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782657</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIRST, England's coach broke down. Then the wheels came off on the field as
another set of students made Mike Atherton's team look in need of extra tuition
before next week's fourth Test.
A year ago, it was the kids from Australia's Cricket Academy who caused great
embarrassment with two wins in as many days over the Ashes tourists. Now, the
South African Students XI recovered from a perilous 23 for five to reach 253
for six when bad light ended play an hour early.
Mark Ilott struck four times inside seven new-ball overs. But Nic Pothas, a
23-year-old from the Rand Afrikaans University in Johannesburg, hit a maiden
first-class century and finished unbeaten on 141, with a 6 plus eighteen 4s. He
received fine support from Mark Davis (44) and spinner Nicky Boje (42 not out)
in rescuing an apparently wrecked innings.
England's day began badly when their coach ground to a halt between Durban and
Pietermaritzburg because of a fuel blockage. A substitute vehicle arrived but
start of play had to be put back half-an-hour.
In addition, Jason Gallian, having arrived in South Africa the previous day
following his call-up from Pakistan, slipped and fell on his back when bowling.
Later, the Lancashire opener suffered a dislocated left little finger while
trying to intercept a Pothas cover drive. Physio Wayne Morton quickly repaired
the damage, Gallian returned to the fray, and should be able to bat without
difficulty today.
