<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#3m plan for hospital at Cumbernauld</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782658</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HOSPITAL for frail elderly patients in Cumbernauld is to be built in
partnership with the Scotcare group through the Private Finance Initiative,
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth announced yesterday.
The #3m hospital will have 40 beds in single rooms for continuing care
patients, and 30 day hospital places offering chiropody, physiotherapy,
occupational therapy and other services. It is expected to open early in 1997.
The patients at the new hospital will receive consultant-led care through the
Lanarkshire Healthcare NHS Trust.
Scotcare, which claims to be Scotland's largest provider of independent health
care, already operates eight homes, including a specialist Alcohol Related
Dementia Unit and the Brain Injury Rehabilitation Unit near Newmains.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
