<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>He's out of his tree</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782659</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
When Ian Smith's group give wooden performances it's guaranteed to delight -
and disturb. Sara Villiers enjoys the alternative street theatre
THERE can surely be no sight more calculated to inspire guilt in the hearts of
Christmas shoppers who have just purchased their festive tree than the
spectacle of The Nervous Forest. This modern-day version of Birnam Wood is
currently making sporadic appearances around Glasgow city centre. It's a
collection of 8ft-high firs being chased shrieking ``keep your baubles to
yourself'', around the streets by two mad woodsmen clutching ferocious axes.
Imagine carrying your truncated tree and having that lot flee past you. It's
bound to cause a few pangs in the hearts of those who haven't been
environmentally conscious enough to purchase a living, potted tree.
The Nervous Forest is a typical example of the ``public subversion with a smile
on its face'' ethos of Ian Smith, the man behind the inspired lunacy of
performance group Mischief le Bas who have been popping up at various events
around Scotland, from outdoor festivals to nightclubs, for the past three years.
They've been entertaining Glaswegian shoppers since the end of November as part
of the city's Shine On Christmas festivities. The Nervous Forest is just one of
Smith's creations: each day three separate teams of Mischief le Bas performers
do a pick'n'mix of eight manifestations.
So, if you've stepped out of Marks'n'Sparks to be confronted by a gang of Elvis
lookalikes, industriously cleaning the streets, had to dodge past some
suspicious looking aliens, merrily doing their Christmas shopping or teetered
along the streets laden with purchases only to pass a group of ``Dizzy
Shoppers'' staggering under a more impressive 8ft-high pile of packages, now
you know what it's all about.
Glasgow streets have been echoing to the cries of ``Eh, what's that?'' as
Mischief le Bas have spread their very particular brand of merry mayhem. Three
slightly dim kings with two camels in tow have been meandering around town and,
while miserably failing in their task to find the nativity star, they did at
least manage to discover baby Jesus - ie, the replacement statue for the one
stolen from the manger in George Square by some particularly perverse thieves a
few weeks ago.
Some Snow Angels have also been drifting around, eagerly awaiting the
consignment of a case of rather splendid spray snow to Smith's long time
supplier, joke shop proprietor Tam Shepherd. ``Tam has assured me that this
spray shoots 24ft in the air,'' says Smith enthusiastically. ``Angels are
usually an image of hope and purity but ours are yobs.''
More civilised are a group of Van Goghs, who are colourfully togged out in
dungarees and straw hats and carry easels and sunflowers. They were originally
conceived by Smith as part of Mischief le Bas residency entertainment programme
for the Scottish Claymores, the American football team based at Murrayfield.
The Van Goghs showed up to make a visiting team from Amsterdam feel at home.
They speak with the standardised MTV presenter European accent which fits all
Mischief le Bas foreign incarnations such as the mayor and mayoress of
Luxembourg and the irascible tattoo-faced food-bearing Nomads. At Murrayfield
the Van Goghs mingled with the crowd, carved Edam cheeses and made occasional
frenetic dashes over the barricade on to the pitch, thus incurring the wrath of
the chief security inspector.
``He got most upset and told us to put the knives away, stop eating cheese and
stop jumping over the barricades,'' grins Smith. ``I kept shouting in our bad
Euro accent, `So sorry, ve do not understand, ve have only one ear' and he just
kept repeating the same thing, only more slowly and louder until I shouted `Eet
ees okay Meester, ve are from Dennistoun.' He went ballistic.''
Mischief le Bas's presence in the city centre has been stepped up from last
year's input to the Shine On festival. Then, they raced around dressed up as
stars and entertained people on the tube, building a ``rapport'' with the
underground staff which resulted in many severe tannoy messages instructing
them to stop lying down on the platform.
That kind of interaction is crucial to Smith's artistic vision. ``Every
manifestation we do interacts with the public,'' he points out. ``What works
for us is the humour in it, if it was too chi-chi then Glaswegians wouldn't
have it, they would think we were showing off.''
While many of the costumes can seem surreal they're certainly not as
off-putting as more pretentious street performers like the Peds, the cult of
black costumed faceless droids who wander the streets of New York and Los
Angeles. While the Peds stride silently, the Mischief le Bas group will
invariably be raucous and giggling.
``When people see us at first they can be a bit freaked out and think we're
weird, but then when, for example, a Dizzy Shopper turns and says `Oh, my feet
are killing me' it always gets a laugh. It's accessible though not puerile. I
mean it's not just people walking down the streets in funny costumes, there's
more to it than that.''
``Mischief le Bas are the best at what they do and have been getting a
fantastic reaction,'' says Neil Butler, artistic director of Shine On. ``No-one
else is doing what Ian is doing. Who else can you phone up and say I want some
camels on the street? I think the fact that it's a strange experience but
obviously so good humoured is essential to its success.
``Ian has an oblique angle of looking at things but you get what he's about.
He's great at dislocating people's sense of reality. The other good thing is
that he's working with lots of people, getting them involved in performing and
really enjoying themselves.''
Smith's ``mini industry of weirdness'' is composed of a growing band of friends
of friends, and only about 10% of those who take to the streets have had
previous performance experience. ``There are no rehearsals, just briefings when
the peformers are given a few catch phrases and a demeanour. They get a 65p
laundry bag containing their costumes which are designed by myself and Rachel
Mimiec, who has callouses on her fingers from running up camel costumes. I'm
always out there with them, keeping it all on beam, but there's a lot of
freedom.''
That element of spontaneity is essential to the effervescent energy of the
company. ``We're always trying out something new,'' says Smith. ``It's about
everyone getting jollies out of it.''
All the same, alongside the fun and hilarity, the mischief makers are prepared
to suffer for their art. Office hours weirdness is arduous work. ``We're
starting to suffer from physical fatigue,'' says Smith. ``We can even identify
certain aches and pains, such as Camel Back and Dizzy Shoppers' collar bone.''
Putting a shine on Glasgow sure requires plenty of elbow grease.
</TEXT>
