<HEADLINE>Warning on feed prices</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>farming digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782661</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIVESTOCK producers should brace themselves for a further rise in compound feed
prices, warns Chris Rackham, Bibby's director of raw materials.
The principal reason for the rise in raw material prices is increased demand
from Asian countries for feed materials and the disastrous US maize and cereal
harvests.
``Customers have been protected from the full impact of these price rises so
far,'' said Mr Rackham. ``However, it is impossible for compounders to absorb
the full cost of these increases as stocks of cheaper raw materials run out.
``Feed prices look set to rise by more than #20 a tonne as the full impact of
the most volatile and bullish market seen for several years is felt.''
Lean lamb
THE market for Scottish lamb in France will continue to grow, says leading
importer Claude Thieblemont. He warns, however, that overfat lamb is not
required at any price - and too many British lambs are failing to meet the
specification. He told an audience at Thainstone, Inverurie, that France was
only 47% self-sufficient in lamb, importing 165,000 tonnes a year to bridge the
gap.
Pig plan
PIG farmers should be alert to the need to plan ahead and keep their breeding
herd at full capacity, says Tim Bramley, North of England business development
manager with PIC. Postponement of replacement by one month on a typical 400-sow
farrow-to-finish unit could reduce annual output by 188 pigs a year, cutting
profit by #4500, he said.
</TEXT>
