<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Handcuffs for turbulent flights</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGinty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782664</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stephen McGinty reports how airlines around the world are cracking down on
rowdy or dangerous passengers - which can mean securing them to their seats
FEW airline passengers have fallen so low by flying so high. But the behaviour
of drunken British and Irish tourists on the Northwest Airlines flight to
America this week has brought the dangers facing cabin crews and passengers out
from behind a cloud of jurisdictional boundaries. One member of the party, made
up of three families, came down to earth with a bang.
Michael Purcell, aged 25, was remanded in custody in America on charges of
assaulting and intimidating a crew member and flight attendant.
The dangerous antics of the drunken group were only tamed when a team of
American Olympic wrestlers grappled with them and handcuffed them to their
seats.
This was only the most recent incident in a series of in-flight assaults which
has prompted British Airways to head a worldwide crackdown on drunken and
violent passengers.
These incidents include:
n September 1995, when a Uruguayan businessman was sentenced to 14 days in
prison for a drunken mid-air assault on a BA steward on a flight from Brazil to
Heathrow Airport.
n Northwest Airlines had a case earlier this year of a Washington talk-show
hostess assaulting a flight attendant who tried to stop her using a laptop
computer while landing.
n In 1994 an eight-year-old boy was indecently assaulted on an Air Canada
flight to London. A doctor molested an 11-year-old girl on a flight from
Minneapolis to Gatwick.
The increase in airborne anti-social behaviour has resulted in British Airways,
British Midland and other major airlines within the past year equipping cabin
crews with handcuffs.
The handcuffs are supplied by an English company called Quik Kuff, who also
provide staff training in the use of their equipment. British Airways began
training on this new restraint kit in May this year.
Previously, airline cabin crews were trained in methods of calming aggressive
passengers but they were not provided with such equipment. Now the use of
handcuffs is part of both initial and recurrent training for all cabin crews.
British Airways are reluctant to discuss such procedures, and a spokesman said
only: ``We have every confidence that our cabin crews can deal with any
incident and ensure the safety of the majority of passengers.''
In America, carrying handcuffs on board planes is mandatory under federal law.
Iain Burns, of American Airlines, said: ``It's simply to secure troublesome
passengers to their seats, and it is exceptionally pleasing to their fellow
passengers.''
Sarah Prew, editor of the newsletter Cabin Safety Update, available on
subscription to British cabin staff, said: ``Training in Britain on how to
restrain a passenger is not a recent introduction, but the actual kits are. The
cabin crew are trained how to protect themselves and use restraints.''
Ms Prew explained that such behaviour is usually a result of drunkenness but
other incidents have occurred among people with poor mental health and those
who have been deported, after their police minder has left the plane.
Ms Prew added: ``The decision to handcuff a passenger is made by the cabin crew
member who is dealing with the passenger at the time. The responsibility also
lies with the chief cabin crew member or services director who will be informed
and may try to talk the passenger out of his behaviour, as may the captain.''
The final decision on whether to turn back or land at the nearest airport is
made by the captain, and only when it has become apparent that the behaviour of
a passenger could compromise the safety and integrity of the aircraft and other
passengers.
Mr Chris Dark, general secretary of BALPA, the British Airline Pilots
Association, said: ``BALPA takes this very seriously because it's our members
who will have to take the decision to restrain a passenger. In the UK we have
got to emphasise that such behaviour is unacceptable in what is a very safe
form of transport.''
Jurisdiction in airspace remains a problem. It was decided at the recent
convention in Tokyo that responsibility for passenger offences should be taken
at the country of arrival. However, a number of nations refuse to allow a
troublesome passenger into the country.
``This forces the offender back on to the aircraft which is, of course, the
last thing we want,'' said Mr Dark. ``Alternatively, some countries have a
sin-bin, a locked room where drunken passengers can sober up before being
returned home.''
In the opinion of the Transport and General Workers Union, who represent cabin
crews, the problem of violent passengers is increasing. A spokesperson said:
``This is becoming an increasing problem for our cabin crew members. The
problem is that there are jurisdictional boundaries - who is responsible?
``Plus some companies are reluctant to pursue the matter for fear of losing
that person as a customer and also bringing on bad publicity. Even today a lot
of our cabin crew suffer sexual abuse and innuendoes.''
The union also highlighted the problems of consuming alcohol at altitude. At
45,000 feet the blood thins and any alcohol consumed will have a greater effect
than if consumed on the ground.
The ability of passengers to bring large bottles of spirits onboard has been
discussed, with some aviation bodies suggesting that the purchase of duty-free
be restricted until passengers return home. However, no such plans are in the
pipeline.
Asked if any aircraft has a padded cell in the cargo hold, Sarah Prew replied:
``Not yet!''
</TEXT>
