<HEADLINE>Lottery awards for heritage projects</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782665</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR heritage projects across Scotland benefited from funds raised by the
National Lottery when the Heritage Lottery Fund announced its sixth award of
grants yesterday.
The fund gave 34 awards throughout Britain for land, buildings, museums, and
galleries, with Scotland receiving #312,119 out of the #25m awarded.
In Perthshire, Historic Scotland was awarded #250,000 to help with the purchase
of Stanley Mills on the banks of the River Tay. The 18th century mill was one
of Scotland's pioneering group of water-powered cotton mills.
The first stage of the project will begin in the new year, and the fund has
indicated it may award further grants to help in the resoration of the mills.
The Shetland island of Fetlar received #20,619 towards the extension of the
Fetlar Interpretive Centre; a museum, visitor centre, and tourist information
point. The extension will provide additional display space for the museum's
collection, which includes photographs and film of folklore and local history.
In Argyll, the Strachur Smiddy Museum received #12,500 towards restoring an
18th century smiddy to its original state.
Stranraer Museum received #29,000 which will go towards an extension providing
additional gallery space as well as renovation of the facade of the museum,
which is housed in the Old Town Hall.
.q.The National Gallery in London has been given #8m from lottery funds to help
buy a painting by George Seurat, The Channel of Gravelines, from a German
collector.
</TEXT>
