<DOCNO>GH951221-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heseltine warns rebels on letting Labour in</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STUART TROTTER, Political Correspondent, and MURRAY RITCHIE, European Editor, from Brussels</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782666</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEPUTY Prime Minister Michael Heseltine challenged Tory rebels MPs who
contributed to the Government's defeat on European fisheries policy to realise
that they could end up installing the Labour Party in power.
It emerged that the Government could have won Tuesday night's vote, instead of
losing by two, if two Tory MPs had not made the mistake of thinking that voting
started at 10pm instead of 7pm and arrived three hours too late.
Their votes would have made it a tie, with the Speaker, Miss Betty Boothroyd,
procedurally bound to vote with the Government.
As Labour whips sought to track down MPs who missed the vote without
permission, the Tory whips' office refused to name the late arrivals, but the
two Tories were identified later as Sir Michael Spicer (South Worcestershire)
and Sir Michael Marshall (Arundel).
Mr Heseltine warned the rebels that they ``have got to face up to a very simple
question: are they trying to replace this Conservative Government with a Labour
government which will, in the simplest of their own terms, abandon all the
safeguards John Major has secured in Europe.''
In a BBC Radio interview, he suggested that local Tory parties should ask the
rebel MPs what they were up to.
Labour leader Tony Blair said yesterday: ``The Government is obviously in
disarray and the real problem is there's no sense of purpose or direction in
the Government any more. The sooner their misery is brought to an end, the
better for the country.''
In the Commons, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth, said the fishing talks
which open in Brussels today might go on until Christmas Eve as Fishing
Minister Tony Baldry fights to get a good settlement for Scottish and UK
fishermen.
However, Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said the Government had
lost the confidence of the nation as it had lost the confidence of the House of
Commons on fishing and should now call a General Election.
SNP leader Alex Salmond taunted Mr Forsyth for attending the last fisheries
council meeting ``playing second fiddle to the English fisheries Minister and
not saying a word.''
Meanwhile, it emerged that Tory Euro-sceptics will be rebuffed today in the
fisheries row when Ministers make clear Britain has no intention of abandoning
the European Union's common fisheries policy (CFP).
Three Ministers are due in Brussels to negotiate for Britain on annual totals
for fish catches and national quotas for next year against the background of
Opposition attacks and Tory Euro-sceptic criticism of British fishing policy.
A British official said yesterday that the Ministers would negotiate on the
basis of reaching a balance between scientifically-argued calls for cuts in
catches and the fishing industry's genuine needs.
After the Government defeat, officials are making it clear they will not give
in to rebel Tory demands for a unilateral abandonment of CFP.
The subject is unlikely to be raised at next year's inter-government conference
to review the Maastricht treaty. Britain has made no attempt so far to have
fisheries added to the already-agreed agenda which would be the only
opportunity to raise fishing policy in the EU.
Ministers take the view that to ditch the CFP, as demanded by Euro-sceptics and
some fishermen, would be impossible because such action would involve launching
complicated bilateral negotiations with all other EU member states.
The result would be to return privileged access to British inshore fisheries
for foreigners as existed when the UK had a 200-mile limit.
In short, Ministers believe the Euro-sceptics' demand for renouncing CFP and
restoring the 200-mile limit is nonsensical.
The UK negotiating team led by Mr Baldry also will include Scottish fisheries
Minister Raymond Robertson and Northern Ireland's Baroness Denton.
They will be negotiating proposals for major cuts in catches of
domestically-popular fish stocks in the North Sea including plaice and haddock
and slightly less dramatic reductions in catches in fishing grounds off the
west coast.
A British official sought to calm fishermen's doubts yesterday when he insisted
that British boats would not land fewer fish from the Irish Box which is due to
disappear on Hogmanay as a formally recognised conservation zone. The box
surrounds Ireland and includes rich fish resources to which the Spanish will
have new but limited access from next month.
An official said: ``The Spanish will have access to more waters but not to more
quotas. There will be no less fish for the UK and no more fish for Spain.''
Meanwhile, the Government will support Irish moves at today's council of
fisheries ministers in Brussels to debate the crisis in the fish farming
industry. Scotland has 5000 jobs dependent on fish farming and the Irish have
about 2000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government accused over cut in housing funds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782667</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOUSING groups and councils yesterday attacked the Government over major
cutbacks in housing expenditure in Scotland first revealed when the share-out
of the Scottish spending block was announced.
They were reacting to an upbeat Government statement on capital spending which
said local authorities should be able to invest about #350m in their council
housing next year and more than #1bn in the next three years.
Shelter Scotland said this actually meant a cut of #400m in direct investment
in housing over the period. It claimed that the size of the cutback was
equivalent to the cost of building 9000 new homes.
Of the allocations total, #240m is projected to come from capital receipts
mainly from council house sales, and the rest is consent to borrow. For the
first time, the Government has ordered councils to use 25% of the cash received
from receipts to repay their capital debt. The figure will rise to 50% the
following year.
Scottish Housing Minister Raymond Robertson said he believed the estimates were
both ``realistic and achievable.''
However, the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities claimed that the new
restriction over the use of capital receipts alone would cut the investment
available for housing by #300m over three years.
Cosla vice-president Councillor Keith Geddes said the new figures showed just
how severely the policy would affect council house building.
Shelter Scotland director Liz Nicholson said the announcement confirmed its
worst fears over the cutbacks. They would amount to 17% for next year and rise
to 38% by 1998-99.
``This is the most savage cut to the housing budget that Shelter can ever
remember. There will be no cheer for homeless and badly housed people this
Christmas'' she said.
However, the Minister insisted that ``substantial resources'' were being made
available for housing in view of this year's tough public spending round.
q.Mr Alan Ferguson, , director of the Chartered Institute of Housing in
Scotland, said: ``Adding to what many authorities have seen as unrealistic
dependence on receipts, the Scottish Office has told councils that 25% of the
receipts has to be used to offset their housing debt. This again limits
councils' ability to improve their stock.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Where is the catch in seizing initiative?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Smith</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782668</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Government's Private Finance Initiative promises much for hard-pressed
departments and the taxpayer. Ken Smith examines the implications
IF the Scottish Office were a house, then Secretary of State Michael Forsyth
would be the head of the household who has just been handed a credit card with
no financial limit, and told to go out and buy what he wants.
No need to save up the money, or to beg a loan from the bank manager, just hit
the shops and worry about the bills later.
That, in a simplistic sense, is the rationale behind the Government's Private
Finance Initiative. Roads, hospitals, sewage works, schools and colleges can
all be built without the Scottish Office paying. Private companies will design
the project, put the money up for it, run it for a set period of say 25 years,
and be paid back over the length of the contract.
The Government does not have to increase the Public Sector Borrowing
Requirement and, in theory, major projects can be brought forward. After all,
philosophically speaking, all finance is private. Whether the money to build a
road is borrowed by the road builder or the Government is of little concern to
the drivers using the road.
When the Treasury relaxed borrowing rules, allowing the PFI to progress,
Michael Forsyth was the Cabinet Minister above all who saw the rich
possibilities it held out. While the Government is keen to keep public spending
at a minimum the PFI allows projects to go ahead which might otherwise be held
back. Indeed, the Scottish Office will argue that it will allow projects to
proceed which would not have happened for years.
So Mr Forsyth seized the ``initiative'', as it were, enthusiastically. By March
1999 the Scottish Office plans #2.2 billion worth of projects financed in this
way, and the final total could be even higher. Only the departments of
Transport and Health have anything like the same amount planned.
But, as anyone with a new credit card in his or her hand should ask, what is
the catch?
Three major road projects in Scotland are planned with private finance. The
first will be the completion of turning the remainder of the A74 at the Border
into motorway. Kevin Delaney of the RAC has few reservations about PFI. In
general, the motoring organisation welcomes PFI, but would be concerned if the
Government simply used it as an excuse to reduce its own spending on roads.
``Financially, it's a lot better than the suggestion that motorists pay tolls
on private roads. Instead, the Government has taken up our suggestion of shadow
tolling, whereby the builders and operators of the roads are paid in ratio to
the numbers using the road,'' he said.
There are two worries among members of the employers' organisation, the CBI.
First that smaller Scottish companies will lose out as the financial backing
and expertise required will be too great for smaller outfits. The second is
that the PFI is so new that it will take some time before contracts are
awarded. That means a hiatus in major capital projects just at a time when
construction companies are desperate to win them in order to survive.
In essence, the contracts are so large - #100m for the A74 upgrade, #150m for a
new Royal Infirmary in Edinburgh and #115m for a new Law Hospital in
Lanarkshire - that what are called special-purpose companies will be set up to
operate them. There will usually be three partners: the construction company to
build it, a financial house to fund it, and an operator to service the building
or road during the length of the contract.
Michael Murphy, a partner in Glasgow-based solicitors MacRoberts, which is
involved in setting up such companies, said one difficulty which has to be
resolved is the future of the equity stake of the partners, particularly the
construction company.
If a special-purpose company is set up to deal with say a #100m project, about
#10m to #15m of equity would be expected. The construction company may put up
about a third of that. The difficulty would be if there is an insistence on the
construction company keeping its equity stake for the length of the contract.
The construction company would prefer to take out its equity once the project
is built and move it on to another Design, Build, Finance and Operate (DBFO)
scheme. Again, if too many such schemes crystallise at the same time then even
the largest construction companies would struggle to provide the necessary
equity.
Mr Murphy is confident, though, that such problems will be resolved. ``There
may be initial difficulties, but I suspect that in the near future we will be
looking back and saying that it's a good initiative and that it is generating
capital projects which are desperately needed.''
The Scottish TUC is less impressed. Assistant general secretary Richard Leonard
said: ``It's a bit like these signs that say `Buy Now and pay in March'. You
end up paying more in the long run. The Government can borrow more cheaply and
the companies will be wanting much bigger profit margins.
``It will also lead to priorities being determined by profit margins rather
than need.''
Nevertheless, if the teething problems are sorted out, there will be a rush of
much-needed capital projects by the end of the decade, and few people will
worry about the actual method of funding. Unless, that is, the major projects
are won by, say, French companies who have built up expertise in this area.
The day may come when the roadworks ahead in Scotland are marked with signs
stating: ``Attention Travaux.''
</TEXT>
