<HEADLINE>Fitting challenge for instructors</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782669</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A system of franchised courses for older people is planned in Dundee. ANN SHAW
describes the level of teaching ability needed
A NOVEL franchise running fitness classes for the elderly has just been
launched by fitness guru Dorothy Dobson. Her name is synonymous with keep-fit
for she was one of the first to pioneer exercise for older people - long before
the current health boom made it fashionable.
Way back in 1978 Dorothy started her first class at Dundee University for the
over-sixties, already recognising the important role that stamina and fitness
play in helping people to enjoy an active Third Age.
In 1992 Dundee named Dobson ``Citizen of the Year'' in recognition of her work
with the elderly. Aware from the start that many older people are worried about
what constitutes safe exercise, Dobson worked in close conjunction with the
university's medical experts.
Research by consultant geriatrician Dr Marion McMurdo at Dundee University
proves that regular exercise offers:
n Reduced risk of heart disease and strokes.
n Stronger muscles, and improving mobility.
n Improved balance, reducing the risk of falls.
n Reduced anxiety and depression.
n A maintained independence to a later age.
The demand for the Dorothy Dobson Over-60s Exercise Classes, based on gentle
exercise to music, proved so phenomenal that Dundee University are currently
running more than 20 classes.
Finally, they decided they could no longer continue to fund more classes and
they have decided to launch them on a franchise basis.
Like the university classes, the emphasis is on quality of instruction and
preference is given to those seeking a franchise who have a medical or
paramedical background, and are also trained fitness teachers.
Half of the profits from this joint venture between Dundee University and
private investors will be reinvested in the university's ongoing research into
ageing and health.
From a marketing point of view this is a growth area. Already 17% of the
population is over 65 and within 10 years this is expected to exceed 25%.
How might you expect to earn? That depends on how many classes you would run
every week. If you were to do four with an average attendance of 30, regarded
as the minimum, you could expect annual earnings of #3250 - hardly a fortune.
On the other hand if you have enrolled 100 per class then you could expect to
earn #11,650.
Energy, and commitment to the cause of fitness for the elderly are prime
requirements: the emphasis is on the quality of instruction rather than
providing a business opportunity for someone to make a quick buck out of a
growing market.
``What you have to remember,'' points out Dobson, ``is that you need to enrol
about 120 in order to get a regular number of 80-90 each week.''
The franchise itself costs #4700 and comes with a full package of support and
training, including a one-week course in Dundee, an ongoing music programme,
along with marketing and promotional help.
``We are not looking for perfection,'' says Dobson, but a class leader should
be fit and healthy and lead a healthy lifestyle. You will be dealing with a
membership of up to 300 people or more, so you must have some organisational
skills. You should also be capable of building the confidence of your members
to achieve their potential.''
What happens once you have completed your application form? Dobson says: ``You
will be invited to attend an initial meeting to assess your qualifications and
suitability for the job. Part of your assessment will involve a brief session
exercising to music.''
n Further information from DD Developments, 20 Whitehall Street, Dundee. Phone:
01382 201262.
</TEXT>
