<HEADLINE>Family mediation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782670</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Y
JENNIFER Cunningham's article highlights the difficulties experienced over the
festive season by the thousands of children whose parents have now separated
(December 18).
For many more families the stress caused by the extra layer of financial and
other concerns created at this time of year will be the final straw which
breaks the camel's back and causes family breakdown.
Large numbers of families will split up over the holiday period. Family law
solicitors will be consulted by these parents in the New Year and will try to
help sort things out.
While is is still necessary to have separate legal advice at some stages,
people can now choose to start the process of separation by going together to a
family law solicitor mediator who will help them work out the practical
difficulties of separating in a co-operative way.
Those difficulties can often be extremely complex and concern both the family's
finances and the arrangements for the children in the future.
Having a mediator who has a detailed and practical knowledge of the law can be
very important. Mediation has many advantages but those who stand to benefit
most are the children.
Clare I Craig,
Vice-Convener - CALM,
60 Bank Street,
Kilmarnock.
</TEXT>
