<HEADLINE>Getting the message (eventually)</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robbie Dinwoodie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782671</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Robbie Dinwoodie describes how one MP's week in politics has turned out to be
long and eventful
ONE RING and it answers - a strangled Dalek croaking out its death throes at
half-speed: ``The mess.......age....... unit....... is .......full.'' Mike
Watson's answering machine has melted under the heat of the Labour whips' wrath.
A week ago, the Glasgow Central MP at the centre of a selection battle with
opponent Mohammad Sarwar was anxiously expectant. Gradually, he became
fretfully confident as the contest reached its climax. Finally, he stood
victoriously depressed as he accepted a victory tainted by electoral
mud-slinging.
A week in politics is a very strange time, as Harold Wilson once almost
observed. Watson began last week as an MP fighting for his very livelihood and
ended it in victory - however narrow - over his adversary. But this is a
different week, and when he returns from his sojourn abroad which led him to
miss Tuesday night's three-line whip, he can expect the Labour Inquisition to
show him the instruments of torture.
Stretched out on the adjacent rack will be neighbouring MP Ian Davidson, chief
aide in the campaign to reselect the candidate. The fact that both MPs put
family holidays before the absolute demands of party managers who knew they had
a chance to damage the Government will inevitably lead to disciplinary action.
Although parliamentary group discipline is not connected to party procedures,
Watson still has to consider the national executive meeting next month which
will decide on an appeal for a re-run of the contest for the new Govan seat.
As one party insider put it yesterday: ``Last weekend, everything was going for
Mike. There was unease about the handling of the selection process, but the
feeling was that a sitting MP had won and he certainly had the support of his
fellow members of the Westminster club, especially since in the immediate
aftermath of the count Mohammad Sarwar and his supporters had gone over the top
in their condemnation.
``But since then Sarwar has gone out of his way to make conciliatory noises,
and now Mike has gone off abroad and missed a crucial vote. The boys in the
club are not pleased.''
How did it come to this? The answer is a combination of the clash between
individual exhaustion and collective discipline, coupled with the haywire
imperatives of one-member-one-vote. At the first of last week's three branch
meetings in the run-in to Thursday's count, only four people turned up to hear
the pleadings of the three candidates. Most preferred to vote by post, and it
was the verification of these votes - the checking of signatures - that led to
the hair's-breadth result.
New Labour will have to live with this new system of hands-off democracy which
gives power to individual party members but no longer requires them to sit
around at dull and lengthy meetings. It is a new machine, with new skills to
run it.
The machine of Old Labour would never have got itself in such a twist. For good
or ill, union power brokers would have sorted out a solution. A well-regarded
MP such as Watson whose seat was disappearing would have been found a new
billet, and an important entrant like Sarwar - with such a significant power
base in the Asian community - would have been found a seat from which someone
else was retiring, or was so persuaded.
This is very non-politically correct to say, of course, and entirely contrary
to the OMOV spirit which the late John Smith bequeathed to his New Labour
heirs. But it would have worked. Whoever accused the Conservatve Party of
internal democracy, after all?
Faced with this new reality the Parliamentary Labour Party gave generous leave
of absence from Westminster to Mike Watson to fight his battle, and Ian
Davidson to support him. The new guerrilla warfare of OMOV was an exhausting
fight, and both MPs marked their calendars in bold red pen for last Friday:
``ON HOLIDAY.''
Watson flew off with his wife for a weekend in Barcelona, returned to London on
Monday, and then flew off abroad again for a week on Tuesday morning. By then,
Davidson had flown off with his wife and two children for a holiday in Sri
Lanka.
They will have their own version of events to tell on their return but the word
from whips yesterday was that neither had sought prior permission, neither had
left a forwarding address or contact telephone number, and that although
Davidson had written to say he would be away on ``urgent business'' this week
both would be in trouble when they got back.
</TEXT>
