<DOCNO>GH951221-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Someone is shielding girl's murderer, says detective</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782672</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE yesterday urged anyone shielding the killer of 16-year-old schoolgirl
Mhairi Julyan to come forward.
The man leading the hunt, Detective Chief Inspector Bob Lauder, said: ``Someone
out there knows who is responsible for this. Someone has vital information and
that's who we want to speak to.''
The officer said that, although the response from the public had been very
good, no-one had been questioned.
Mhairi, a Kilmarnock Academy pupil, disappeared after a night out with friends
at the pantomime Sleeping Beauty in the town's Palace Theatre on Saturday.
On Sunday, her body was found in the Stagecoach bus depot close to her home in
Samson Avenue. Police said the sexually motivated attack was ``brutal and
savage''.
Young women in Kilmarnock admitted they were shocked at the possibility of a
killer being in their midst.
Teresa Le Masurier 19, a horticulturist, said: ``I'm from New Farm, which isn't
very far from the murder scene. It's scary when you think it happened so close
to home. London Road is a busy road, and you'd think somebody saw something.
``Now everybody's telling me to take a bus or a taxi but never walk home.''
Lesley-Anne Jardine 20, an auxiliary nurse from Kilmarnock, said: ``We don't
know if he will strike again. The poor lassie was only walking home. It could
have been anybody who did it.''
Her friend, sales assistant Gillian Falconer 20 added: ``I can't sleep at night
now. I'm even having nightmares about it, and that's never happened to me
before. We just don't feel safe anymore.''
Police have mounted extra patrols and have urged parents to find out where
their children are going at night.
</TEXT>
