<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bus routes to get priority</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782673</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOTHIAN region's transport committee yesterday approved parking restrictions to
enable speedier bus transport in Edinburgh. Red lines will denote no parking
whatsoever and green-coloured lanes will signify buses only.
If the Scottish Secretary approves the plan early next year, it could be in
operation by next September.
Fake notes alert
THE Bank of Scotland has warned of counterfeit #20 notes in circulation. The
fake Bank of Scotland notes are of poor quality and can be identified by
checking for a non-existent or faint security thread and an unclear watermark
or the numeral 20. The backs of the counterfeit notes are also blurred.
Drink move
CHIEF Superintendent David Mitchell told West Lothian District Council
yesterday that he would shortly recommend two town centres in the distict where
public drinking of alcohol should be banned to reduce nuisance and street crime.
Woman `stable'
AN 83-year-old Edinburgh woman is ``stable'' in hospital after being struck by
a wheel which broke from a trailer behind a Land Rover in Colinton Mains Drive.
Mrs Doris Brown, of Oxgangs, is Edinburgh Royal Infirmary with head injuries.
By the neck
FOR Men Only, a barber's shop in Stephen's Brae, Inverness, is serving up a
free bottle of beer with every haircut as a festive gesture to customers.
Holiday sale
A T Mays launched a #10m sale yesterday by taking up to 35% off the cost of
cruises and summer breaks. The travel agent has 96 branches in Scotland.
Vandal jailed
PATRICK Reid, 31, of Benula Road, Inverness, was jailed for five months at
Inverness Sheriff Court yesterday for smashing 110 windows on three coaches at
the ScotRail depot on Longman Road, Inverness, on November 26. The damage
amounted to #8000.
Batons on way
NORTHERN Constabulary's 600 officers will start training with US-style
side-handled batons in the new year. They will also be issued with easy to use
speedcuffs.
Hibs deal
LOTHIAN region yesterday agreed to sell to Hibs for #65,000 the former
technical block of Norton Park school, next to the club's ground in Albion
Place, Edinburgh. It will be used as club offices.
Delays ending
THE majority of the work to streamline Clydebank's Kilbowie roundabout on Great
Western Road will be over before the start of the Christmas break. Delays have
been caused for five months.
Canal upgrade
FOUR kilometres of towpath on the Forth and Clyde Canal between Clydebank and
Glasgow is being raised to a standard suitable for walking and cycling.
Clydebank District Council will contribute up to #13,000 to British Waterways
to help finance the work.
Body found
A PENSIONER who went missing two weeks ago has been found dead. The body of
Hugh McNab, 85, was found at Invergowrie, near Dundee. He had last been seen at
his home in the Menzieshill area of Dundee on December 7. There were no
suspicious circumstances.
220lb baby
AN Asian elephant has had a female calf weighing 220lb at Chester Zoo. Only one
Asian elephant has been successfully reared in the UK - also at Chester, in
1977 - and zoo staff are anxious to repeat their success.
Green for go
WORK on signalling systems at Haymarket railway station in Edinburgh is to go
ahead. It will cost between #3m and #4m, and is expected to improve punctuality
of arrivals at Waverley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
