<DOCNO>GH951221-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nicol favourite to lift British title</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782674</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Nicol, who missed the Scottish Championships last weekend, has been named
No.1 seed for the QM British National Championships in Birmingham from January
9 to 15.
The Inverurie man, who lost to Peter Marshall in the final two years ago, has
been placed ahead of England's world championship-winning trio of Del Harris,
Simon Parke, and Mark Chaloner.
Last week the world No.8 became the first Scot to win a Super Series event, the
Mahindra International in India, and he aims to be the first to win the British
title.
But Martin Heath, winner of the Scottish Championship last weekend, will not
compete in Birmingham, for which the draw will be made today. Heath complained:
``I don't agree with the Squash Rackets Association rankings. It is only the
English players who are automatically included, so I really regard it as an
English Closed event.''
Colchester's Harris is back at the top of the English rankings - for the first
time since March 1991. Harris takes over from Nottingham-based former world
No.2 Marshall, who had dominated the SRA rankings for four years but has had to
drop out of competition because of chronic fatigue syndrome.
Yorkshire's Simon Parke is No.2 and Lincolnshire's Mark Chaloner - the Sports
Writers' Association International newcomer - is third.
Norfolk's Cassie Jackman has displaced Suzanne Horner of Yorkshire at the top
of the women's list. Jackman, another former world junior champion, last held
first place two years ago but has been consistently topped by Horner since May
1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
