<DOCNO>GH951221-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peace without progress Diplomacy fails to keep pace in Northern Ireland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Leader</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782676</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE latest brutal murders in Northern Ireland are not directly involved in the
struggle between nationalists and loyalists. They do seem to have their origin
within the nationalist community all the same, and the pattern whereby its
leaders are simultaneously judge, jury, and executioner is familiar.
Indirectly, there is a message related to the political struggle - the murders
show how the IRA retains its ability to operate in a lethal manner with near
impunity. Curiously, neither the Dublin nor London governments had much to say
about these killings until yesterday when the murders were vigorously
condemned, just after the Unionst MP Ken Maginnis had drawn attention to the
official silence. Probably the timing was fortuitous but the fact is that the
established governments may be too deeply involved in the peace process to
react quickly to other challenges to civilised society.
The two governments are not making much progress in their efforts to establish
a lasting peace. Sometimes they are waylaid by minor matters, like the dispute
concerning EU subsidies to an Indian takeover of an Irish steelmaker. Sometimes
they merely go through the motions of diplomacy - like the summit meeting
scheduled for today - where nothing substantial can be achieved. Activity by
itself is not enough, and some activity even when positive is worth little. The
fact that the two governments got on well in their discussions with the
Alliance Party hardly matters, for it is the most reasonable of all Ulster's
political groupings. If liberal and democratic governments could not get on
well with Alliance representatives there would be no hope anywhere in Ireland.
Th
So far, so gloomy. The fact remains, however, that the political peace seems to
be holding into its second Christmas. The momentum for its continuance is
almost palpable. Could it prove irresistible? Just possibly the IRA will insist
on keeping its weapons but desist from using them. That is far from ideal but
it is better than a regression to the old ways. Obviously, the talks must go on
but any quick, neat resolution of years of conflict seems improbable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
