<DOCNO>GH951221-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Presbytery not railroaded</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782677</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOME of the correspondence concerning the Presbytery of Glasgow's treatment of
the Asylum Bill prompted by Stewart Lamont's somewhat inaccurate article
(December 16) implies that a small number of activists railroaded the
Presbytery into the decision that it made. Furthermore it is alleged that this
was pre-orchestrated and that the Presbytery Council knew nothing of it.
I would like to point out that Norman Shanks contacted me as convener of the
Presbytery's Community Responsibility Committee asking if he could make a
deliverance arguing against the withdrawal of benefits from asylum-seekers as
part of our report. This proposal I was happy to agree to after confirming with
the convener of the Presbytery Council that such a procedure would be
acceptable.
That it was not pre-orchestrated is shown by the fact that another speaker.
unaware of our intentions, made an essentially identical motion immediately
before our report was due to be delivered.
The terms of the motion and the implications of the motion were then placed
before Presbytery and discussion was invited. If Presbytery felt that it was
being railroaded or that it was not sufficiently informed of the facts to make
a decision then this was the time to complain - a number of us bear sufficient
bruises from previous verbal maulings to know that the members of Glasgow
Presbytery are not hesitant when it comes to making their views known .
However, a majority of Presbytery members were then happy to vote to accept the
terms of the motion and, if memory serves me right, only Mr Lamont actually
voted against.
This hardly smacks of railroading and would seem to imply common assent to an
issue that goes to the heart of concepts such as dealing justly and with
righteousness towards the sojourner in our midst.
In suggesting that a small cabal railroaded Presbytery into a decision which it
did not understand nor wished to make, Stewart Lamont does his fellow
presbyters a great disservice which he should attempt to put right as soon as
possible by accepting that on this, as on many other issues, it would seem that
his colleagues in Presbytery fully understand the issues and yet still choose
to disagree with him.
Rev Peter McEnhill,
16 Royal Terrace,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots racing track operators told to get together</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor, Parliamentary correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782678</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE operators of both the Forrestburn and Knockhill motor racing circuits were
urged yesterday to get together by Scottish Office Minister George Kynoch.
He was speaking in a Commons debate in which concerns were raised about the
threat to Knockhill in Fife from the new race track development at Forrestburn
in Monklands.
The issue was raised by Ms Rachel Squire (Dunfermline West - Lab.), who argued
that if Forrestburn succeeded, it could put Knockhill out of business.
The plan at Forrestburn is to produce a 3.2 mile international lay-out designed
to attract Formula 2 and Formula 3 race driving - with Formula 1 a possibility
in the long term.
Pointing out that #1.4m of EU money would be used in the Forrestburn project,
Ms Squire said only a limited number of events were large enough to attract
crowds big enough to make the business viable.
She called for full consultation with experts around the UK on whether there
was sufficient business available to support two racetracks within such a short
distance of each other before further progress was made on Forrestburn.
She voiced fears that ``public money will have been used to build up false
hopes in Lanarkshire and ruin a successful private enterprise business in Fife,
which I believe could damage the sporting reputation of Scotland.''
For the Government, however, Mr Kynoch said the two tracks were looking at
essentially different markets, and suggested that they could be complementary
projects rather than one being seen in competition with the other.
He said he understood Ms Squire's reservations, but said that she should get in
touch with organisations supporting the Forrestburn development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Raider who liked to inspire terror is jailed for 27 years</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782679</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A THIEF known as Lucifer was jailed for 27 years yesterday after a campaign of
terror that police said had spanned 10 years and made him #1m.
Powerfully built Keith Bramble, 36, had boasted he was protected by Satan and
could never be caught. His 6ft 4in frame swayed in the dock in a Middlesex
court and he had to grip the rail as he received the longest jail term ever
passed for domestic break-ins.
Judge Derek Clarkson, who retires today, told Bramble that he preyed on the
wealthy and vulnerable, and had enjoyed frightening his victims.
``Inspiring terror seems to have had an appeal to Keith Bramble,'' the judge
said. ``This defendant gloried in the effect that he could produce. It was, as
well as the prospect of enrichment, part of the attraction.''.
Judge Clarkson said that too many courts these days looked ``with a certain
intellectual detachment'' on crimes committed in Britain without taking into
account the effect on the victims.
``The public expect and they are right to expect judges to take into account
the effect of crimes of this sort on people who are attacked in their own
dwellings, where they should feel always at ease and secure.
``I take the view that these crimes do merit severe punishment. They are wicked
and callous crimes against people in their own homes and the punishment must
act as a deterrent.''
He invoked sentencing powers available under the Criminal Justice Act to impose
a jail term 50% longer than he would otherwise have passed.
The judge told Bramble he would serve concurrent terms of 21, 22, and 27 years
on the three robberies of which he was convicted at Guildhall Crown Court, and
serve an additional six months, also concurrent, for assaulting a prison
officer with intent to resist arrest.
He sentenced Anthony Gabbidon, 31, who accompanied Bramble on the last and most
serious raid, to 16 years.
Bramble used the cover of dark and stormy nights to target homes in up-market
areas.
He would be masked, and invariably armed himself with an array of weapons,
including crowbars and knives.
Detective Inspector John Shatford, who led the hunt, said after the hearing
that Bramble liked his victims to be in so he could ``relish their fear'' and
feed his addiction for inflicting ``maximum terror''.
``He carried out a campaign of unmitigated terror but many people can rest
easier in their own homes now that he is out of circulation.
``That sentence will do more to prevent similar offences than anything else the
police could do.''
Bramble stole fortunes in cash and jewellery and spent much of it on crack
cocaine, surrounding himself women whom he treated like slaves.
In court, Mr Shatford told the judge of the effect Bramble had had on his
victims.
``They will never recover from it. I have spoken to them all and they are
totally devastated,'' he said.
One of those in the packed public gallery during the sentencing hearing was
fashion firm chairman William Angel, 69, whose house was the last Bramble
raided.
Mr Angel said: ``The judge summed it up by saying that not a lot of thought was
given to the victims. Courts just don't realise the terror we have been through.
``When we go out at night we are petrified. We are worried 24 hours a day.''
Mr Angel, who tried to use a table to defend himself and his wife and his aged
brother-in-law when Bramble burst in, said that during the struggle with his
attacker he managed to pull off his mask.
``I keep on seeing that face over and over in my mind. That face will always
stay with me.
``There was an expression of absolute fury on his face but at the same time
panic. Being unmasked really unnerved him.''
Jailers later spoke of Bramble being in a ``zombie-like state'' after the
sentence. One said: ``He was so stunned he couldn't speak. But during the trial
he was full of bravado and had convinced himself he was going to get off.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
