<TEXT>
DEVOLUTION and abolishing the undemocratic archaic House of Lords has been
promised by the Labour Party since Keir Hardie's election address of 1888, and
has never been delivered.
Keeping in mind that the present New Labour Party is unquestionably the least
radical in its history how, in the name of Scotland, can anyone believe its
present ambiguous ``commitment'' to a so-called Scottish parliament?
Devolution is something which must be granted as a privilege by Westminster; it
is not a right, and may be given or taken away. As such it has very limited
use, except to appease Scottish political aspirations and preserve Labour's
vote in Scotland.
Decisions on issues such as taxation, nuclear waste, defence, unemployment
benefit, and the economy would still be taken by Westminster. Devolution would
amount only to an extra tier of local government called a Scottish parliament.
Labour's Jack Straw boasts that ``power devolved is power retained''. Obviously
Labour's priority is not devolving real power to Scotland but preserving it at
Westminster. Scotland mustn't confuse appeasement and treachery with power.
Lachlan MacColl,
Flat 7/4 Crown Avenue,
Inverness.
</TEXT>
