<HEADLINE>A remedy for those who have the bottle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782681</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
It's party time and with it comes the dangers of over-indulgence. Ann Shaw has
some timely advice for anyone falling foul of the demon drink
SCOTS botanist Duncan Napier put together a cure for over-indulgence in 1860: a
mixture of bitter yellow Peruvian bark, pulverised cloves, crushed cinnamon and
a large pinch of sulphuric acid in a weak mixture of alcohol and warm water.
This gruesome concoction, which sold well in Edinburgh, was one of many
traditional remedies which medical herbalist Dee Atkinson discovered when she
took over Napier's Dispensary, the oldest herbal house in Britain, a few years
ago.
Happily, today more palatable cures are offered for hangovers. The most popular
in Scotland, according to one young Glaswegian is ``Irn Bru and a fry up.''
The search for the perfect ``morning after'' cure is something as old as man's
ability to brew beer, distil spirits and ferment grape juices.
The aim behind all hangover cures is to boost the liver, to help it metabolise
the alcohol. Drinking water helps with the rehydration of the body, but you
need more than that.
A boost with some multi-vitamin and mineral supplements is needed. An extra
gram of      vitamin C, before and after a night out, helps. Eating lots of
fresh fruit and drinking orange juice is one of the simplest and most effective
ways of helping to cure the condition, says Atkinson.
Take your pick from alternative health remedies. One that comes highly
recommended is an extra vitamin B complex supplement plus six evening primrose
oil capsules with a glass of water and a small piece of dry wholemeal bread.
This combination, if taken an hour before a drinking session, is believed to be
good at preventing hangovers.
On the other hand, many people simply reach for a couple of paracetamol and a
glass of water. As good a cure as any, says one doctor.
There are some simple precautions that can be taken: eat a meal before drinking
to delay absorption of alcohol; alternate alcoholic drinks with mineral water
or fruit juice; try herbal tea rather than coffee as the morning-after caffeine
merely stimulates a hangover; and drink lots of water to replace the fluids
lost by the dehydrating effects of alcohol.
Or again there is another popular, remedy: stay in bed. Some people swear by
the ulcer drug Zantac, which apparently cures hangovers quickly.
A point to remember: rum, port, red wine, whisky, and brandy generally produce
more serious hangovers than vodka, gin and white wine.
Don't forget that alcohol can have a very different effect on people of the
same height and weight. Some people seem to have a natural ability to clear
alcohol out of the system faster than others.
Regular drinkers are less likely to suffer hangovers since their body has built
up a tolerance. Those most at risk of severe hangovers are the      people who
really only let themselves go at Christmas and New Year.
The bad news for women is that the female liver is less alcohol tolerant to
start with. Hormonal levels also seem to affect metabolism with some women
finding they can consume more at certain times of the month, according to their
menstrual cycle.
Finally, a word of warning from one doctor for those considering some short,
sharp, shock treatment for the body: it is dangerous to indulge in vigorous
exercise if you have still got alcohol in the bloodstream and you are
dehydrated.
The bottom line, of course, is not to drink. On the other hand, when
non-drinkers get up in the morning bright-eyed and bushy-tailed, that's as good
as they'll feel all day.
HOW TO CURE
IT NATURALLY
n THOSE looking for something novel to cure a hangover should try either of
these herbal remedies: Hangover Hotch Potch Bitters or Swedish Bittes.
Dee Atkinson says: ``We do a roaring trade in Hangover Hotch Potch Bitters.
This is a tongue-tingling mixture of dandelion roots, milk thistle seeds and
gentiana compound.'' (Available from Napier's in Edinburgh and Glasgow price
#1.95, also on mail order.)
Swedish Bittes is popular with continentals. It is a herbal elixir based on
bitter herbs which have traditionally played an important role in maintaining
food health and overall wellbeing.
This 11-herb mixture contains manna, aloe, senna leaves, rhubarb root, zedoary
root, angelica root, theriraca (blended mix), carline thistle root, myrrh,
camphor, and saffron. Available from all good health shops for #6.99.
Brew that is true after
a flagon of the dragon
A SURVEY carried out in The Herald office revealed that the most popular cure
for a hangover is Irn-Bru.
Billy Connolly even dedicated a song to it in remembrance of hangovers cured.
It has to be remembered that Irn Bru is a piece of Scots folklore. This fizzy
orange liquid is not just a drink. It is an icon - as much a part of Scotland
as tartan or heather - which is believed to possess magical restorative and
medicinal powers.
A hard man can walk into a Gorbals bar and ask for a bottle of Bru without
anyone turning a hair. But there is no medical evidence that Irn Bru solves a
hangover better than any other fluid. Yes, it helps with rehydration but so
does sweet tea, and that's cheaper.
You would be better off, says medical herbalist Dee Atkinson, eating lots of
fresh fruit and drinking orange juice, for the benefit of vitamin C, and to
boost your liquid intake.
Every nation has its tried-and-tested treatments:
The French favour a small coffee with salt.
The Germans believe in a magnesium-rich breakfast - bananas and red meat washed
down with milk.
The Swiss reach for the O-Pur: a can of neat oxygen which gives 10 minutes'
supply and comes with a disposable face mask.
The Japanese drink gallons of green tea, while the Chinese boil banana skin and
drink the liquid.
Russians believe a bottle of vodka is the answer, often mixed with rassol, the
juice left after pickling salted cabbage.
Icelanders go for the time-honoured cure of a large glass of cider vinegar and
honey.
The Americans go for the prairie oyster: a raw egg, tomato juice, and hot
pepper sauce, mixed and drunk in a oner.
Or there is the Californian ethos: ``Stop pouring poison into your body. Honour
it as a temple with abstinence.'' Californian doctors have also developed a
drug, Naltrexone, which removes the pleasurable effects of drinking, leaving
the drinker with only the hangover.
The answer for Italians is simply a very large cafe espresso, brewed fortissimo.
A REALLY RUDE
AWAKENING
n-``HIS mouth had been used as a latrine by some small creature of the night,
and then as its mausoleum. During the night, too, he'd somehow been on a
cross-country run and then been expertly beaten up by secret police.''
- Kingsley Amis's definition of a hangover in Lucky Jim.
n-HANGOVER: Roget's Thesaurus definition: ``Crapulence, crapulousness;
next-morning feeling, sottishness, beeriness, leaving you feeling squiffy,
tight, lushy, soused, soaked, pickled, blotto, drunk as a lord, stinko.
n-FOR a bad hangover, take the juice of two quarts of whiskey.
- Eddie Condon.
n-I'D take a bromo, but I can't stand the noise.
- Joe E.Lewis.
EXPERTS PUT IT TO THE TEST
TESTS carried out by Which? magazine found that commercial hangover remedies
should relieve symptoms but two paracetamol and a glass of water will do the
job more cheaply.
A panel of experts analysed five products which are designed to treat a
combined headache and upset stomach.
n.Beecham Resolve (contains paracetamol, citric acid, sodium bicarbonate
potassium bicarbonate, sodium carbonate, vitamin C) Cost: #2.95 for pack of 10.
``Vitamin C won't tackle hangover symptoms and you should get enough from a
healthy diet to make the amount in Resolve an unnecessary addition.''
n.Alka Seltzer (aspirin, citric acid, sodium bicarbonate). Cost: #2.99 for pack
of 30.
``The combination of sodium bicarbonate and citric acid partly protects the
stomach from attack by aspirin, but most of our experts preferred products
containing paracetamol.''
n.Boots Headache and Indigestion Relief (paracetamol, caffeine, citric acid,
sodium bicarbonate, sodium carbonate) Cost: #1.59 for 200mml.
``Contains only half as much caffeine as Answer, so is even less likely to give
you a lift.''
n.Superdrug Paracetamol Seltzer (paracetamol, sodium bicarbonate) Cost: #1.55
for 24 tablets.
``Contains the important ingredients and costs much less per dose than the
others.''
The magazine summed up its findings. ``You may find that remedies which combine
a painkiller and antacid are convenient to take and that those with sweeteners
(all but Alka Seltzer) are more palatable. But our experts reckon that taking
plenty of liquid and two paracetamol will work just as well and cost much
less.''
A number of home remedies were also considered by the panel with varying
results.
While evening primrose oil could work in theory, the panel thought it unlikely
to have an effect. A fried breakfast may work for some people but it is one of
the worst things to have on a delicate stomach.
Prairie oyster - raw egg, lemon juice, pepper and spicy sauce - has a
reputation for effectiveness but the panel could find no explanation for this.
Dioralyte, a treatment for severe dehydration, will combat some of the effects
but at 40p a dose it is expensive, compared with plain water.
The panel was clear on one of the worst things a hungover drinker can do -
treat the symptoms with more alcohol. Although the ``hair of the dog'' may help
the symptoms temporarily it could be the slippery slope to alcoholism.
</TEXT>
