<HEADLINE>Office deal makes true rental value</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Stewart McIntosh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<FLAG>Features commercial industrial property</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782682</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN Glasgow's biggest office deal for several years, 250 St Vincent Street has
changed hands for #10.25m. The building has been purchased by BBC Pension Trust
Ltd from Scottish Widows at a price which reflects a net initial yield of 7.1%.
The building was completely redeveloped in 1990 behind a retained facade by
Burton Property Trust, creating 44,000 sq.ft of open-plan space. Scottish
Widows purchased the redeveloped property in 1991 for some #8.25m, achieving a
#2m uplift in value over the past four years. The property is let to Norwich
Union at an initial rental of #755,000 per annum on a 25-year lease. The BBC
Pension Trust has been active in the Glasgow market, having recently sold the
office investment at 225 Bath Street to a subsidiary of the Royal Bank of
Scotland in a #7.75m deal.
Scottish Widows was represented by Hillier Parker and the purchaser by Knight
Frank &amp; Rutley. ``This is the largest and most significant office transaction
to take place in Glasgow over the past few years,'' says Peter Smolka of
Hillier Parker. ``Investment funds are engaged in a flight to quality. The rent
at 250 St Vincent Street is close to the building's true rental value and it
has an excellent tenant with an unexpired 20 years left on the lease. The deal
is a strong indication of renewed investor confidence in the city.''
He is optimistic that the blip in investment activity which boosted the Glasgow
market a couple of years ago might be repeated in 1996.
``There won't be an avalanche of investment deals, but I think we'll see a
steady flow. A lot of big investors have Glasgow on their hit list - but they
are extremely picky about which buildings they will purchase, only the best
will do. There would be more deals done in Glasgow if there were more quality
buildings available on the market, but landlords are tending to hold on to
their best stock.''
However, he is concerned about Glasgow's planning policy which pushes for city
centre redevelopments to be carried out behind retained facades, wherever
possible. ``There is a growing reluctance among the big investors to purchase
this kind of building. This is an important planning issue which Glasgow needs
to face up to,'' he says.
</TEXT>
