<HEADLINE>Robinson Crusoe, His Majesty's, Aberdeen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<FLAG>Review</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782683</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERHAPS it is the feet and the way they don't like being seen walking together.
Or the way the knees seemed to concertina with the responsibility of pointing
forward all the time - the way they shoogle and buckle and shimmy sideways to
avoid whatever lies straight ahead.
Gerard Kelly has got pure dead glaikit legs. They are currently supporting him
in Robinson Crusoe, along with a stalwart cast who all seem to share a real
affection for the particular quirks of old-fashioned panto.
From the moment the lights dim, tradition asserts itself: Blackheart the Pirate
(Derek Lord with a deep, dark swaggering voice to match his deep, dark
swaggering vices) crossing rhyming couplets with the ethereal spirit of the
Northern Star (Mairi McHaffie).
There's booty at stake. A vital map, a desert island, treasure - all needing to
be found by someone more deserving than Blackheart. Enter penniless Captain
Cockle, his lovely daughter and her fearless beau, Robinson Crusoe
(enthusiastically played by Briony McRoberts temporarily deserting the High
Road for the high seas).
The plot takes in such perennial favourites as the shipwreck, the underwater
kingdom, a desert island full of hotsy-totsy dancing cannibals and a Friday
(Cornell John) who spouts elegant Shakespeare unless we shut him up!
James Horne's Dame is properly garish and coos like a foghorn but it's Kelly's
Silly Billy that wins hearts and powers the comedy. ``Am I the man for the
job?'' he beseeches us. ``You are. You are!'' we roar back lovingly. ``If the
job is keeping panto alive for another generation, that's certainly true,''
said Ofpants, the official panto watchdog. ``Kelly leads by a mile and two daft
feet.''
</TEXT>
