<HEADLINE>Row over Scots education plans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor, Parliamentary correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782684</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BLABOUR and the Tories were involved in angry exchanges yesterday over the
state of Scottish education.
The plan for nursery vouchers, the assisted places scheme and the student loans
system all came under fire from Labour during Scottish Question Time in the
Commons.
Mrs Maria Fyfe (Glasgow Maryhill - Lab.) referred to the recent announcement
that the Government's plan for privatising student loans had been delayed for a
year, which means it will not be brought in before October 1997, well after the
last possible date for the next General Election.
She asked Scottish Education Minister Raymond Robertson how he would
``extricate himself from this shambles,'' but Mr Robertson insisted the student
loans scheme was working well.''
From the Labour Front Bench, Mrs Helen Liddell renewed her attack on the
proposals for nursery vouchers.
Mr Robertson, who clashed with Mrs Liddell on Tuesday over the assisted places
scheme, told her: ``Over the recess you should be looking at what you have been
saying from the Front Bench because sometimes your comments have been
absolutely shameful.''
</TEXT>
