<HEADLINE>Royal SNO Christmas Concert, Royal Concert Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<FLAG>Review</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782685</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALL'S well that Bell's well. Putting Irish conductor Christopher Bell in charge
of a musical occasion with a strong social element - where the conductor has to
communicate with the audience, whether it's kids or grown-ups out for a night
on the town - is an increasingly clever thing to do.
Bell has not only a natural gift of the gab, he is completely from another
planet (in the best sense). In 13 years of working on this page, and in
thousands of concerts covered, no other conductor would have dared to invite an
audience to come along to a New Year concert and ``throw up over everyone''.
In attempting (successfully) to get the audience at last night's RSNO Christmas
Concert to sing along, he hurled good-natured abuse at the huge crowd,
referring to the ``ancient Celtic singing'' that was going on, that the sound
of the mob suggested to him that there were some Russians out there, and
referred to the women's singing as ``hormonally challenged'', with an
exhortation to the ladies to ``hoist yerselves up''.
Knockabout stuff, lapped up by the crowd, though the coup de grace was getting
us all to do a ``crossover Mexican wave, with some double thrusting by the
chaps in the middle''. All of which had almost nothing to do with the musical
content of the show, though everything to do with the atmosphere.
In and around all the nonsense, there was congregational choral singing, Dave
Anderson - as droll as a bassoon - narrating Brother Heinrich's Christmas, and
the RSNO adult and junior choruses in shining fettle for a series of seasonal
items.
</TEXT>
