<HEADLINE>A festive gesture giving little away</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<FLAG>Features</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782686</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILLIAM RUSSELL heralds the satellite arrival of the classics they couldn't kill
BRITAIN's television viewers have seen nothing like it before. Will they wish
to see anything like it again? Bravo, the satellite channel, is to screen on
Monday nights at 10pm over the next two months the best, if there is such a
thing, of the films made by New York's famous Troma studios.
They are being shown after 10 because, as even the studio's boss and leading
director, Lloyd Kaufman, with 42 films in 22 years, admits Troma films are not
family viewing. ``I don't think teeny children should be watching them,
although otherwise they are fun,'' he says.
Troma specialises in not so much low-budget as no-budget movies. Kaufman
believes it is a mould-breaking organisation which has led the way where
Hollywood has been afraid to go, although it has duly followed. Big names who
started at Troma include Robert de Niro, Oliver Stone and Kevin Costner.
The films in the season will be the directors' cuts, says Kaufman, and include
such famous titles as Stuff Stephanie in the Incinerator, Surf Nazis Must Die
and A Nymphoid Barbarian in Dinosaur Hell. This latter was one example of where
Troma pre-dated Hollywood and showed Steven Spielberg a thing or two, claims
Kaufman.
``We were unable to afford his animatronic computerised dinosaurs, but our
creatures are very good,'' he said. ``We hatched them ourselves from original
eggs in Troma's damp New York basement. The story is about a deadly, horny
dinosaur who pursues the last woman alive on earth. She is a sexy, little
blonde and the dinosaur gets lucky, no doubt about it.''
Kaufman says that women in Troma films were always strong. They had to be. And
it was Troma policy not to be sexist so they did not use the word women, but
called them Gyno-Americans. Not only were they strong and courageous, but they
wore very small costumes. Indeed, very small costumes was a Troma speciality.
It saved money.
IT is not just available in video stores or on Bravo. It is also on the
Internet, and Lloyd said he got sacks of fan mail from all over the world, many
from persons of the sex opposite to his own. Feminists loved Troma.
I asked what his current project was, and he said he was busy making Tromeo and
Juliet, having visited Stratford upon Avon recently and been entered by the
spirit of Shakespeare. He declined to say how.
The greatest Troma star is the Toxic Avenger, known familiarly as Toxie, a
green-faced mutant who has featured in several adventures in which he cleans up
the world. Lloyd said Toxie was extending his range and would be joining the
Three Tenors Tour next year, having just been signed up by Harvey Goldsmith,
although whether Toxie would sing or just clean up after the famous three Lloyd
did not say. The original Toxic Avenger film is Bravo's Christmas Day treat,
while the sequel goes out at New Year.
He hoped the British public, which was being exposed for the first time to
Troma, would like what he had to offer, although being ``only a poor artiste''
he had no idea whether it would. Then he promised to send me a copy of his
masterpiece, Chopper Chicks, which stars several Gyno-Americans in very small
costumes, for Christmas. When I thanked him he made clear he had said lend, not
send. Lloyd gives nothing away.
</TEXT>
