<HEADLINE>Scrimping to survive on a state pension</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Johnstone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974782687</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Anne Johnstone examines a report which exposes the misery of old folk trying to
live on meagre incomes
`THERE are some days when I think, why do I have to do this when I've worked
all my life and reared a family of 10 children? There's just no end to it. I'm
constantly robbing Peter to pay Paul.'' The speaker is Kathy Bell and she's
wondering why, at the age of 74, she's still having to go out to work to make
ends meet.
Kathy is one of the pensioners whose ``spending diary'' is featured in a report
out yesterday from Age Concern. Just About Coping doesn't pretend to be a
scientific study, bristling with shocking statistics. The size of the sample
(32) is far too small for that. Rather, it brings those statistics to life,
lifting the lid on the misery of life for many pensioners in Britain today.
If, as some suggest, you can judge a country by the way it treats its old folk,
Britain doesn't appear to come off very well. This report paints a sad picture
of tired old people who always choose the cheapest brand, rarely eat out and
can't afford to buy clothes.
More than a third of the sample said they had difficulty staying out of the red
and half appeared to have a weekly deficit. ``Often, it's a one-off item such
as a repair bill that knocks them for six,'' says Jane Titley, Age Concern's
campaigns manager and author of the report. She says that rather than borrow,
older people fall back on their savings and when these are exhausted, they
start cutting essentials like fuel and food.
Asked how they would spend the money if they had another #10 a week, almost all
said it would go on basics: food, clothing, heating. Most said they never took
holidays. Half said they spent nothing on clothes.
Though much is made of old people's access to free prescriptions, a third of
those in this survey reckoned that long-standing health conditions such as
arthritis, osteoporosis, angina and high blood pressure, cost them money. Such
expenditure includes fares for travel to and from hospital appointments and
medication not covered by prescription.
One lone pensioner told how she needed to buy antiseptic after falling and
cutting herself outside. It cost #1.49. She could only afford it by buying less
food that week.
All those participating in the survey were asked to keep a ``diary'' listing
income and expenditure each week, and complete a detailed questionnaire about
their longer-term spending and income. The diaries leave an impression of old
people scrimping and saving and always on the trail of special offers and the
cheapest of everything.
One man, who lived a long way from shops, made a meticulous list before each
week's shopping trip, detailing each item he needed and the exact cost, then
juggling the items until he could get it to fit his meagre income.
The survey is part of Age Concern's 1995 Short Change campaign for a decent
level of income for all pensioners. Its findings closely reflect those of a
similar exercise conducted among Scottish pensioners two years ago.
The Government is fond of telling us how well pensioners have fared under the
Conservatives. For example, Peter Lilley, then Social Security Secretary,
stated in 1993 that pensioners' ``average'' net incomes have increased by 54%
since 1979.
Sally West of Age Concern says such statements are misleading: ``If only
average figures are considered, the picture is skewed by the richest fifth or
so of pensioners who have enjoyed much higher increases. There is a clear trend
showing the lower the income, the smaller the percentage increases.'' In fact,
after the deduction of housing costs the poorest fifth of pensioners were just
2% better off in 1989 compared with a decade earlier.
Many pensioners are worse off in real terms because of the introduction of
charges for services which used to be free, and increases in indirect taxation.
All age groups have to squeeze their belts at times. The difference between
most old people and most of the rest of us is that we generally look forward to
at least modest pay rises. Because state benefits are uprated annually on the
basis of the retail price index, rather than average earnings, many old people
will never see their earnings rise, and life is a constant struggle.
</TEXT>
