<HEADLINE>Scots employers more Scrooges than Santas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782688</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH workers are less happy with their lot than other UK employees,
according to two surveys published today by Proudfoot management consultants
and the MSF trade union.
Some 59% of Scottish workers describe their boss as a Scrooge rather than a
Santa according to Proudfoot's study, which shows 55% as the UK average. They
also have more complaints about pay levels (60% as opposed to a 45% average),
poor promotion opportunities (49% against a 25% average), and being expected to
work too hard (46% against 34%).
The Manufacturing Science and Finance survey shows that 92% of Scottish
employees feel the jobs in their workplace are no more secure than last
Christmas, while 46% believe they are less secure.
These figures for Scotland are higher than the UK averages, which are given as
85% and 43% respectively, but considerably short of the gloom emanating from
London (94% and 61%), Northern Ireland (100% and 67%), and Wales (100% and 73%).
The MSF study also indicates a worsening of treatment of employees by their
bosses and that stress at work is escalating. A total 20% complained of
worsening treatment compared with three months ago, while 42% described the
treatment in their workplace as ``very poor'', with the biggest complaints
coming from the financial services sector, where 58% said their treatment was
poor or very poor.
Apart from job security, pay continues to be the main issue of workplace
concern, along with worries about pressure of work and increased stress. Stress
is a particular concern in financial services, the voluntary sector, and the
NHS.
Commenting on the survey, which covers 366 private and public sector workplaces
employing 118,000 staff, MSF general secretary Roger Lyons said: ``People are
going into the Christmas period not knowing if they will have a job in the new
year.
``Tax cuts have not changed a thing and people have no confidence in John Major
and his beleaguered Government. The best Christmas present he could give us is
a General Election.
``Ebenezer Scrooge remains the number one role model for Britain's bosses,'' he
added.
Proudfoot chief executive Malcolm Hughes said his company had wanted to take a
light-hearted look at how employees evaluate their bosses, but the survey had
raised some serious issues which managers should seek to address in the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
