<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shah shakes A team</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782689</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND A's hopes of completing a clean sweep in the one-day series against
Pakistan - and finishing the tour unbeaten - were dashed by 21-year-old fast
bowler Sajid Shah in Sheikhupura yesterday.
The right-armer, playing his first match of the series, took six for 43 as
England A were dismissed for just 115 in reply to Pakistan A's 40-over score of
248 for five for a crushing 133-run defeat. But England A won the Test series
1-0 and the one-day internationals 2-1.
The tone had been set by opener Sajid Ali, who plays for Poloc in the Western
Union and has represented Pakistan in 10 one-day internationals. He scored 38
from 34 balls, with seven 4s and a 6, out of the total of 53 when he became the
second victim of Sussex paceman Ed Giddins. Test men Shakil Ahmed (69 off 83
balls, with two 6s) and Asif Mujtaba (62 off 82, with one 6) then had a stand
of 118 runs off 126 balls.
Shah then ripped through England's top order, capturing half their wickets to
reduce them to 59 for five. The main resistance came from Kent paceman Dean
Headley, with two 6s in an unbeaten 26.
SCORES: Pakistan A 248-5 (Shakil Ahmed 69, Asif Mujtaba 62); England A 115
(Sajid Shah 6-43). Pakistan A won by 133 runs.
q PAKISTAN thrashed New Zealand by 54 runs in a one-day match in Wellington
yesterday to take a 2-1 lead in the four-match series.
Aamir Sohail (58), Inzamam-ul-Haq (54), Ijaz Ahmed (42), and Akram, whose 36
not out off just 15 balls included two 6s and three 4s, helped Pakistan pile on
261 for four. In reply, Craig Spearman scored a quickfire 33, but Pakistan
captain and man-of-the-match Wasim Akram removed him and Bryan Young in
successive balls.
There was brief resistance from Stephen Fleming (35), Roger Twose (37), and Lee
Germon (40) but New Zealand were all out for 207.
SCORES:: Pakistan 261-4 (Aamir Sohail 58, Inzamam-ul-Haq 54); New Zealand 207.
</TEXT>
