<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Signal for shambles Rail privatisation forges ahead</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Leader</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782690</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHUNTED by ideology and fired by a desperate sort of determination, rail
privatisation is pushing ahead. We may not like it, believing that there was
little wrong with the nationalised service except a deliberate lack of state
investment, but the privatisation process now resembles nothing so much as the
headlong rush to introduce the poll tax. Just as the general public could
hardly believe that anything as wrong-headed as the poll tax would be pressed
upon them, there is a feeling abroad that rail privatisation is so generally
unpopular that it could not possibly happen. Would that it were so. The simple
fact is that, although the Government cannot meet its latest target of
privatising just over half of the system by April of next year, there is every
likelihood that the bulk of the railways will be in private hands by the time
of the next election. The only caveat to that is that Mr Major and his
colleagues may fall by the trackside before 1997, but those who are appalled at
the prospect of a privatised rail system should not rely on such an outcome.
The Government's determination is personified by Sir George Young, previously
the mildest of men, who appears to have developed a privatising zeal for
anything that moves on rails. His plans, and the requirements for services set
down by the franchising director, Mr Salmon, were soundly rebuffed recently by
the Appeal Court judges in London who decided that the minimum service levels
set by Mr Salmon were too low and in contravention of Government guidelines.
This has not troubled Sir George; he has merely altered the guidelines and
allowed the first three privatisations to go ahead. We can learn a good deal
from these commercial agreements; the first point is that the Labour Party's
attempts to deter private investors from involving themselves in franchise
holders by the threat of taking the privatised services back into public
ownership under a Labour Government appears to have failed. This is suggested
by the appearance of the important venture capital company 3i in two of the
first three franchises. Other potential investors who may have hesitated will
be heartened by the involvement of 3i and may be more willing to emulate them.
The plans set out by the management-employee buy-out teams who were yesterday
awarded the Great Western franchise and the London, Tilbury and Southend line
(LTS), better known as ``the misery line'', tell us other things. The Great
Western company will receive public support of #53.2m in the first year of
operation, falling to #38.2m in the year 2003. Depending on how you assess the
figures, it can be argued that there was no public subsidy to British Rail on
the routes in 1993-4. Other interesting facts include the admission by the
heads of both Great Western and LTS that jobs will be cut and that a varying
amount of fares (in the case of Great Western only 25%) are protected by the
fare-capping system. Stagecoach, which has been awarded the franchise for South
West Trains, provides other interesting facts. Although the company has no
plans to raise fares or reduce services, neither does it have plans to buy new
rolling stock. With a seven-year franchise this is, perhaps, understandable,
but Stagecoach's development plans appear to focus largely on linking their bus
services into the new privatised rail network. Is that really what all this
upheaval has been about?
The privatisation of the rail network is no more palatable to the general
public than the poll tax; that much appears certain. Unfortunately this holds
no weight with the Government which stands alone as an enthusiastic proponent
of the scheme. It is important to remember, as the arguments rage back and
forth, that there was an alternative to the present shambles. That was to
finance properly what was already an excellent rail service and, moreover, one
which was integrated because it was held in the hands of the state. It is
wrong, of course, to have a closed mind on the subject. It is possible that
some of the privatised services may improve on the previous system, but as all
private schemes require a greater return on capital than public schemes, we
await with interest news of the added, and inevitable, cost burden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
