<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kingussie lie in wait for Skye</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MacLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782691</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SKYE Camanachd could not have drawn a shorter straw than their first match of
1996 after the festive break.
The island side, who play in north division one, suffered a heavy defeat at the
hands of all-conquering Kingussie in a recent MacAulay Cup tie. They have now
have been scheduled to meet the premier league side again in their MacTavish
Cup tie which was postponed a fortnight ago.
Skye should be thereabouts when the play-off for the right to go up to the
premier league takes place between the champions from divisions one in the
north and south.
Duncan Cameron, president of the Camanachd Association, has been pleased with a
very successful second part to 1995. He said: ``We have to be delighted with
the way things have gone so far, especially coming off the back of such a great
Camanachd Cup final at the end of last season, and the international
performances against Ireland.
``I now look forward to building on that success in 1996 and the implementation
of our development plan is now the key to our future, with our first ever
full-time administrative officer in place and due to make up his new duties
formally at New Year.''
No premier-league matches have been scheduled for January 6, but Fort William
and Newtonmore cross camans in an all-premier MacAulay Cup tie at the Eilan.
The first-round draw for the top competition, the Glenmorangie Camanachd Cup,
will take place on January 16.
With that, and the Centennial final at the end of the season, there is still a
lot of shinty to come, Cameron's view is that 1996 should produce a fitting
climax to the historic first season of the premier league.
</TEXT>
