<DOCNO>GH951221-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sky's the limit for television demands Football in danger of selling the pass</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>James Traynor, Chief sports writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782692</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUGBY League has been quick to deny reports that Rupert Murdoch's News
Corporation were given the power to veto player movements in rugby league's
Super League which begins next March, but their protestations will not ease
fears that sport is running short on morality. The sports we love appear to
know no bounds in their willingness to prostitute themselves.
Football is not immune. Indeed, some fear that the game, which accepts hundreds
of millions from satellite television, could come under assault from the money
men who will make greater demands far beyond those which have tinkered with
kick-off times and days on which matches are played.
Even though Rugby League's chief executive, Maurice Lindsay, was protesting
that his sport has not sold control to Murdoch's people, you don't have to be a
cynic to believe sport is heading in the wrong direction. There is no doubt the
hand of satellite television is tightening around sport and Jim Farry, chief
executive of the SFA, said last night: ``I am worried about sport's dependency
culture on media moguls. I see difficult times ahead.''
Another of the most influential players in the Scottish game, Rangers owner
David Murray, feels football's autonomy eventually will come under increasing
threat by television companies. ``Easy targets have already been identified and
picked off,'' he said. ``Television is already calling the shots and Sky
appears to be taking over. I don't see any danger to us at the moment, but we
might not be able to say that in the future.''
Some time in the not-to-distant future there will be a ridiculous number of
channels available to viewers - at a cost, of course - and it is thought Sky
are negotiating with the top clubs in England with a view to offering each of
them their own channels.
Sky Television have paid #87m to create the Super League and reports claimed
that players had signed ``loyalty'' agreements with News Corporation. Such
deals would have allowed the media people the final say in any transfer deals.
``It is nonsense to suggest we have given up control of our sport or any part
of it,'' said Lindsay. ``Claims that the loyalty agreements signed between
players and News Corporation require the players to play wherever News
Corporation say are both unfair and irresponsible.''
He did admit that voluntary loyalty agreements had been signed by players, but
that these will benefit players, clubs, and fans.
Nevertheless, with the advent of satellite television it was inevitable sport
would be corrupted. The process of change has taken another, some might say
sinister, turn with rugby league's agreements and, as Sky's slogan says, there
is no turning back.
Those in football who fear the influence of television companies will recoil in
horror that players in another sport have signed agreements not to play for
teams in a rival rugby league - the Super League is in competiton with
Australian Rugby League - and although they were saying such a distasteful
scenario could never befall the people's game, everyone and everything has a
price. Satellite television is paying hundreds of millions into football on
both sides of the Border.
The more football becomes dependent on satellite television's money, the less
likely the sport is to hold out against new demands. Football is already close
to the point where the money from television companies is greater than gate
receipts and that is a perilous position for any sport.
The day football's administrators first held out their hands and accepted
millions for live coverage of their product was the day some of us realised the
game was up. It all seemed to be happening too quickly and it appeared that not
enough thought was being applied, because people were bewitched by the amounts
offered. The consequences were not properly considered.
It was in the mid-80s that Scottish football accepted around #12m from Sky for
live broadcasting rights and there must always be a price. Sky, who have the
rights to live FA Premier League action because #304m was paid in 1992 - the
rights to the Endsleigh League have just been bought for #125m - are clearly
determined to have it all.
Next time football will receive an even greater sum but their own cost could be
higher. Satellite companies are not throwing money at football because they are
benefactors; they have their own motives and they will ask for more in return.
``It's Citizen Kane gone crazy,'' was the reaction of Leeds United's manager
Howard Wilkinson in The Independent, which carried reports of rugby league's
sell-out. ``Sport has to maintain its independence if it is to maintain its
integrity,'' he added.
Farry does not feel Scottish football is in any immediate danger of being
brought to heel by a television company, but the SFA are like King Canute in
the modern day. While the English authorities have sold their game to live
television, the SFA continue to impose strict restrictions, with Farry pointing
out: ``We are one of the last bastions in that we feel football's interests
should always come first.''
How much longer football will be able to hold out before television people
start interfering with the fundamentals remains to be seen, but the signs are
ominous. There is something to be feared in having media companies tailor an
entire sport to its own needs. Football must resist. The price of failure does
not bear thinking about.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
