<DOCNO>GH951221-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Submarine deal sparks criticism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782694</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEC LOOKED poised last night to win a crucial #2500m submarine contract as the
Government came under fire for ``smuggling out'' the announcement days before
Christmas.
Defence Ministry officials confirmed that GEC-Marconi had been selected as
preferred bidder for up to five of a new class of nuclear-powered submarines.
The decision could prove a damaging blow to Britain's sole submarine
manufacturer, VSEL, and have serious ramifications for the future make-up of
the British warship industry. GEC owns both VSEL and Yarrow shipbuilders on the
Clyde.
Both GEC and VSEL submitted bids to build the submarines a week after GEC
defeated British Aerospace to buy VSEL, based at Barrow-in-Furness, Cumbria.
This produced a curious battle with a parent company competing against a
subsidiary.
Defence officials were astonished to read the respective bids - and discover
GEC bidding with a much more creative design at significantly less cost.
News of the decision leaked out when Labour's John Hutton (Barrow and Furness)
raised a point of order in the Commons.
Mr Hutton said: ``Involvement in this contract is absolutely essential for the
future of VSEL and for the jobs of thousands of my constituents.
``The Government's decision today will, at the very least, create unwelcome
uncertainty about the future of VSEL, where nearly 10,000 jobs have already
been lost.''
An MoD official said the GEC tender offered the best value for money and best
matched the technical compliance requirements.
Negotiations would now begin with a view to awarding the contract late next
year.
Although VSEL is the only British yard capable of producing an entire submarine
from design to launch, GEC proposed a novel solution.
It argued that individual sections - hoops - could be manufactured in different
parts of the country, then brought together at a yard such as VSEL for final
assembly.
The system has been used in Sweden for constructing conventionally-powered
submarines for some years.
It is expected that GEC will carry out final assembly work on the submarines at
VSEL.
However, the majority of the work will be carried out at different sites around
the country and the impact on the VSEL yard could be significant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turning their back on sunshine trip</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782695</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JIM Park, the national coach, is disappointed that less than half the Scottish
squad have accepted invitations to a training camp in Florida in February.
A fortnight in the Fort Lauderdale sun may seem an attractive proposition, but
only four of the 10-strong squad, Alison Sheppard and Forbes Dunlop, from
Milngavie and Bearsden, and Stirling University pair, Kerry Martin and Pauline
McLean, will be on the plane on February 5.
The Scottish Amateur Swimming Association arranged the trip on the basis that
it would provide an ideal training opportunity in the final build-up to the
Olympic trials in Sheffield at the end of March.
``It is a great chance for the swimmers to get away from home pressures and
focus on training, and I would certainly have liked more swimmers to accept,''
said Park. ``Some have complained that it is too close to the Olympic trials,
but I don't agree.
``It is disappointing, but we do want to stay flexible and the association will
be providing funding for those who have made alternative arrangements.''
That category includes Richard Hope and younger sister, Kirsty, who will join
Milngavie and Bearsden's Sheppard, Jamie McNeil, Tom Griffith, and Douglas
Forrest on a club trip to Arizona a week today, and Arbroath's Cameron Black,
who also is going to the US next week.
But Commonwealth Games medallist Fraser Walker is one Scot who has decided on a
stay-at-home policy. The 22-year-old has been training with Warrington this
season, and he explained: ``I went to Lanzarote with the Scottish squad last
year and came home ill. I can't afford that to happen again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sympathy for the sitting MP</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782696</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM sure many readers will view with abhorrence the dispute about the
selection of a prospective Labour candidate for Govan.
I am bound to say my sympathies are with Mike Watson. After all he is a sitting
MP whose seat in Glasgow Central has been squeezed out by the reduction in the
number of Glasgow parliamentary constituencies.
He has been an excellent MP and it would be unfair if his parliamentary career
were to be cut short while he is still a relatively young man.
I am all in favour of ethnic minorities being represented at Westminster but
not at the expense of sitting MPs. Mr Sarwar should have waited until a
suitable seat became available.
The Labour Party is free of racism. In Glasgow as elsewhere the party has gone
out of its way to avoid the accusation of racism in its selection of
candidates. The full-time officers of the Labour Party in Scotland supervised
the count in Govan in accordance with the party rules.
Mr Sarwar has the right to query the selection of Mike Watson and appeal to the
National Executive committee. Doubtless he willl avail himself of this right
but it does not help having George Galloway, MP for Hillhead, taking sides. He
should have kept out of the controversy.
Bill Hattan,
Tanera,
Strachur, Argyll.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aces on top of the world</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782697</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TENNIS
PETE Sampras and Steffi Graf have been named world champions by the
International Tennis Federation.
This is the third time Sampras has won the award, while Graf was named for the
sixth time in the past nine years.
Sampras won Wimbledon and the US Open, each for the third time, and was
runner-up in the Australian Open. He won three other tournaments and led the
USA to victory in the Davis Cup.
Graf won the three Grand Slam tournaments she entered: the French, Wimbledon,
and US Open. She also won the season-ending WTA Tour Championship and suffered
only two defeats during the year.
``Pete Sampras and Steffi Graf have played exceptional tennis, especially at
the majors,'' said ITF president Brian Tobin. ``They fully deserve to be
recognised again as the best of the best.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rugby league</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974782698</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORWARD Tony Hilton has been fined an undisclosed sum by Rochdale Hornets after
being banned for three months by the Rugby Football League.
Rochdale have also warned him about his future conduct after he tested positive
for Ephedrine - found in cough and cold remedies - following last month's game
against Featherstone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Christian warriors and public anxieties</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782699</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IS there any particular reason why Christian churchmen choose to go to war, at
least in the pages of the press, during what they claim is a season of
universal goodwill? Two years ago it was the Virgin Birth controversy, now it
is the question of asylum and immigration.
I suspect that most people are willing to accept that asylum should be offered
to those in genuine need but all sorts of tales are currently circulating in
Central Scotland about illegal economic immigration and it is this, real or
imagined, that causes anxiety.
When spokesmen for the Muslim Parliament declare our system of democracy
corrupt and redundant and, in effect, set up a state within a state obedient
only to Islamic Law, anxieties increase.
To people who are worried, Andrew McLellan's words (``I want Britain to be
proud, strong, principled, brave, free, and generous'') may sound a little bit
like King Vortigern addressing some timorous subjects who want Hengist and
Horsa sent packing (December 18).
I feel that this whole matter cannot be clearly and properly discussed because
of various shades of political correctness as well as fear and suspicion of
``the alien in our midst''. If we could address our moral and economic problems
more effectively, perhaps such anxieties would diminish.
It does seem rich, however, that the descendants of the Dalriads, who boast
today that they are scattered over the face of the earth to the effect that
there are more people of Scots descent out of Scotland than in it, should make
such a fuss about immigration and the threat to their way of life.
Geo S Neil Mochrie,
16 Heugh Street, Falkirk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>To start the whisky trail in London</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782700</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS interested to read the letter, The whisky trail in London (December 14).
Certainly it would seem that the British Tourist Authority is biased in favour
of English tourism. However, as many tourists intending to visit Scotland will
enter the UK at London Airport, they could do worse than start the whisky trail
in London.
Some of the London shops stock a wide range of malts and some years ago when I
lived in London I sometimes found rare malts more easy to obtain in London than
in Scotland.
Although whisky is not made in London now, some was in the nineteenth century.
According to Barnard (1887), the Lea Valley Distillery, Stratford, London, made
305,000 gallons of grain whisky, and 155,000 gallons of malt whisky, annually.
However, the distillery closed down in 1902. For some years the buildings were
occupied by paint manufacturers but they were demolished some years ago.
In Barnard's time there were also whisky distilleries in Bristol and Liverpool.
At that time, the English whisky could be blended with Scottish whiskies and
the blend sold as Scotch. Now, a whisky could not be described as Scotch if it
contained any English spirit.
John S Davidson,
Crosslaw,
Ballplay Road,
Moffat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951221-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951221-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951221</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dead wood among policy makers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974782701</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO THERE is now a rebellion threatened by the clubs as they sense the whiff of
a major upset. Ah yes, if ever there was a time for the clubs to be the SRU,
and the reverse, then this is it. What a great deal of political back-watching
we are about to see.
It's not the staff, it's some of the wallies on the various committees that
perplex the Diary. Urgent and drastic streamlining is needed for an accountable
SRU.
You see, it's not the Bill Hoggs of this world who are the problem, it's the
rather obvious queue of unemployable nitwits who would quite fancy Bill Hogg's
post itself if they could ever oust the man from his seat. Whether they could
or not is open to question, but it would be a big mistake.
Just like the Tory government, the SRU has to divide itself between
``operational'' and ``policy'' matters. No-one is slagging off the operational
side too much. It's the policy tossers that need sorted out. There are some
good guys, no doubt. But only the SRU would look to some of the dead wood
that's there for advice.
Frankly, it's embarrassing.
q Glasgow's rugby clubs are examining their individual agendas over the coming
weeks to see what lies ahead for the city, and the Diary understands that Andy
Little, GHK's director of rugby, is penning a paper for the club on how he sees
the future at Old Anniesland.
``It's deep-thought time,'' says Brian Simmers at Glasgow Accies. ``We spoke
with GHK two years ago, but it was decided then that amalgamation was not the
way ahead, which is why we got Kevin Greene. That's the way it still stands and
I am happy at that.
``All the clubs need to have a clear idea of where they want to go.''
The Diary understands that talks among the Glasgow clubs are imminent. Many of
the clubs in the city are ambitious, and with the advent of eight-team leagues,
the need for at least one team in the top division is paramount.
q WHEN Glasgow played Connaught at the weekend, two of the Glasgow committee
were invited to preview the match by taking part in a discussion on the local
radio station with the Connaught coach and captain.
``Tell me, Tom,'' said the Irish interviewer to Tom Morrice, one of our brave
Glasgow chappies. ``What style of rugby do you play now?''
``Oh,'' replied our flustered hero, perhaps unsure of the rigours of live
broadcasting, ``I haven't played rugby for a while. I gave the game up years
ago.''
Muffled laughter all round.
q HEARD at a mini rugby game as uttered last weekend by an anxious mother
standing on the touchlines, her side having just made an error of dazzling
proportions - ``Come on, Dalziel, catch a grip of yourselves.''
The next mistake was severely punished. ``Come on, Dalziel,'' said the mother.
``You're as bad as . . . Strathaven.'' We must now see the Strathaven mini
rugby team in action.
q THE Diary can reveal exclusively that a club touch-rugby competition is to
come to Glasgow this summer for those that are interested.
It's worth noting that the Edinburgh clubs took part last summer and Glasgow's
did not. Various venues are being examined, and the City of Glasgow is to get
involved in the shape and form of Ken McEwan and some dosh.
q THERE I was walking along Great Western Road on Tuesday, when an enormous
great big Jaguar stopped and rolled down its window.
Seated within were Jimmy Martin and Bill Dunlop of GHK. ``What are you doing
out?'' asked Martin, the GHK president. ``I thought you were dead.''
When he said ``thought'' I think he meant hoped. Nice friends.
