<HEADLINE>Zero tolerance does not apply</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>Correspondence</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974782702</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OU carried two articles on teachers (December 15) . One on the gratifying
clearing of Mr Thomas McGhee over false accusations of assaulting his pupils,
the other commenting on the brave actions of teachers in the horrific
Middlesborough stabbings.
Your reports, obviously, made no links; please allow me to do so. I would
suggest that most of us in the teaching profession are the caring and dedicated
people typified by the Middlesborough three and the recently murdered Head, Mr
Lawrence.
However, this is not currently widely recognised or reported. We are those who
regularly ``fail'' our pupils if politicians are to be believed. We are those
used as party political footballs subject to the throwaway comment.
For example, the normally laudable Mr Blair, Leader of the Labour Party,
recently said that when he comes to power there will be zero tolerance of
failure.
I realise that like any other human beings teachers are prone to failure at
times. However, Mr Blair's zero tolerance phrase is borrowed from another place.
Does he really see teachers in the same category as drunken men who regularly
and systematically beat their womenfolk to a pulp?
We live in a day of trumpeted pupil and parental rights. Don't teachers have
feelings and rights, too? It's surely time to give credit where it's due and to
redress a clear imbalance.
Frank Murray,
7 Netherwood Grove,
Cumbernauld.
</TEXT>
